<BODY>
<HEADLINE> AP Top News at Midnight EDT  </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
 Friday, May 12, 2000
</P>
<SUBHEAD>
New Mexico Fire Still Rages
</SUBHEAD>
<P>
   LOS ALAMOS, N.M. (AP) -- Although blowtorch winds and searing heat that fed a
raging Los Alamos wildfire broke Friday, the fire remained out of control in the
nearby forests and canyons, and residents were told they could not return to
their houses for at least a week. The fire, which began with a
government-prescribed burn to clear brush, damaged the town's nuclear weapons
laboratory and forced 25,000 people to flee. The weapon lab appeared out of
danger today, and all of the facility's major buildings were unscathed, said
Richard Burick, deputy lab director for operations.
</P>
<SUBHEAD>
Midwest Storms Kill Two, Injure Dozens
</SUBHEAD>
<P>
   DUNKERTON, Iowa (AP) -- A quickly moving storm spawned tornadoes, high winds
and baseball-sized hail from Texas to Michigan Friday, killing one person in
Texas and injuring at least two dozen others. A 4-year-old Kansas girl died
earlier in the day in aftermath of a tornado. One person died in Hill County,
about 60 miles south of Dallas, when a twister touched down Friday evening, said
Cpl. Charlie Morgan with the Texas Department of Public Safety. The storm ripped
roofs off houses and flipped mobile homes as the storm moved through. In St.
Nazianz, Wis., straight-line wind gusts up to 110 mph and baseball-size hail
caused heavy damage to a mobile home park Friday night, where several people
were injured.
</P>
<SUBHEAD>
Indian woman crowned Miss Universe 2000
</SUBHEAD>
<P>
   NICOSIA, Cyprus (AP) -- A 21-year-old model from India who said beauty
pageants give women a platform to ''voice our choices and opinions'' was named
Miss Universe early Saturday. Lara Dutta succeeded Mpule Kwelagobe of Botswana
to become the 49th winner of the pageant and the first Miss Universe of the new
millennium. Claudia Morena, 22, of Venezuela was second and Helen Lindes, 18 of
Spain was third. Dutta, who holds a master's degree in communications, won out
over 78 other contestants.
</P>
<SUBHEAD>
Ethiopia, Eritrea Fighting Again
</SUBHEAD>
<P>
   ADDIS ABABA, Ethiopia (AP) -- Ignoring international pleas to end their
two-year border conflict, Ethiopia and Eritrea returned to open war on Friday
with fighting reported on three fronts. U.N. Secretary-General Kofi Annan
predicted ''a very brutal war,'' and expressed frustration that peace efforts
had failed. The two sides issued contradictory statements on the details of the
fighting, but both agreed that war had erupted once again along the 620-mile
frontier, which contains a now-evacuated stretch of fertile land of great value
in this drought-wracked region of Africa. The U.N. Security Council demanded the
two countries immediately stop fighting and hinted at a possible arms embargo if
Africa's newest war doesn't dissipate over the weekend.
</P>
<SUBHEAD>
Clinton, Bush Offering Gun Ideas
</SUBHEAD>
<P>
   WASHINGTON (AP) -- President Clinton Friday announced grants to develop
''smart gun'' technology while Gov. George W. Bush said he will distribute free
trigger locks in Texas. Filling out the election-year debate, Vice President Al
Gore acknowledged that he often voted with the National Rifle Association during
his early years in Congress, but they have parted ways. Bush and Gore sat down
for interviews on morning television shows, raising their voices on one of the
most volatile issues of the presidential campaign season. Recent polls show
voters split between Gore and Bush on whom they trust on gun policies.
</P>
<SUBHEAD>
Even Cheap Drugs May Not Aid Africa
</SUBHEAD>
<P>
   JOHANNESBURG, South Africa (AP) -- A plan by pharmaceutical companies to
reduce sharply the price of AIDS drugs was greeted Friday as a sign of progress
-- but one that will have little impact on most of those infected. Five major
drug companies announced in Geneva on Thursday they would work with governments
in Africa and other poor regions to cut the overall costs of HIV/AIDS drugs by a
reported 70 to 85 percent. However, few countries in sub-Saharan Africa, where
70 percent of the world's 33.6 million HIV-infected people live, have the
resources to provide any large-scale programs to their infected populations.
</P>
<SUBHEAD>
Dow Ends Up 63; Nasdaq Gains 29
</SUBHEAD>
<P>
   NEW YORK (AP) -- Stocks rose Friday after the report of a decline in
wholesale prices in April helped quell worries about rising interest rates. The
Dow Jones industrial average ended up 63.40 points at 10,609.37. On the NYSE,
gainers led losers 1,604-1,330. The Nasdaq rose 29.48 to 3,529.06. For the week,
the Dow lost a total of 31.51 points and the Nasdaq lost 287.78.
</P>
<SUBHEAD>
Heat Defeat Knicks 77-76 in OT
</SUBHEAD>
<P>
   NEW YORK (AP) -- Anthony Carter's incredible shot from behind the backboard
-- which didn't count until an offensive goaltending call was waved off -- gave
the Miami Heat a 77-76 overtime victory over the New York Knicks on Friday
night. In a strange finish to a one of the better Knicks-Heat playoff games
ever, the fickle bounce of the ball and a rare reversal of a referee's call gave
the Heat a 2-1 lead in the best-of-seven series.
</P>
<SUBHEAD>
AP NewsBrief by RICHARD A. SOMMA
</SUBHEAD>
</TEXT>
