<DATE_TIME> 2000-05-13 00:47 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Duckpin Bowlers Ponder Decline  </HEADLINE>
By DAVID DISHNEAU
<TEXT>
<P>
   HAGERSTOWN, Md. (AP) -- Duckpin bowling, with its shrunken pins
and balls, has always been about smallness.
</P>
<P>
   Devotees feel it is shrinking even more -- in popularity.
</P>
<P>
   ''We have to get into the 20th century and get a Web page and
explain to people more about duckpin bowling,'' Chuck Lavin,
executive director of the National Duckpin Bowling Congress, said
Friday as the group opened its annual meeting.
</P>
<P>
   According to Lavin, the game was born a century ago in Baltimore
and popularized along the East Coast by two Baltimore Orioles
baseball players, John McGraw and Wilbert Robinson, who owned a
bowling alley.
</P>
<P>
   They thought the squat pins -- two-thirds as tall as conventional
bowling pins -- flew around like ducks when struck, Lavin said.
</P>
<P>
   The sport peaked around 1950 with more than 300 duckpin alleys
from Massachusetts to North Carolina, according to Lavin and
bowling consultant Stacy Karten, publisher of Duckpin News in
Owings Mills.
</P>
<P>
   Today, just 80 bowling centers offer duckpins, mainly in
Connecticut, Maryland, Rhode Island, Virginia and West Virginia,
they said.
</P>
<P>
   Lavin said the number of leagues sanctioned by the
Baltimore-based duckpin congress has dwindled to 500 from 1,500 a
decade ago.
</P>
<P>
   The game's appeal is obvious to anyone who has ever picked up a
conventional tenpin ball, weighing 10 to 16 pounds. Duckpin balls
are about half as big and weigh less than four pounds. They have no
finger holes.
</P>
<P>
   Duckpin bowlers get three balls per frame -- one more than in
tenpins -- but that doesn't make it easier to score. No one has ever
bowled a perfect, 300-point game in duckpins, Lavin said.
</P>
<P>
   ''I think duckpins is the game it is because it's a challenge,''
he said. ''You don't throw the ball down and get a strike every
time.''
</P>
<P>
   The last U.S. manufacturer of duckpin machines, Maryland-based
Sherman Pinsetter Co., disappeared decades ago, Karten said. As
duckpin alleys closed, their machines were bought by foreign
operators, mainly in the Philippines and Argentina, he said.
</P>
<P>
   U.S. operators have turned to late-night laser bowling and
organized duckpin youth leagues in hopes of rekindling interest in
the game.
</P>
<P>
   ''We're in a lull right now,'' Lavin said. ''But we're
optimistic.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER> AP-NY-05-13-00 0047 </TRAILER>
