<DATE_TIME> 2000-05-13 00:47 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Legionnaires' Survivors Reflect  </HEADLINE>
By MIKE CORDER
<TEXT>
<P>
   MELBOURNE, Australia (AP) -- Ingrid Rigby decided not to take her
4-year-old son, Anthony, to Melbourne's popular new aquarium last
month. There would be too many people, too long a wait to get in.
</P>
<P>
   She let out a sigh of relief this week as she recalled the
decision.
</P>
<P>
   ''We were going to go in the Easter holidays. Luckily we
didn't,'' she said after visiting the aquarium Wednesday.
</P>
<P>
   Rigby's reluctance to wait outside the busy aquarium meant she
was not among thousands of visitors exposed to a fine mist of
microscopic water droplets tainted with the deadly legionella
bacteria that drifted out of the tourist attraction's air
conditioning cooling towers in mid-April.
</P>
<P>
   In the month since, three people have died, seven are
hospitalized in critical condition and a total of 93 people,
including Australian Finance Minister John Fahey, have been
confirmed as having contracted Legionnaires' disease.
</P>
<P>
   Elton Parkhill, one of those infected, is slowly recovering but
doctors fear his heart may have been permanently damaged.
</P>
<P>
   On April 18, Parkhill waited in line for more than an hour
outside the aquarium on the northern bank of the Yarra River while
his wife, Anita, took their two grandchildren to play elsewhere.
</P>
<P>
   Like others, he marveled at the beauty of the three-story,
oval-shaped blue building, with a metallic wave motif at the base.
He didn't notice the hot air blowing from the building's air
conditioning vents nearby. He also didn't know that the silent
stalker's incubation period meant that he would leave the aquarium
feeling fine.
</P>
<P>
   Eight days later, Parkhill, an active and healthy 76-year-old,
began to succumb to the pneumonia-like disease, which can kill up
to one in five of those infected and preys especially on the
elderly.
</P>
<P>
   ''I felt very stiff and then very, very weak -- unable to move,''
he recalled. ''For my age, I regard myself as pretty fit. I
couldn't understand it.''
</P>
<P>
   It was only when Parkhill's wife, Anita, heard about the
Legionnaires' outbreak that they called a doctor.
</P>
<P>
   Parkhill was admitted to the Royal Melbourne Hospital almost
immediately and treated with powerful antibiotics. He struggled for
each breath as he was fed oxygen through a mask.
</P>
<P>
   Parkhill said he feels lucky to be alive.
</P>
<P>
   ''If I'd gone into hospital a day later, I might not have
survived,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   His story was echoed by 69-year-old English tourist Donald
Storer who visited the aquarium on April 14 with his wife and three
grandchildren.
</P>
<P>
   A week later, he began to feel very tired. A day after that, he
could barely move. The following day he became delirious and was
not eating or drinking water. He was admitted to Melbourne's Box
Hill Hospital, where he was rehydrated and given antibiotics.
</P>
<P>
   Storer pulled through, but he has developed an irregular heart
beat and will have to be on medication for some time.
</P>
<P>
   Parkhill, Storer and the other visitors infected by the deadly
mist are not the only ones suffering.
</P>
<P>
   The $19.5 million Melbourne Aquarium, which opened at the
beginning of the year, was virtually deserted on Wednesday. Despite
a health official declaring the aquarium ''the safest place in
Melbourne to visit,'' attendance is down almost 50 percent,
spokesman Tom Smith said.
</P>
<P>
   Before the outbreak, it had been one of Melbourne's most popular
tourist destinations and the biggest gun in the southern city's
battle for a share of the country's lucrative tourist trade.
</P>
<P>
   ''There are hardly any people inside,'' Rigby said after leaving
the aquarium with her son. She admitted to being apprehensive about
visiting, although the cooling towers have been declared safe.
</P>
<P>
   The aquarium also faces a class-action lawsuit seeking
unspecified compensation for those who became infected. The case
will go to Victoria Supreme Court for an initial hearing in July,
attorney Eugene Arocca said.
</P>
<P>
   But Melbourne's Legionnaires' crisis could have been much worse.
</P>
<P>
   Health authorities believe the swift discovery of the source of
the outbreak and widespread reporting of it meant that those
suffering sought medical help early, before their health
deteriorated irretrievably.
</P>
<P>
   In the past, outbreaks have been far more deadly.
</P>
<P>
   The worst on record was the first -- at a 1976 convention of the
American Legion in Philadelphia. It sickened more than 180 people,
killed 34 and gave the newly discovered disease its name.
</P>
<P>
   Last year, an outbreak at a Dutch flower show claimed 28 lives.
</P>
<P>
   Legionella bacteria, which cause the disease, occur naturally in
soil and rivers but only begin to pose a serious health risk when
they gather and proliferate in places like air conditioning cooling
towers and whirlpool baths where water is warmed and recirculated.
</P>
<P>
   Opening its campaign to win back visitors, Melbourne Aquarium
has announced it will replace its water-cooled air conditioning
with a system that uses no water, eliminating the risk of further
infections.
</P>
<P>
   ''We can't afford to have anything that damages the reputation
that we have,'' Smith said. ''Certainly, given this has had
worldwide exposure, we have a lot of work to do to win back the
confidence of people.''
</P>
<P>
   ------
</P>
<P>
   On the Net: http://www.melbourneaquarium.com.au/
</P>
<P>
   Victoria state Department of Human Resources Legionnaires'
Disease page:
http://hna.ffh.vic.gov.au/phb/hprot/inf--dis/legion/contents.htm
</P>
