<DATE_TIME> 2000-05-13 00:57 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Court Decision May Alter Funding  </HEADLINE>
By JONATHAN D. SALANT
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON (AP) -- A federal court decision has moved closer to
removing all limits on what political parties may spend on behalf
of their candidates at a time when the Democrats and Republicans
are breaking all fund-raising records.
</P>
<P>
   But with both parties already spending unlimited ''soft money''
contributions on issue ads, any impact may be muted, said Jim
Jordan, political director for the Democratic Senatorial Campaign
Committee.
</P>
<P>
   And that assumes the decision stands. Lawyers for both parties
are reviewing the case, which still could be appealed to the
Supreme Court.
</P>
<P>
   ''It remains to be seen whether that decision will have an
impact on the 2000 races,'' said Jonathan Grella, spokesman for the
National Republican Senatorial Committee.
</P>
<P>
   The Denver-based 10th U.S. Circuit Court of Appeals earlier this
month struck down federal limits on how much money the parties can
spend on activities coordinated with the candidates.
</P>
<P>
   In 1996, the Supreme Court ruled that parties can spend as much
money as they want to help elect candidates so long as they don't
coordinate their expenditures with the campaigns.
</P>
<P>
   The parties already are pouring millions of dollars in
unregulated soft money into issue advertisements that are designed
to help elect candidates without specifically urging voters to
support them.
</P>
<P>
   Current law limits both the national and state parties to
spending $33,780 apiece to help elect a House candidate. The Senate
limits are based on population, and range from $135,120 in Delaware
to $3,272,876 in California.
</P>
<P>
   The money is in addition to the maximum $17,500 contribution a
party can make to a Senate campaign and $10,000 contribution to a
House campaign.
</P>
<P>
   If the federal court decision stands, it will give the parties
more flexibility in deciding how to spend its ''hard money'' --
funds raised under federal limits that can be used to directly aid
congressional candidates.
</P>
<P>
   ''The ruling really elevates hard money,'' said Rep. Tom Davis,
R-Va., chairman of the National Republican Congressional Committee.
''I would much rather use coordinated dollars than run issue ads.''
</P>
<P>
   Across the aisle, Democratic Congressional Campaign Committee
spokesman John Del Cecato said his party has plenty of hard money
to match the GOP spending.
</P>
<P>
   ''Whatever the environment is, our financial advantage will make
us better equipped to compete,'' Del Cecato said.
</P>
<P>
   The parties are routinely reporting new fund-raising records.
For example, the DCCC had $28.6 million in the bank as of March 31,
nine times more than the $3.1 million it had four years ago. The
NRCC reported a bank account balance of $18.2 million, up from $11
million during the same period in 1996.
</P>
<P>
   President Clinton is scheduled to headline a Philadelphia
fund-raising event next Friday that is to bring in an estimated
$500,000 for the DCCC, while Vice President Al Gore is the guest of
honor at a birthday party and fund-raiser for Rep. Charles Rangel,
D-N.Y., who would become chairman of the House Ways and Means
Committee if the Democrats recapture the House. The Rangel bash,
scheduled for June 5 in New York City, ''has the potential to be
one of our biggest events outside of Washington ever,'' Del Cecato
said.
</P>
<P>
   On the Republican side, presumptive presidential nominee George
W. Bush has agreed to headline some fund-raisers for the House
Republicans.
</P>
<P>
   ''He's a critical part of us keeping the House,'' Davis said.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER> AP-NY-05-13-00 0057 </TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> APW20000513.0015 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-05-13 00:57 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Lawmakers Move Against Corps Change  </HEADLINE>
By JENNIFER LOVEN
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON (AP) -- Congress is moving to block the Clinton
administration's effort to break up the cozy relationship between
Capitol Hill and the Army Corps of Engineers, which is battling
charges that top officials rigged data to justify a costly
Mississippi River construction project.
</P>
<P>
   A provision forbidding federal funds from being used to make
management changes at the corps was quietly tacked onto the
spending blueprint for agricultural programs next year. The $75.3
billion bill was approved by the Senate Appropriations Committee
earlier this week.
</P>
<P>
   The ''rider,'' inserted by Sen. Pete Domenici, R-N.M., is aimed
at an announcement last month by Army Secretary Louis Caldera that
all final decisions on corps project recommendations would be
placed in the hands of the Army's assistant secretary for civil
works. Caldera's changes were an attempt to assert his control over
the corps and its $4 billion in river construction and flood
control projects.
</P>
<P>
   But the Republican chairmen of the Senate Appropriations, Armed
Services and Environment committees complained. They said the
reforms might allow too much involvement by the Clinton
administration in the corps' recommendations to Congress on
projects, which are popular with lawmakers for the jobs and
spending they bring to their districts.
</P>
<P>
   Caldera agreed to suspend the restructuring, while the three
committees conduct a still-pending joint investigation.
</P>
<P>
   The rider drew a strong reaction from the Pentagon. A statement
from the Army noted the administration is cooperating with the
Senate investigation.
</P>
<P>
   ''In light of those ongoing discussions, the introduction of
this new proposal is unwarranted and unproductive,'' the Army
statement said. ''Moreover, we are deeply concerned about the
effect the proposed provision would have on the authority and
responsibility of the executive branch ... to manage the corps,
maintain civilian oversight of the agency and ensure appropriate
accountability to the American people.''
</P>
<P>
   The provision also angered environmental groups.
</P>
<P>
   ''The absence of meaningful civilian oversight over the Corps of
Engineers has empowered Congress to set the agenda for the corps,''
said Scott Faber of the conservation group American Rivers. ''That
has created an environment where the abuse of corps planning rules
is rampant.''
</P>
<P>
   Domenici spokesman Chris Gallegos said the senator just wanted
to ensure no changes would be enacted without consultation with
Capitol Hill.
</P>
<P>
   ''There is an attempt to shift accountability of the Army Corps
from Congress and more to the administration side,'' Gallegos said.
</P>
<P>
   The controversy began when a whistleblower alleged that top
corps brass altered an economic study to favor a $1 billion project
to double the length of seven barge locks on the upper Mississippi
and Illinois rivers.
</P>
<P>
   Politically connected agribusiness companies say the 60-year-old
navigation system needs massive modernizations to ensure faster,
cheaper trips for commodity-laden barges.
</P>
<P>
   Environmentalists argue the river's fragile ecosystem cannot
handle more large-scale changes without serious losses in habitats
and fish and bird populations.
</P>
<P>
   The sworn affidavit filed by corps economist Donald Sweeney led
the federal Office of the Special Counsel to order the Army, which
oversees the corps, to investigate. Caldera also has asked the
National Academy of Sciences to examine the corps study. In
addition, some in Congress have asked for reviews of their own and
several committees are investigating.
</P>
<P>
   Corps officials have repeatedly denied wrongdoing, saying new
data -- not foul play -- has caused the still-unfinished study to
change.
</P>
<P>
   ------
</P>
<P>
   On the Net: Army Corps:
http://www.mvr.usace.army.mil/pdw/nav--study.htm
</P>
<P>
   Environmental Defense:
http://www.edf.org/programs/Ecosystems/mississippi
</P>
<P>
   Industry: http://www.marc2000.org
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
