<HEADLINE> Twins 4, White Sox 3, 10 Innings  </HEADLINE>
By RICK GANO
<TEXT>
<P>
   CHICAGO (AP) -- Corey Koskie delivered his fourth hit of the
game, a 10th-inning RBI single Friday night, as the Minnesota Twins
beat Chicago 4-3, sending the White Sox to their ninth loss in 11
games.
</P>
<P>
   Ron Coomer drew a walk off Sean Lowe (1-1) and pinch-hitter
David Ortiz dropped a single to center. Koskie then hit a hard
grounder that went under Paul Konerko's glove at first and into
right field as Coomer scored.
</P>
<P>
   It was the third straight dramatic win for the Twins, who
rallied from 8-1 and 5-0 deficits to win their last two games
against Cleveland.
</P>
<P>
   Travis Miller (1-2) got four outs for the win and Hector
Carrasco pitched the 10th for his first save.
</P>
<P>
   Trailing 3-1, Chicago tied it in the fifth after Mark Johnson
and Jose Valentin hit singles off starter Joe Mays. Frank Thomas
blooped a double down the right-field line that a diving Matt
Lawton just missed as Johnson scored. Lawton retrieved the ball and
overthrew the cutoff man for an error, allowing Valentin to also
score.
</P>
<P>
   Mays, who was 2-0 with a 1.96 ERA against the White Sox last
season, allowed nine hits and three runs in 7 2-3 innings before he
was lifted.
</P>
<P>
   Sox starter Jim Parque, who'd missed his previous start while
serving a three-game suspension for his role in an April melee with
Detroit, walked Koskie and Matt LeCroy to start the second before
Jacque Jones and Cristian Guzman delivered RBI singles for a 2-0
lead.
</P>
<P>
   Koskie's double, a wild pitch and another run-scoring single by
Jones made it 3-0 in the fourth.
</P>
<P>
   Carlos Lee hit an RBI double in the fourth to score Chris
Singleton from first, making it 3-1.
</P>
<P>
Notes: The start of the game was delayed 1 hour, 31 minutes by
rain. ... Thomas' first-inning single moved him into sole
possession of fifth place on the White Sox's career hit list with
1,609, moving ahead of Ozzie Guillen. ... Jones, who went 3-for-4,
is now 21-for-49 over his last 16 games. He also made two great
catches, the first in the eighth when he jumped into the wall to
snag Lee's long foul fly. Then in the ninth he crashed into the
center field fence to rob Valentin of extra bases and send the game
to extra innings.
</P>
