<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Court: We're not getting involved in nude photo shoot case  </HEADLINE>
By JOEL STASHENKO
<TEXT>
<P>
   ALBANY, N.Y. (AP) -- In a rare occurrence, members of the state's
highest court declined to give their opinions about the legality of
photographer Spencer Tunick's posing nude models on the streets and
bridges of New York City.
</P>
<P>
   The Court of Appeals Friday refused a request by the federal
Court of Appeals for the Second Circuit to clarify questions of
state law.
</P>
<P>
   Specifically, the federal appeals panel wanted answers to
''certified questions'' whether a photo shoot of between 75 and 100
naked people arranged in abstract formations would be barred under
state nudity laws and whether it makes any difference whether the
photo shoot is outdoors or indoors.
</P>
<P>
   For only the fifth time since the state Court of Appeals started
answering such certified questions for other courts in 1986, the
judges declined to venture their opinions.
</P>
<P>
   Instead, the judges said it would be best if the issue was
worked out in federal court without their input. In an unsigned
ruling, the judges said it would take them months to gather briefs
and hear oral arguments about the certified question, and they said
there was a fair chance the issue would be decided by federal
judges before they could render a ruling anyway.
</P>
<P>
   ''We conclude that certification should be declined in the
mutual interest of expeditious resolution'' of Tunick's contention
he is being denied his right of free expression by New York City's
police department, the court said.
</P>
<P>
   Tunick in July 1999 did receive a permit to take photos for five
minutes with models' clothes on, but he was barred from getting a
second permit for taking pictures of nude models by city Police
Commissioner Howard Safir. Safir argued the nude shoot would
violate city and state laws against public nudity.
</P>
<P>
   One of the lawyers representing Tunick, Norman Siegel of the New
York Civil Liberties Union, called the Court of Appeals' decision
not to answer the certified questions ''extraordinary'' and
''unusual.''
</P>
<P>
   The case now goes back to federal court. Tunick initially won
when federal Judge Harold Baer Jr. last July enjoined the city from
interfering with the artist, but the federal Court of Appeals
stayed Baer's injunction pending answers on the certified questions
from the Court of Appeals.
</P>
<P>
   Siegel said he did not think the federal appeals court needed
any help from the state Court of Appeals to decide the
free-expression claim raised by Tunick.
</P>
<P>
   ''We thought that they could decide the question,'' Siegel said.
''I think where we are, possibly we lost a few months on this in
the time frame, but it is unprecedented.''
</P>
<P>
   The photographer has earned a reputation for taking unusual
pictures of large numbers of nude people in public places,
including the streets and bridges of New York. He usually takes the
photos during hours when there are few passers-by, but he and his
models have repeatedly been arrested. The charges previously have
been dropped.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER> AP-ES-05-13-00 0113 </TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> APW20000513.0021 </DOCNO>
