<HEADLINE> Giuliani weighing options in continuing Senate bid  </HEADLINE>
By MARC HUMBERT
<TEXT>
<P>
   ALBANY, N.Y. (AP) -- Closeted with top advisers, Mayor Rudolph
Giuliani is questioning whether he can salvage a Senate bid against
Hillary Rodham Clinton and weighing his health and marital
problems.
</P>
<P>
   A person very knowledgeable about the Republican mayor's
discussions, who spoke on condition of anonymity, said that as the
conversations proceeded Friday, Giuliani sounded increasingly
discouraged about the prospects for his campaign.
</P>
<P>
   The source said that pessimism was reflected in ''the type of
questions that he's asking and the kinds of comments he's making
after we give him answers.''
</P>
<P>
   Cautioning that the situation was extremely fluid, the source
said the mayor was going back and forth in his thinking about
whether to stay in the race.
</P>
<P>
   As of late Friday, the mayor had not told his advisers what he
would do, and the source said that the mayor's inner circle did not
expect a decision before Sunday or Monday at the earliest.
</P>
<P>
   In fact, the New York City mayor was scheduled to speak tonight
in Oneonta at the Delaware County GOP dinner.
</P>
<P>
   Giuliani announced two weeks ago he had been diagnosed with
prostate cancer. The following week he told reporters he was
spending time with ''a very good friend,'' Judith Nathan. This
week, he disclosed he was seeking a legal separation from his wife
of 16 years, Donna Hanover. Hanover responded by dropping her own
bombshell, alleging that their marital woes began several years go
over his relationship with a former press aide, Cristyne
Lategano-Nicholas.
</P>
<P>
   Several Republicans have indicated they might be willing to step
into the race if Giuliani does quit. They include Reps. Rick Lazio
and Peter King, both of Long Island; Wall Street financier Theodore
Forstmann; and state Assembly Minority Leader John Faso, among
others.
</P>
<P>
   On Friday, still working through his health and marital
problems, the mayor said he was still mulling over his options but
promised a decision as soon as possible.
</P>
<P>
   He said he felt a responsibility to the Republican Party and
would ''make a decision as quickly as I can responsibly make it.''
The state party's convention is May 30 to nominate a candidate for
the Senate race.
</P>
<P>
   Giuliani made it clear that his health was his top priority when
he talked about possibly canceling a few political events next
week, including several fund-raisers.
</P>
<P>
   ''If some things are canceled, that's the reason they're being
canceled,'' he said. ''There are things I couldn't do this week
that I'm going to have to do next week.''
</P>
<P>
   A fund-raising trip slated for several cities in California next
Tuesday and Wednesday was still tentative, but could easily be
rescheduled, said campaign spokeswoman Juleanna Glover Weiss.
</P>
<P>
   ''We still very much believe that he is running,'' she added.
</P>
</TEXT>
