<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-05-13 01:13 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Pollsters see potential Giuliani problems in close race  </HEADLINE>
By MARC HUMBERT
<TEXT>
<P>
   ALBANY, N.Y. (AP) -- Voter dissatisfaction over Rudolph
Giuliani's marital problems and concern about his health are
beginning to show up in the polls, albeit in small numbers, in New
York's already close U.S. Senate race.
</P>
<P>
   Pollsters said the situation spells potential electoral trouble
for the New York City mayor should he stay in the race against
Hillary Rodham Clinton.
</P>
<P>
   ''You don't need a poll to tell you this is going to hurt him,''
Maurice Carroll, director of the Quinnipiac College Polling
Institute, said Friday.
</P>
<P>
   A New York Daily News/New York 1 poll out Friday found that 81
percent of New York voters said Giuliani's announcement this week
that he and his wife were discussing a legal separation was a
private matter and had no effect on how they viewed him as a Senate
candidate. Nonetheless, 11 percent said the issue was relevant and
made them see him more negatively as a candidate.
</P>
<P>
   When asked if the combination of factors -- his treatable
prostate cancer, the separation, his close friendship with Judith
Nathan and his wife's claim that he had a previous relationship
with a City Hall employee during their marriage -- meant he should
get out of the race, 63 percent said he should continue to run.
Seventeen percent said he should pack up his campaign gear.
</P>
<P>
   Asked Friday if he found the results heartening, Giuliani said:
''No, this is a very highly, personal matter. My focus and concern
are for all the people involved in it. I've never paid an awful lot
of attention to polls.''
</P>
<P>
   The mayor said he had still not made up his mind about staying
in the race.
</P>
<P>
   A New York Post/Fox TV poll from the end of April, conducted by
Zogby International just after Giuliani announced he had cancer,
found that 12 percent of voters felt that meant he was no longer a
strong candidate. Eighty-two percent said he did remain a strong
candidate.
</P>
<P>
   While the negative fallout for Giuliani appears relatively
small, thus far, it comes at a time when the polls were showing the
race to be a statistical dead heat even before news of the mayor's
health and marital problems surfaced.
</P>
<P>
   Pollsters said it was the marital problems, particularly wife
Donna Hanover's allegations about the mayor's earlier behavior,
that presented the greatest political threat for Giuliani.
</P>
<P>
   ''I think that was very damaging. He's been nurturing upstate,
traditional conservative voters, many of whom may not be following
the give and take,'' said Lee Miringoff, head of Marist College's
Institute for Public Opinion. ''But the net effect of it all is
there was some wrongdoing and he was the perpetrator.''
</P>
<P>
   ''I think there's a general discomfort in watching 'Scenes From
a Marriage' and the unfolding of one's private life,'' pollster
John Zogby said.
</P>
<P>
   ''The only people likely to care about the allegations and the
issue of the marriage are social conservative types of voters and I
think they hate Hillary,'' Zogby added. ''But they might not vote
for him'' as a result of the new information.
</P>
<P>
   In New York, the independent statewide polls have, for months,
been showing that most voters have already made up their minds
about Giuliani and Clinton and that the battle is over a very small
segment of undecided voters. A Quinnipiac poll out May 1 had just
10 percent of those surveyed still on the fence. Clinton was at 46
percent to 44 percent for Giuliani.
</P>
<P>
   The New York Times has been following 11 such voters. Three of
the seven they were able to contact told the newspaper for its
Friday editions that the Giuliani marital situation had turned them
against him.
</P>
<P>
   ''I tried to overlook a lot of things,'' Thomas Beck, a Long
Island guidance counselor, told the Times. '' But I'm X-ing him out
now, I really am.''
</P>
<P>
   ''Stick a fork in him; he's done,'' said Doug Taggart, vice
president of a financial services firm in Manhattan.
</P>
<P>
   ''That's too much scandal for me,'' Charlene Clinton, a school
aide from Buffalo, told the newspaper.
</P>
<P>
   Miringoff said that about the only political bright spot for
Giuliani was that the election was still six months away.
</P>
<P>
   ''Should he decide to keep running, now is better than
mid-October,'' the Poughkeepsie-based pollster said.
</P>
<P>
   Quinnipiac College's Carroll said that in addition to hurting
him with voters, the situation will also ''hurt his capacity to
concentrate on the job'' of being a candidate. ''It's a lot of
work. You've got to concentrate. You've got to focus.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER> AP-ES-05-13-00 0113 </TRAILER>
