<DOCNO> APW20000513.0023 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-05-13 01:14 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Friend's persistence earns Vietnam veteran a place on the memorial wall </HEADLINE>
By CAROLYN THOMPSON
<TEXT>
<P>
   BUFFALO, N.Y. (AP) -- David O. Kamp is finally on the Vietnam War
Memorial Wall, set in stone as solid as the friendship that grew
between the radio operator and the platoon leader whose life he
saved, and who fought to have the name inscribed.
</P>
<P>
   Marine Cpl. Kamp's name was to be added to the wall this week.
It will be acknowledged at a Memorial Day ceremony that would not
be taking place if not for the persistence of a platoon
leader-turned-school teacher, First Lt. Dick Anderson.
</P>
<P>
   ''I'll be down in D.C. this Memorial Day,'' Anderson promised
Friday from his Portville home, about 70 miles south of Buffalo.
</P>
<P>
   Kamp, a native of Muskegon, Mich., was paralyzed at age 19 in a
firefight with the Viet Cong in December 1967. He died of heart
failure and infection in Florida in 1997.
</P>
<P>
   After Kamp's death, Anderson made it his mission to see that
Kamp be given his rightful place on the wall.
</P>
<P>
   It was not easy. Three times, Anderson submitted written
statements from doctors and nurses acknowledging that Kamp had died
as a result of his war wounds. Three times his request was rejected
by Marine Corps brass.
</P>
<P>
   A quadriplegic from wounds to the neck and chest, Kamp was in
and out of hospitals throughout his life with infections, pneumonia
and other respiratory and digestive problems, Anderson said.
</P>
<P>
   ''His lungs weren't strong enough to take in all the air,'' he
explained. ''He wouldn't have died at such a young age if he didn't
have so many complications due to his paralysis.''
</P>
<P>
   Finally, Anderson turned to the brother of a Marine he
befriended during basic training, Washington, D.C., attorney John
Dowd.
</P>
<P>
   ''He said, 'I've got a friend, a senator named John McCain,'''
Anderson said. ''McCain called the Marine Corps and a week later I
got a call and a letter saying that due to new documentation,
Dave's name is going to be put on the wall.''
</P>
<P>
   Anderson, a native of Portville, went to Vietnam in January 1967
as a Marine platoon leader with the Third Battalion, First Marine
Division. Kamp was his radio operator. Assigned on
search-and-destroy missions southwest of Da Nang, they worked
together constantly, Anderson said, and were partners in two-man
foxholes.
</P>
<P>
   Kamp saved Anderson's life, and perhaps the lives of others,
when the platoon was walking on a dike through a rice paddy one day
33 years ago.
</P>
<P>
   ''The radio man's always walking behind the platoon leader,''
Anderson said. ''Just as I got by, out of this plant pops this Viet
Cong and he had a weapon and was just about to open up on me and
the others. David Camp shot him.''
</P>
<P>
   That November, the platoon ''went afloat'' with the Third
Battalion.
</P>
<P>
   ''There was always a battalion afloat,'' he said, ''floating in
ships of the coast, making landings and doing operations wherever
they were needed.''
</P>
<P>
   Anderson, however, was assigned to serve as watch officer at
First Marine Division headquarters in Da Nang, monitoring reports
of firefights and operations. He was listening when his platoon was
sent in on an operation near Hue on Dec. 27.
</P>
<P>
   ''On the second night they were there, they got hit real bad,''
he said. ''A whole larger force came in. I'm hearing my platoon get
shot up, and that didn't make me feel very good.
</P>
<P>
   ''The firefight lasted 27 hours,'' he recalled, ''and every
officer in the company was killed. Dave was hit in the neck by an
AK-47 and took two rounds in the chest. He laid there five hours
before they could get him out.''
</P>
<P>
   Anderson visited Kamp in Great Lakes (Mich.) Naval Hospital and
again after he went home to Muskegon.
</P>
<P>
   ''They expected him to live two years,'' Anderson said. ''He
fooled them all and lived 28{ years.''
</P>
<P>
   About 22 of Kamp's relatives and fellow platoon members plan to
attend the Memorial Day ceremony.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER> AP-ES-05-13-00 0114 </TRAILER>
