<DATE_TIME> 2000-05-13 01:58 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Red Sox 9, Orioles 0  </HEADLINE>
By DAVID GINSBURG
<TEXT>
<P>
   BALTIMORE (AP) -- By the end of the game, even the Baltimore fans
were cheering for Pedro Martinez.
</P>
<P>
   Not long after that, several players and both managers applauded
the performance with superlatives that served as a testament to his
greatness.
</P>
<P>
   A well-rested Martinez marked his return from a five-game
suspension by pitching a two-hitter and striking out 15 as the
Boston Red Sox beat the slumping Baltimore Orioles 9-0.
</P>
<P>
   Pitching for the first time since May 6, Martinez (6-1) allowed
only two baserunners. He retired the first 12 batters before Albert
Belle led off the fifth inning with an opposite-field single. After
Jeff Conine hit a one-out single, Martinez recorded 14 straight
outs.
</P>
<P>
   ''That was the best display of pitching I've ever been a part
of,'' Boston catcher Jason Varitek said.
</P>
<P>
   ''If he pitches like this all year, he'll win 30 games. That's
as dominating as I've ever seen him,'' Baltimore manager Mike
Hargrove said. ''He's obviously the best in baseball today, and
pitched like it tonight.''
</P>
<P>
   That wasn't the first time a Hargrove team has been beaten by
the talented right-hander. The manager also took his share of lumps
in the 1990s while in charge of the Cleveland Indians.
</P>
<P>
   ''I don't I've ever seen anybody be this consistently dominant
for this long,'' Hargrove said. ''This guy's better than Randy
Johnson, I think. He's pitching as well as I've seen anybody
pitch.''
</P>
<P>
   Martinez, the 1999 Cy Young winner, was suspended for hitting
Cleveland's Roberto Alomar with a pitch on April 30. Martinez
struck out 17 in a 1-0 loss to Tampa Bay on May 6, then dropped his
appeal of the suspension and served the five days, which pushed
back his start by one day.
</P>
<P>
   ''Gee, I'm sure glad he got suspended,'' Hargrove deadpanned.
</P>
<P>
   Asked if he intended to make a statement to Frank Robinson, who
levied the suspension, Martinez replied, ''I don't have anything to
prove to him. He understands the way I am and he understands about
baseball. ... I'm just here to pitch, do my job and go home and be
happy.''
</P>
<P>
   Martinez returned in top form, going to 2-0 on only two batters
in lowering his ERA to 1.01. The 32 strikeouts in two games tied
the AL record set in 1968 by Cleveland's Luis Tiant.
</P>
<P>
   By the end of the game, with the home team hopelessly trailing
by nine runs, the Baltimore fans yelled after every strike.
</P>
<P>
   ''Not only are they rooting for their team but they're rooting
for the good things that happen in baseball and they recognize it
and clap for it,'' Martinez said. ''It's really nice to see that. I
can tell now that this is a baseball town.''
</P>
<P>
   It was Martinez's first shutout of the year and 12th of his
career. He has struck out at least 10 batters five times this
season and has done it 59 times lifetime.
</P>
<P>
   Mike Bordick and Greg Myers struck out three times and every
Baltimore starter fanned at least once. It was the first shutout
loss of the season for the Orioles, who have dropped five straight
and nine of 10.
</P>
<P>
   Martinez went out with a bang, striking out six of the final
seven hitters. He struck out the side in the eighth, ending the
inning with a 97 mph fastball that disposed of Mark Lewis.
</P>
<P>
   ''He was throwing just as hard at the end as he was at the
beginning. He never lost anything,'' Lewis said.
</P>
<P>
   ''That was a very special performance. It just doesn't get any
better, I don't think,'' Boston manager Jimy Williams said.
</P>
<P>
   Jose Offerman and Brian Daubach provided more than enough
offense for Martinez -- Offerman went 4-for-5 with a homer and two
RBIs, and Daubach had a homer and four RBIs.
</P>
<P>
   Sidney Ponson (2-2) gave up five runs and 11 hits in eight
innings. He gave up a run before getting an out in the first, and
that proved to be enough offense for Martinez, who threw strikes on
77 of his 113 pitches.
</P>
<P>
Notes: Martinez has not lost consecutive games since 1998. He has
won 12 of his last 14 starts. ... Belle was 0-for-13 with seven
strikeouts against Martinez before his hit. ... Boston's Mike
Stanley snapped an 0-for-18 skid with singles in the sixth and
eighth.
</P>
</TEXT>
