<DATE_TIME> 2000-05-13 02:00 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Hurst Credits Concentration, Caddie  </HEADLINE>
By TERESA M. WALKER
<TEXT>
<P>
   FRANKLIN, Tenn. (AP) -- Pat Hurst has the perfect remedy for
playing a course new to the LPGA Tour: a caddie who is a quick
study.
</P>
<P>
   ''My caddie has figured it out,'' Hurst said after shooting a
4-under-par 68 Friday for a six-stroke lead and an 11-under 133
total after two rounds of the Electrolux USA Championship, a new
tournament at The Legends Club.
</P>
<P>
   ''I only played this course once in the pro-am. He tells me
where to hit it, how far, whether to use 3-wood or bang a driver.
He keeps me in the right direction.''
</P>
<P>
   Reminded that some players don't like to admit they rely heavily
on their caddie, Hurst answered that Dan Wilson has been perfect
through 36 holes on estimating yardages.
</P>
<P>
   ''He's been dead-on for every club. That gives me a lot of
confidence. I know I've got the right club in my hand, because he
hasn't missed yet,'' she said.
</P>
<P>
   Hurst is playing her best golf since giving birth to her first
son last June. Part of the reason is changes she made in correcting
her swing back to a fade from a draw she first started using during
pregnancy. She also has been using a crosshanded grip for putting
the past month.
</P>
<P>
   And it doesn't hurt to have a caddie who knows his job. Hurst
hooked up with Wilson, who used to caddie for Dottie Pepper, in
March.
</P>
<P>
   That combination has helped her turn in an eagle, 11 birdies and
only two bogeys in leading the first two rounds.
</P>
<P>
   Cindy Figg-Currier (72) and Michelle Redman (69) were tied for
second at 5-under 139. Karrie Webb (67), Jeong Jang (67), Michelle
McGann (69), Mhairi McKay (71) and Mary Beth Zimmerman (70) were at
140, and Juli Inkster was among three at 141. Nancy Lopez was among
the 76 who survived the cut at 148.
</P>
<P>
   The ability to concentrate also has aided Hurst, whose last tour
victory was the 1998 Nabisco Dinah Shore. Winds have gusted between
20 and 25 mph the first two days, reminding Hurst of growing up in
San Francisco, where the winds blew in every afternoon off the bay.
</P>
<P>
   ''As long as you don't get down saying, 'My God, it's windy out
here. I can't believe it,' it really makes you concentrate. It
makes you think each shot,'' she said. ''You're focusing on each
shot, because you know you have to.''
</P>
<P>
   Hurst started slowly on the back nine with four straight pars
before taking advantage of the par-5 14th. She hit a lob wedge to 4
feet, setting up her first birdie. Her longest birdie putt came on
the par-4 No. 15 after an 8-iron left her six feet short.
</P>
<P>
   She ran into trouble on No. 18 when she hit her second shot into
the water and couldn't get up and down for only her second bogey
through the first 36 holes.
</P>
<P>
   Webb rebounded from her second-worst round this year, an opening
73, with six birdies and one bogey, and she could've been closer if
she hadn't lipped out a birdie putt on the 18th.
</P>
<P>
   When Webb shot a second-round 75 in January, she wound up
winning The Office Depot tournament. She is looking for her fifth
LPGA Tour victory this year and seventh overall, and said her
confidence is just fine.
</P>
<P>
   ''I'd be foolish to think I couldn't still play well,'' she
said. ''I'm in red numbers at least, so we'll see what happens this
weekend.''
Divots: Courtney Wood, a 17-year-old amateur, was among the 76
golfers who survived the cut at 148. The Nashville native, who has
a scholarship to TCU, was at 147. ... Five golfers withdrew on
Friday due to a variety of injuries, but the worst was Pearl Sinn.
She opened with a 78, but had to be carted off the course Friday
because of her allergy to fescue grass, which makes up the rough.
She had such bad hives her eyes swelled shut.
</P>
</TEXT>
