<DATE_TIME> 2000-05-13 02:19 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> More Peacekeepers in Sierra Leone  </HEADLINE>
By CLARENCE ROY-MACAULAY
<TEXT>
<P>
   FREETOWN, Sierra Leone (AP) -- Fresh troops arrived in Sierra
Leone's capital as the president paid homage to 19 people killed
during a recent demonstration against rebel troops who resumed
fighting.
</P>
<P>
   A few hundred more Jordanian soldiers arrived Friday to help
shore up the beleaguered U.N. peacekeeping force in Freetown, where
as many as 30,000 refugees gathered to escape attacks by an
advancing guerrilla army.
</P>
<P>
   During the service for the 19 killed, President Ahmed Tejan
Kabbah said the rebels who broke a peace deal and resumed fighting
the government can ''never be trusted.''
</P>
<P>
   With the coffins containing the victims lined before him, Kabbah
told more than 10,000 people crowded into the national stadium that
the Revolutionary United Front rebels had intended to overthrow the
government when they opened fire Monday on unarmed demonstrators.
</P>
<P>
   ''Their deaths have revealed evidence of wickedness toward the
government,'' Kabbah said. ''One lesson the events of last Monday
have taught me is: One should never trust anybody called a rebel.''
</P>
<P>
   The declaration was a sharp contrast to the conviviality on
display in July when Kabbah and rebel leader Foday Sankoh signed a
peace accord ending a brutal eight-year civil war that not only
left thousands dead but included the maiming and mutilation of
thousands of Sierra Leonean men, women and children.
</P>
<P>
   The peace accord, already imperiled when rebels took 500
peacekeepers hostage last week, was tattered further when
bodyguards for rebel leader Foday Sankoh began shooting in crowds
of peace demonstrators in front of Sankoh's home Monday.
</P>
<P>
   A two-hour gun battle between the rebels and government soldiers
erupted, during which some of the victims were slain by rebels
execution-style. Sankoh disappeared and his whereabouts remain
unknown.
</P>
<P>
   Thirteen civilians and six soldiers were killed, some by gunshot
and mortar wounds, others when they were trampled by the panicked,
stampeding crowd. The oldest fatality was a 60-year-old journalist;
the youngest, a 16-year-old schoolboy.
</P>
<P>
   Thousands lined the route leading from the stadium as the
coffins containing the remains of the civilians -- each draped with
Sierra Leone's green, white and blue flag -- were transported aboard
an open trailer to a cemetery at Kissy, on the eastern outskirts of
the capital. The soldiers were buried at a military cemetery on the
opposite side of the city.
</P>
<P>
   Despite calls from African countries to let United Nations
peacekeepers use more force against the rebels, there was little
indication Friday that the U.N. Security Council wanted to play a
more active combat role in the conflict.
</P>
<P>
   Council members have instead focused on reinforcing troops on
the ground with better trained and equipped battalions who could
help salvage what remains of the peace deal, European and American
diplomats said.
</P>
<P>
   Peacekeepers are currently authorized to use force to protect
themselves and civilians in danger but have refrained from any
offensive attacks.
</P>
<P>
   Meanwhile, British Defense Secretary Geoff Hoon said the
presence of British troops has partly been responsible for a
''calming in the situation'' in Sierra Leone.
</P>
<P>
   He said the British are being bolstered by other forces -- and
that that will eventually signal a British departure.
</P>
<P>
   ''We now see the Jordanian forces arrive, and we will see
further forces arriving in due course. That does mean that we will
have completed our responsibilities there -- we will have kept the
lifeline open, we will have given confidence to the U.N. forces and
we will have seen a real difference on the ground,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   ''That is a substantial achievement for British forces,'' he
said.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER> AP-NY-05-13-00 0219 </TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> APW20000513.0038 </DOCNO>
