<DATE_TIME> 2000-05-13 02:20 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Big Game Winner Reacts To Jackpot  </HEADLINE>
By KATHY BARKS HOFFMAN
<TEXT>
<P>
   LANSING, Mich. (AP) -- Having millions of dollars to his name
means swimming-pool installer Larry Ross can retire, buy a boat,
buy a house -- maybe even that purple Jaguar his wife always wanted.
</P>
<P>
   But the newest winner of the Big Game lottery jackpot also
realizes his winning ticket doesn't gain him admission to a
worry-free life.
</P>
<P>
   ''You have the ecstasy of winning and then you start realizing
the agony of what might happen,'' he said Friday after coming
forward with his wife and three children to claim half of the
record-breaking $363 million jackpot.
</P>
<P>
   ''You've got security problems now. You think about your family,
who's at risk. We're not in a secure neighborhood. We don't have
security like rich people have.''
</P>
<P>
   Ross, a 47-year-old occasional lottery player accustomed to
working 80 to 100 hours a week in the summer, said he and his
family hope to be able to weather the media attention until his
youngest child finishes seventh grade next month. Then they plan to
move from their four-bedroom ranch in the Detroit suburb of Shelby
Township to a more secure neighborhood somewhere in Michigan.
</P>
<P>
   Ross and his wife, Nancy, will take their share of the bounty in
a lump-sum payment of about $90 million before taxes. After the
lottery deducts 28 percent for federal taxes and 4.2 percent in
state income taxes, the Rosses will get about $61.2 million.
</P>
<P>
   Ross said he plans to give some of the money to charity.
</P>
<P>
   ''We're not going to do anything rash. We're going to invest
wisely,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   The other winning Big Game ticket was sold in Lake Zurich, Ill.,
30 miles northwest of Chicago. That winner has not yet come
forward.
</P>
<P>
   Ross bought his ticket to Tuesday's drawing at Mr. K's Party
Shoppe near Utica, 20 miles north of Detroit. He had stopped in to
buy a hot dog, and all he had was a $100 bill. At his wife's
urging, ''I asked the guy to give me change in lotto tickets,'' he
said.
</P>
<P>
   The Rosses have been married 25 years. Their children are: Ian,
21, Eric, 25, Shannon, 12.
</P>
<P>
   Ross said he wrote down the winning numbers incorrectly Tuesday
night on the way home and didn't realize he was a winner until
Wednesday morning.
</P>
<P>
   After he saw the winning numbers on television, ''I invented a
new dance -- I started doing the lottery dance.''
</P>
<P>
   Since then, Ross says he hasn't slept or eaten in three days.
</P>
<P>
   ''It's a great diet program: win the lotto and lose weight,'' he
said.
</P>
<P>
   The $363 million jackpot was the richest in U.S. history and
easily topped the previous record, a $295.7 million Powerball
jackpot split two years ago by 13 machinists in Westerville, Ohio.
</P>
<P>
   The Big Game's biggest individual payout remains the $197
million awarded last year to a Massachusetts woman. The Big Game is
played in Georgia, Illinois, Maryland, Massachusetts, Michigan, New
Jersey and Virginia.
</P>
<P>
   The world lottery record is $1.2 billion, set in December by
Spain's El Gordo, or the Fat One, but that game awards thousands of
prizes.
</P>
<P>
   ------
</P>
<P>
   On the Net:
</P>
<P>
   Big Game: http://www.theofficialbiggame.com
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER> AP-NY-05-13-00 0220 </TRAILER>
</DOC>
