<DATE_TIME> 2000-05-13 02:29 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Spike Lee employee alleges discrimination in pat-down searches  </HEADLINE>
By LARRY NEUMEISTER
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK (AP) -- An employee of filmmaker Spike Lee says she was
degraded and humiliated when she was unfairly singled out by U.S.
Customs agents for a humiliating full-body pat-down after returning
from a plane trip abroad.
</P>
<P>
   ''Their intrusive, sexually degrading, biased practices must
stop,'' Yvette Bradley told a Manhattan news conference Friday as
she described what she experienced on April 5, 1999 when she
arrived at Newark International Airport shortly before 10 p.m. from
a trip to Jamaica with her sister.
</P>
<P>
   ''I was degraded and my body was treated as if it had no
value,'' the 33-year-old Manhattan resident said of a search by
U.S. Customs agents.
</P>
<P>
   ''This is just one case among many,'' said Ira Glasser,
executive director of the American Civil Liberties Union.
</P>
<P>
   Bradley filed a lawsuit in federal court in Newark, citing a
General Accounting Office report suggesting that Customs agents
should do a better job choosing which airline passengers to search.
</P>
<P>
   The report, from March, said black female citizens in 1998 were
nine times more likely than white female citizens to be X-rayed
after being frisked or patted down. The searches occurred even
though the black women were less than half as likely to be found
carrying contraband as the white women, the report said.
</P>
<P>
   Janet Rapaport, a spokeswoman for the U.S. Customs Service, said
she ''cannot comment on today's case because it's pending
litigation.''
</P>
<P>
   She did note, however, that Customs had tightened procedures
involving airport searches considerably in the last year,
increasing supervision and making other changes.
</P>
<P>
   In a statement issued at the news conference, Lee said Bradley
had worked with him as an associate creative director for two
years.
</P>
<P>
   ''I was outraged and saddened when she told me of her experience
at Newark Airport, not only on her behalf but on behalf of all
African-American women who have come to expect and fear this
humiliating treatment,'' Lee said.
</P>
<P>
   ''As an employer, I am deeply disturbed that Yvette and other
women of color who work for me must wonder, every time they get on
an airplane, whether they will be detained and mistreated,'' he
added.
</P>
<P>
   Bradley said that when she returned from Jamaica she noticed as
she waited in line at a Customs checkpoint that a
disproportionately high number of black women had their luggage
searched.
</P>
<P>
   She said she mentioned the disparity to the Customs agent in
charge of her line, but he ignored her and proceeded to search her
suitcase, purse and backpack.
</P>
<P>
   Then, responding to the agent's questions, Bradley told him she
was an advertising professional with a prestigious agency and that
she lived in a Fifth Avenue penthouse. He then sent her to a room
with female inspectors, Bradley said.
</P>
<P>
   ''I think I was a little too uppity for him,'' she said. ''I
think he sent me over to degrade and humiliate me.''
</P>
<P>
   In a separate room, a female Customs agent rubbed her hands over
the surface of Bradley's entire body, including her breasts and
between her legs, according to the lawsuit.
</P>
<P>
   ''I had to suffer through it,'' she said.
</P>
<P>
   Bradley said she was later told she was selected for a search
because a $300 hat she was wearing raised suspicions.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
