<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-05-13 02:36 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Dodgers 13, Cardinals 0  </HEADLINE>
By R.B. FALLSTROM
<TEXT>
<P>
   ST. LOUIS (AP) -- Two Los Angeles Dodgers slumps are now history.
</P>
<P>
   Darren Dreifort threw a two-hitter and Shawn Green had four RBIs
in a 13-0 victory over the St. Louis Cardinals Friday night as the
Dodgers ended a four-game losing streak and a seven-game skid on
the road.
</P>
<P>
   Dreifort (3-1) struck out six and walked three in his third
career complete game, all of them shutouts. He succeeded by keeping
the ball down, allowing only three fly-ball outs.
</P>
<P>
   ''That was our best-pitched game of the year,'' manager Davey
Johnson said. ''It looked like he was kind of forcing it early, but
he settled in and made it look easy.''
</P>
<P>
   Catcher Todd Hundley helped by ending a 1-for-19 slump against
basestealers, throwing out Fernando Vina after Vina drew a leadoff
walk in the first. Hundley also homered for the fifth time in six
starts with a two-run shot that capped a five-run first, but
appeared more excited about his arm.
</P>
<P>
   ''How about that? How about that?'' he joked, pointing at
reporters. ''I just got rid of it and used the turf. I've got to
give our shortstop credit for that.''
</P>
<P>
   Green, who had a three-run double in the first and an RBI double
in the second, is 9-for-20 the last five games.
</P>
<P>
   The Dodgers jumped on Darry Kile (6-2), who has had six good
outings and two horrendous ones. He gave up eight earned runs in 1
2-3 innings at Colorado on April 13. Against the Dodgers, Kile
lasted 5 2-3 innings and allowed eight runs on seven hits as his
ERA soared to 5.51.
</P>
<P>
   ''I went out there and pretty much had my lunch handed to me,''
Kile said.
</P>
<P>
   In his other six outings, Kile has a 3.51 ERA.
</P>
<P>
   ''The Dodgers swung the bats like they knew what was coming,''
pitching coach Dave Duncan said. ''Even if you get balls in the
middle of the plate, the timing is going to be off some of the
time. It wasn't tonight.''
</P>
<P>
   Kile didn't think he was tipping his pitches.
</P>
<P>
   ''A lot of times you throw pitches over the heart of the plate
and they're going to be right on them, no matter what it is,'' Kile
said. ''That's why they're at this level.''
</P>
<P>
   Kile wasn't helped in the first when left fielder Ray Lankford,
suffering from blurred vision, was tentative going after two
catchable fly balls that dropped for hits. One of them was Green's
three-run double to left center.
</P>
<P>
   Lankford was replaced in the bottom of the first by Eric Davis,
whose two-out double was the Cardinals' only hit through the first
five innings. Manager Tony La Russa said Lankford's eyes were
dilated from a vision test on Thursday.
</P>
<P>
   The Cardinals, the NL Central leaders, lost for the seventh time
in 10 games in May.
</P>
<P>
   Reliever Darren Holmes also had a tough night, allowing an RBI
single to Todd Hollandsworth in the sixth and a two-run double by
Mark Grudzielanek in a three-run eighth.
</P>
<P>
   Alex Cora's two-run single in the ninth, his third hit, made it
13-0.
</P>
<P>
Notes: Dreifort's last shutout came against Florida on Aug. 18,
1999. ... Illinois football coach Ron Turner threw out the first
pitch and it was a wild one, sailing far above the head of the
Cardinals' Larry Sutton. ... Before Friday, the Cardinals had
outscored their opponents 48-18 in the first inning. ... The
Dodgers started the season 9-3 on the road. ... Hundley has homered
in five of his last six starts. ... The Cardinals have dropped two
of three each of the last three series. ... The Dodgers were
outscored 42-23 during their four-game losing streak.
</P>
</TEXT>
