<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-05-13 02:39 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Civil rights commission stands by NYPD report  </HEADLINE>
By SHANNON McCAFFREY
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON (AP) -- A federal civil rights panel stood by its
recommendation that a special prosecutor should handle severe cases
of police misconduct in New York City despite opposition from
Manhattan's chief prosecutor.
</P>
<P>
   The proposal is contained in a draft report the U.S. Commission
on Civil Rights prepared on the New York Police Department in the
wake of the police torture of Abner Louima and the shooting of
Amadou Diallo.
</P>
<P>
   While the report praised the department for working to improve
its relationship with minorities, it's findings were largely
unflattering. It criticized the department on everything from
training to promotions and said it appeared ''racial profiling''
was being used by city cops in deciding who to stop and frisk.
</P>
<P>
   At a meeting Friday, the commissioners suggested they may make
further specific recommendations on how the city should combat
racial profiling.
</P>
<P>
   The report they are refining also recommends requiring officers
to live in the city and that they be encouraged to obtain a
four-year college degree. Evidence shows that better-educated
officers were less likely to engage in misconduct.
</P>
<P>
   Commission Chairwoman Mary Frances Berry said she supports the
idea of a special prosecutor because it removes even the appearance
of a conflict in cases where a district attorney would usually
investigate and prosecute police officers with whom they typically
work closely. The report suggests intervention by a special
prosecutor only in serious felony-level cases.
</P>
<P>
   ''I would think the DAs would like this also,'' Berry said.
</P>
<P>
   But that doesn't appear to be the case.
</P>
<P>
   Manhattan District Attorney Robert Morgenthau wrote a letter to
the commission saying special prosecutors were not needed because
his office already vigorously pursues cases of police misconduct,
Berry said. In the letter, Morgenthau also complained that his
office had not been contacted about the commission's
recommendation. U.S. Sen. Daniel Patrick Moynihan, D-N.Y., has
called the need for special prosecutors ''nonsense.''
</P>
<P>
   Morgenthau's office had no comment Friday on the report or the
letter.
</P>
<P>
   Much of Friday's four-hour commission meeting in Washington was
spent hammering out minor details in the draft report which has yet
to be released publicly. The committee is awaiting rebuttals to its
findings from New York City Mayor Rudolph Giuliani, Police
Commissioner Howard Safir and the Civilian Complaint Review Board.
</P>
<P>
   The report -- critical of the Giuliani administration -- comes as
the mayor runs against Hillary Rodham Clinton for the U.S. Senate
seat from New York. At least one of the commissioners said the
timing of its release was politically motivated.
</P>
<P>
   ''I think that's quite self evident,'' said Commissioner Russell
Redenbaugh. ''Now we're putting out a report in the political
season.''
</P>
<P>
   The civil rights panel consists of four Democrats, three
independents (including Redenbaugh) and one Republican. Giuliani
has called the panel a ''political operation of the Democratic
Party,'' out to aid the first lady's Senate bid.
</P>
<P>
   Indeed, in a sign of how politically touchy the report is, the
commission spent a good portion of its meeting Friday discussing
how to ensure the final version includes input from the Giuliani
administration.
</P>
<P>
   ''Given the controversy ... we need to make sure we cross our
T's and dot our I's on this,'' Commissioner Christopher Edley said.
</P>
<P>
   The commission, which was created by the Civil Rights Act of
1957, has no enforcement powers but makes recommendations to
Congress and the president. The panel held a hearing on the NYPD in
New York City last May and subpoenaed thousands of pages of
documents and police complaint records.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER> AP-ES-05-13-00 0239 </TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
