<DATE_TIME> 2000-05-13 02:46 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> N.M. Fire Sends Smoke for Miles  </HEADLINE>
By BARRY MASSEY
<TEXT>
<P>
   SANTA FE, N.M. (AP) -- A fire that devoured forests and homes in
Los Alamos has left a haze over much of northern New Mexico,
causing watery eyes and scratchy throats for those living beneath
the smoke plume.
</P>
<P>
   ''Forest fire smoke contains a lot of really nasty compounds,''
said C. Mack Sewell, state epidemiologist in the state Health
Department. Among those are carbon monoxide.
</P>
<P>
   Authorities say the health problems locally should leave with
the smoke, and government officials maintained there was no danger
for people in other states.
</P>
<P>
   Additionally, though the fire invaded Los Alamos National
Laboratory, property that covers 43 square miles and 50 technical
sites, officials there said no radioactivity had been carried aloft
with smoke. A lab spokesman said air monitoring has detected no
elevated levels of radioactivity.
</P>
<P>
   For days, the smoke has hung over portions of northern New
Mexico. The fire had burned more than 33,000 acres by Friday.
</P>
<P>
   A shift in wind direction Friday pushed smoke into Santa Fe, 35
miles southeast of Los Alamos. A haze partly obscured the Sangre de
Cristo Mountains northeast of the city and an acrid odor lingered
in the air. Health officials said the smoke was responsible for
watery eyes, scratchy throats and runny noses.
</P>
<P>
   ''You can't go outside. It hurts your throat. We left town the
last couple of nights because it was so bad,'' said Terry Mulert,
36, who lives in tiny Cordova, north of Santa Fe, with his wife and
2-year-old son.
</P>
<P>
   Authorities advised people to remain indoors with windows shut
if they have respiratory problems such as asthma or feel eye and
throat irritation.
</P>
<P>
   Because of questions about pollution and health hazards from the
fire, the U.S. Environmental Protection Agency and state
Environment Department were installing independent air monitoring
equipment to measure potential contaminants from the smoke.
</P>
<P>
   The lab, which is part of the federal nuclear weapons complex,
permanently operates an air monitoring network on its property and
nearby areas. But once the fire began, the lab temporarily placed
air sampling devices in outlying towns -- some up to 40 miles away --
to test the smoke plume.
</P>
<P>
   ''There are a lot of rumors floating around. This is to give
that extra comfort level to the public to rest assured their health
is not being impacted by radioactivity,'' said Doug Stavert, the
lab's air quality group leader.
</P>
<P>
   The lab has maintained that its main supplies of radioactive
materials and high explosives are safely protected from the fire in
reinforced buildings or concrete bunkers.
</P>
<P>
   But there are questions about what's happened to buried dumps on
lab property -- some dating to early atomic bomb work in the 1940s --
that contain millions of cubic feet of wastes contaminated with
plutonium, uranium and tritium.
</P>
<P>
   Because of the continuing fire threat, the lab hasn't been able
to survey the waste sites to determine which ones were burnt,
Stavert said.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER> AP-NY-05-13-00 0246 </TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> APW20000513.0051 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-05-13 02:49 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Six Rockets Explode in Baghdad  </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
   CAIRO, Egypt (AP) -- At least six missiles exploded in the Iraqi
capital of Baghdad before dawn on Saturday, killing an infant girl
and wounding an undisclosed number of people, an Arab satellite
television channel reported.
</P>
<P>
   The attack is the second bombardment of Baghdad this month and
the third this year.
</P>
<P>
   No group immediately claimed responsibility, but Qatar's
Al-Jazeera channel reported that Iran was suspected of being behind
the attack. The Iraqi government blamed the attacks of earlier this
month and in March on Iranian agents.
</P>
<P>
   There was no immediate word either from the Iraqi government or
from Iran about the attack.
</P>
<P>
   The rockets demolished three houses in al-Karkh, a district on
the west bank of the Tigris River. Al-Jazeera showed the interior
of one of the destroyed homes and an ambulance at the scene.
</P>
<P>
   On May 1, rockets exploded in the Baladiyat district of Baghdad,
wounding eight people, at about the same time as a mortar attack on
police headquarters in Tehran, Iran. The Iraqi-based rebel group,
Mujahedeen Khalq, claimed responsibility for the Tehran attack that
wounded six people.
</P>
<P>
   On March 22, a mortar attack on Baladiyat killed four people and
injured 38.
</P>
<P>
   Iraq and Iran fought an eight-year war that ended with a
U.N.-brokered cease-fire in 1988. The two Muslim neighbors never
signed a peace treaty and their relations since the end of the war
have remained tense. Each harbors dissident groups fighting the
other's government.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
