<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Film Spotlights Algeria, France  </HEADLINE>
By MARILYN AUGUST
<TEXT>
<P>
   PARIS (AP) -- The scenes are separated by more than three
decades: the first French refugees departing aboard ship in 1962 as
Algeria lurches violently toward independence from France, the
second in 1994 as Muslim women march for peace to end nightly
massacres amid a bitter Islamic insurgency.
</P>
<P>
   The powerful images evoking the torment of modern Algeria are
brought to the screen in a new movie by French director Alexandre
Arcady, 51, a pied-noir, or French colonial, who fled with his
family in 1961.
</P>
<P>
   A box-office hit since it opened in France last month, ''La-bas,
Mon Pays,'' or ''Over There, My Homeland'' is the first foreign
film to be shot on location in Algeria in 16 years. It has earned
high marks from the press in Algeria following its world premier
there.
</P>
<P>
   ''The film crews stopped traffic. We prepared sets. This wasn't
like making a documentary or filming for the nightly news,'' said
Arcady, who received permission to film from President Abdelaziz
Bouteflika.
</P>
<P>
   Loosely adapted from a novel by Rene Bonnell, ''La-bas, Mon
Pays'' is the tale of a high-profile television anchorman called
back to his native Algeria to rescue the daughter of his first
love, Leila, who is the daughter of an Arab postal worker who lived
in the same building.
</P>
<P>
   Part thriller, part love story, the film shifts from past to
present: the good life enjoyed by French colonials colliding with
the violence and oppression of today.
</P>
<P>
   Colonial Algeria and the 1.2 million pieds-noir -- including
120,000 Jews like Arcady, who fled during the 1962 war of
independence -- have fueled the director's imagination since he
began filmmaking.
</P>
<P>
   ''It was incredible to be behind the camera in the streets where
I played as a kid, in the house where I was born, in the cemetery
where my grandmother is buried,'' Arcady said. ''But the Algeria of
my childhood no longer exists.''
</P>
<P>
   Arcady says the film's very existence sends a signal Algeria may
be ready to renew artistic ties with the West. Before independence,
Algiers once boasted 400 movie theaters, mostly French-owned.
Today, there are only 10 cinemas in the whole country, he said.
</P>
<P>
   ''I think it's a sign of a new openness and a desire for
change,'' he said at a post-screening debate in Paris.
</P>
<P>
   Algeria has been isolated since 1992 when violence erupted after
the army canceled elections that a Muslim fundamentalist party was
poised to win. Since then, resulting violence has killed at least
100,000 people.
</P>
<P>
   Last November, Bouteflika, who was elected on a peace platform
six months earlier, invited popular pied-noir singer Enrico Macias,
whose songs evoke passion and longing for Algeria, to perform in
his native Constantine.
</P>
<P>
   In exile since the massacre of family members during the
independence war, the Jewish Macias accepted. The tour was canceled
after Algerian officials bowed to pressure from 18 Muslim clerics
who protested the visit as an attempt to establish diplomatic ties
with Israel.
</P>
<P>
   ''Before independence, Christians, Jews and Arabs lived in the
same building, with their front doors always open, sharing each
other's joys and sorrows,'' Arcady said.
</P>
<P>
   That harmony ended when violence broke out and segregation
became the norm.
</P>
<P>
   ''A European walking in an Arab neighborhood or vice versa was
risking his life,'' said Lazare Bouaziz, 66, a retired dentist,
whose entire family fled the port Oran on the eve of the infamous
July 1962 massacres.
</P>
<P>
   Sylvie Moryoussef, 42, remembers being bundled into blankets and
sped to the airport in a hail of bullets in the middle of the
night. She was 4 years old.
</P>
<P>
   ''My parents lost everything, but basically, they felt lucky to
get out alive,'' she said.
</P>
<P>
   The film has been popular among pieds-noir who lived through the
period.
</P>
<P>
   ''Arcady could have made a sugarcoated version of our
experience,'' Bouaziz said. ''But instead, he showed the violence
of our exodus -- raw and unembellished.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER> AP-NY-05-13-00 0352 </TRAILER>
