<HEADLINE> Giuliani Weighing Senate Options  </HEADLINE>
By MARC HUMBERT
<TEXT>
<P>
   ALBANY, N.Y. (AP) -- Closeted with top advisers, Mayor Rudolph
Giuliani is questioning whether he can salvage a Senate bid against
Hillary Rodham Clinton and weighing his health and marital
problems.
</P>
<P>
   As the conversations proceeded Friday, Giuliani sounded
increasingly discouraged about the prospects for his campaign,
according to a person very knowledgeable about the mayor's
discussions.
</P>
<P>
   The source, who spoke on condition of anonymity, said the
mayor's pessimism was reflected in ''the type of questions that
he's asking and the kinds of comments he's making after we give him
answers.''
</P>
<P>
   Cautioning that the situation was extremely fluid, the source
said the mayor was going back and forth in his thinking about
whether to stay in the race.
</P>
<P>
   As of late Friday, the mayor had not told his advisers what he
would do. The source said the mayor's inner circle did not expect a
decision before Sunday or Monday at the earliest.
</P>
<P>
   Giuliani, 55, announced two weeks ago he had treatable prostate
cancer. The following week he told reporters he was spending time
with ''a very good friend,'' Judith Nathan. And this week, he
disclosed he was seeking a legal separation from his wife of 16
years, Donna Hanover. Hanover responded by dropping her own
bombshell, alleging that their marital woes began several years ago
over his relationship with a former press aide, Cristyne
Lategano-Nicholas.
</P>
<P>
   New polls indicate that voter dissatisfaction over the mayor's
marital problems and concern about his health could become factors
in his race with Clinton.
</P>
<P>
   A New York Daily News/New York 1 poll out Friday found that 81
percent of New York voters said Giuliani's marital problems are a
private matter. Nonetheless, 11 percent said the issue was relevant
and made them see him more negatively as a candidate.
</P>
<P>
   When asked if the combination of factors -- his treatable
prostate cancer, the separation, his close friendship with Nathan
and his wife's claim that he had a previous relationship with a
former staff member -- meant he should get out of the race, 63
percent said he should continue to run. Seventeen percent said he
should pack up his campaign gear.
</P>
<P>
   Asked Friday if he found the results heartening, Giuliani said:
''No, this is a very highly personal matter. My focus and concern
are for all the people involved in it. I've never paid an awful lot
of attention to polls.''
</P>
<P>
   A New York Post/Fox TV poll from the end of April, conducted by
Zogby International just after Giuliani announced he had cancer,
found 12 percent of voters said the disease meant he was no longer
a strong candidate. Eighty-two percent said he remained a strong
candidate.
</P>
<P>
   Several Republicans have indicated they might be willing to step
into the race if Giuliani bows out. They include Reps. Rick Lazio
and Peter King, both of Long Island; Wall Street financier Theodore
Forstmann; and state Assembly Minority Leader John Faso, among
others.
</P>
<P>
   On Friday, still working through his health and marital
problems, the mayor promised a decision as soon as possible. The
state party must nominate a candidate for the Senate race at its
convention May 30.
</P>
<P>
   Giuliani made it clear that his health was his top priority when
he talked about possibly canceling a few political events next
week, including several fund-raisers.
</P>
<P>
   ''If some things are canceled, that's the reason they're being
canceled,'' he said. ''There are things I couldn't do this week
that I'm going to have to do next week.''
</P>
<P>
   A fund-raising trip slated for several cities in California next
Tuesday and Wednesday was still tentative, but could easily be
rescheduled, said campaign spokeswoman Juleanna Glover Weiss.
</P>
<P>
   ''We still very much believe that he is running,'' she added.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER> AP-NY-05-13-00 0517 </TRAILER>
