<HEADLINE> Potassium Cyanide Barrels Found  </HEADLINE>
By GEORGE WATSON
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK (AP) -- A trailer that had contained 20 barrels of
cyanide when it was stolen from a New Jersey warehouse was found
empty in an industrial park.
</P>
<P>
   The trailer was found late Friday without a cab or license
plates at an industrial park in Queens. It had been reported
missing May 4, after it was taken from the Union County warehouse
in Linden, N.J., where it contained a shipping container with 20
drums of potassium cyanide destined for Puerto Rico.
</P>
<P>
   The orange drums are each marked with the number ''1680,'' an
industrywide number used to identify the chemical, said Detective
Joseph Pentangelo, a police spokesman. The combined value of the
cyanide, which was in powder form, is roughly $3,800, he said.
</P>
<P>
   Linden police had said earlier that the thieves were probably
unaware of their deadly cargo.
</P>
<P>
   New York City officials were first informed of the missing
trailer on Thursday, said Richard J. Sheirer, the director of the
city's Office of Emergency Management.
</P>
<P>
   The World Health Organization says potassium cyanide could be
used by terrorists, though Sheirer said, ''we don't believe it's
terrorists.''
</P>
<P>
   The FBI also is investigating.
</P>
<P>
   Potassium cyanide is used in electroplating, a process employed
to make silverware and jewelry, and can be fatal if inhaled or
swallowed.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER> AP-NY-05-13-00 0600 </TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> APW20000513.0059 </DOCNO>
