<HEADLINE> Fires Spread to S. New Mexico  </HEADLINE>
By CHAKA FERGUSON
<TEXT>
<P>
   WEED, N.M. (AP) -- Howling winds slung fire down a narrow 20-mile
swath of southern New Mexico, quickly spreading the fire over
20,700 acres and forcing 125 people to flee scattered mountain
cabins before firefighters made headway in stanching the blaze.
</P>
<P>
   The southern New Mexico villages of Sacramento and Weed -- and
several canyon enclaves in the Sacramento Mountains -- were among
areas evacuated late Thursday and early Friday as a small fire
caused by a downed power line mushroomed into a major inferno,
fanned by 70-mph winds, forest spokeswoman Denise Ottaviano said.
</P>
<P>
   ''It was just amazing how fast and furious that fire grew. It's
a narrow fire, but very long -- 20 miles long,'' Ottaviano said.
</P>
<P>
   But firefighters managed to gain some ground on the blaze.
</P>
<P>
   Fire spokeswoman Mary Stuever said the fire was 50 percent
contained and firefighters expect to have full containment by
Tuesday.
</P>
<P>
   The fire in southern New Mexico burned about 200 miles from the
blaze in Los Alamos that had torched 36,000 acres and destroyed 260
homes by Friday.
</P>
<P>
   The southern fire burned at least 20 structures -- including
homes -- in Weed, where a highway sign reads, ''Welcome to Weed.
Population 20.''
</P>
<P>
   Evacuees gathered at Cloudcroft High School about 20 miles west
of the fire's cutting edge. Some went back for a look at the damage
Friday.
</P>
<P>
   ''This was our house,'' Randy Walker said, pointing to the
smoldering ruins of what used to be a three-bedroom home.
</P>
<P>
   ''The only thing we got out of it was a few pictures and a few
clothes,'' said Walker, who fled the home Thursday night and
returned Friday morning to survey the fire's handiwork.
</P>
<P>
   The fire -- sparked by a downed electrical line -- skipped over
some canyon slopes, torched others and passed by Weed and
Sacramento about 5 miles away.
</P>
<P>
   Ottaviano, a Lincoln National Forest spokeswoman, said the fire
grew too fast for firefighters to keep up with it.
</P>
<P>
   Otero County Commission Chairman Richard Zierlein has asked Gov.
Gary Johnson to declare the fire a disaster so funds expended would
be reimbursed by the Federal Emergency Management Agency.
</P>
<P>
   Not all was lost -- among 18 homes in Sacramento, only a shed
appeared to be burned. Flames stopped 20 feet short of Karen Hall's
log cabin, rebuilt after a 1974 fire.
</P>
<P>
   ''It's the center of our family, where everybody comes. This is
home,'' said Hall of Las Cruces, who took time off from her
teaching job to check the cabin. ''We skinned every one of those
logs ourselves.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
