<HEADLINE> Mayor still mulling over whether he'll stay in Senate race  </HEADLINE>
By DONNA DE LA CRUZ
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK (AP) -- Mayor Rudolph Giuliani says he's still mulling
over whether he'll remain in the U.S. Senate race or drop out
because of his prostate cancer and his personal problems.
</P>
<P>
   But the mayor on Friday promised a decision as soon as possible.
He made it clear that his health was priority No.1 when he talked
about possibly canceling a few events next week, including several
fund-raisers.
</P>
<P>
   ''If some things are canceled, that's the reason they're being
canceled,'' he said. ''There are things I couldn't do this week
that I'm going to have to do next week.''
</P>
<P>
   A fund-raising trip slated for several cities in California next
Tuesday and Wednesday was still tentative, but could easily be
rescheduled, said Giuliani campaign spokeswoman Juleanna Glover
Weiss.
</P>
<P>
   ''We still very much believe that he is running,'' she added.
</P>
<P>
   Giuliani has just one event on his campaign schedule in the next
few days -- a Town Hall meeting next Thursday in Manhattan. He
canceled a trip to Oneonta for tonight's Delaware County Republican
dinner.
</P>
<P>
   The mayor dined out Friday night with Judith Nathan, the woman
he's described as his ''very good friend.'' The two were joined by
several mayoral aides at an Italian restaurant on the Upper East
Side of Manhattan.
</P>
<P>
   Giuliani and Nathan smiled for photographers and strolled to
Nathan's home with the aides. She kissed each one on the cheek and
gave the mayor a goodbye hug. Just a few hours earlier, Giuliani's
wife, Donna Hanover, flew to California for a Mother's Day visit
with her parents. The mayor announced this week that the two are
separating.
</P>
<P>
   Despite the political speculation provoked by the announcement,
his supporters urged him not to abandon the race. During the
mayor's weekly radio show Friday, a caller who identified herself
as Susan from Brooklyn called Giuliani ''a national treasure.''
</P>
<P>
   Later in the show, Al from Long Island practically begged
Giuliani to stay in the Senate race against Democrat Hillary Rodham
Clinton.
</P>
<P>
   ''I'd like to call you Senator Giuliani because I think you
deserve it,'' Al said. ''I would hate to see you back down because
you're a real man. ... A man like yourself is hard to find.''
</P>
<P>
   Another caller, Michael from New Jersey, told Giuliani he should
finish his term as mayor, then run for governor.
</P>
<P>
   ''I think your talents would be wasted as a cog in the
slow-moving bureaucracy of the Senate,'' Michael said. ''I just
don't think you're suited for that, to be honest with you.''
</P>
<P>
   Giuliani told Michael other people have said the same thing to
him, and others have urged him to stay in the Senate race.
</P>
<P>
   ''I think being in the Senate would be a great honor and it
would be a great place to continue the kind of work that I've done
for the city of New York, and to spread it to the entire state, and
to some extent ... to the rest of the country,'' Giuliani said.
''And I think a change in role is good for you. I think people can
do a lot of different things in their lives.''
</P>
<P>
   However, the mayor repeatedly said Friday he has not yet decided
whether to remain in the Senate race. But he did say he had a
responsibility to the Republican Party.
</P>
<P>
   ''I'm going to make a decision as quickly as I can responsibly
make it,'' he told reporters at a bill-signing event. ''I do feel
that I have an obligation to the party.''
</P>
<P>
   Giuliani again cited his prostate cancer and his personal
problems as the main factors he's weighing, but refused to comment
further on either subject. The mayor publicly announced two weeks
ago he was diagnosed with prostate cancer.
</P>
<P>
   Two days ago, he disclosed he was seeking a legal separation
from Hanover, his wife of 16 years. Hanover responded by dropping
her own bombshell, alleging that their marital woes began several
years go over his relationship with a former press aide, Cristyne
Lategano-Nicholas.
</P>
<P>
   The tale of marital strife and alleged infidelity has filled
local papers for days, much to the mayor's dislike, and his
demeanor has been rather downcast. However, Oreo, a 7-month-old
Labrador puppy who licked Giuliani's face as he signed a bill
regarding the sterilization of dogs and cats adopted from shelters
or pet shops, seemed to perk him up a bit.
</P>
<P>
   As did one particular caller to his radio show.
</P>
<P>
   ''May all your problems be little ones,'' said Viola from
Manhattan.
</P>
<P>
   ''Yeah, I agree with that,'' the mayor said.
</P>
</TEXT>
