<HEADLINE> Couple's alleged heists through Connecticut, Massachusetts comes to an end </HEADLINE>
By The Associated Press	   A couple's lucrative six-week robbery spree through
southwestern
Connecticut and the Boston area came to an end this week when the
FBI was tipped to their New York City hideout, authorities said.
<TEXT>
<P>
   Thomas Beard, 40, and Marta Lozada, 33, of Massachusetts, were
taken into custody without incident Thursday at a Bronx apartment
where they had been staying for several days, police said. The bank
heists netted the suspects more than $50,000 in cash, according to
an FBI affidavit released Friday.
</P>
<P>
   Lozada was charged with one count of bank robbery and conspiracy
in connection with the April 28 robbery of the People's Bank on
East Putnam Avenue in Greenwich.
</P>
<P>
   Beard, who has a prior conviction for bank robbery, was charged
by the FBI Friday with four counts of bank robbery for a series of
holdups in the Boston area in late March.
</P>
<P>
   Agents said Beard's estranged wife identified him through bank
surveillance tapes.
</P>
<P>
   ''(The wife) stated that she was sure it was her husband,'' FBI
Agent Gary Cacace wrote in an arrest affidavit. ''(She) stated that
in one or more of the photos, Beard was wearing clothes that she
recognized as clothes she had bought for him.''
</P>
<P>
   The couple, who are described in police documents as drug users,
are also suspects in a spate of bank robberies in Norwalk, Darien
and Milford, Conn. and an attempted robbery in Rye, N.Y., according
to court papers.
</P>
<P>
   Both were being held in federal custody without bail.
</P>
<P>
   It was Beard's distinctive holdup notes and his prior
convictions for bank robbery that linked him and his female
companion to the crimes, FBI agents said.
</P>
<P>
   ''This is a robbery. Large bills. No dye,'' was scrawled on most
of the notes handed to the tellers.
</P>
<P>
   No weapons were shown in any of the robberies.
</P>
<P>
   Beard used a nearly identical holdup note when he robbed the
Quincy Savings Bank in Quincy, Mass., on Jan. 7, 1994. He was
subsequently convicted for that robbery and for a second holdup at
Fleet Bank in Randolph, Mass., on Jan. 14, 1994.
</P>
<P>
   The FBI alleges Beard started robbing banks again in March.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
