<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-05-13 13:13 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Sierra Leone Junta Leader Returns  </HEADLINE>
By ALEXANDRA ZAVIS
<TEXT>
<P>
   FREETOWN, Sierra Leone (AP) -- Until recently, Johnny Paul Koroma
was the loathed leader of an ex-junta whose forces helped rebels
ravage Freetown, burning, looting, maiming and killing thousands.
</P>
<P>
   Today he is hailed as the savior of this war-weary capital, the
one who can rescue the city from a feared rebel assault. People
wave and cheer as truckloads of Koroma's followers, bristling with
guns, race past.
</P>
<P>
   ''They are going to protect us,'' said a shouting and clapping
Mohammed Kabbah. ''We have to forgive them. They are like prodigal
sons.''
</P>
<P>
   Most here have lost confidence in the United Nations' ability to
hold together a ragged July peace accord that was supposed to end
eight years of brutal civil war. Revolutionary United Front rebels
have robbed U.N. troops of their guns, equipment -- even their
clothes -- in a series of encounters in the country's interior. They
are currently holding about 500 U.N. personnel captive.
</P>
<P>
   As clashes between the RUF and U.N. troops moved closer to the
capital this week, Koroma went on national radio to rally hundreds
of his supporters to the defense of a power-sharing government in
which he chairs a commission on the consolidation of peace.
</P>
<P>
   ''Once a soldier, always a soldier,'' Koroma said during an
interview Friday, leaning back in an overstuffed sofa in his dimly
lighted study, where a young fighter with a rifle slung over his
shoulder hovered in the background. ''I cannot sit by as a soldier
and see my country under threat.''
</P>
<P>
   Outside, soldiers in blue jeans and dark sunglasses loaded
machine guns and rocket-propelled grenades onto a truck in a haze
of marijuana smoke.
</P>
<P>
   President Ahmed Tejan Kabbah, whose government was overthrown by
Koroma in 1997, has welcomed the support of his former enemy, and
made no attempt to stop ex-junta soldiers from rearming.
</P>
<P>
   ''I really believe that people have vented enough anger and
irritation regarding what the army did before,'' Kabbah's
spokesman, Septimus Kai Kai, said at the heavily defended
presidential residence.
</P>
<P>
   ''Given this opportunity, I really believe they are trying to do
everything possible to remake their images, to rededicate
themselves to the country,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   Kai Kai noted that one of Koroma's first acts when he returned
from exile in neighboring Liberia was to visit a Freetown camp for
war victims, and apologize to men, women and children whose hands,
legs, noses and ears were hacked off by rebels in a systematic
campaign of terror.
</P>
<P>
   ''We found him to be remorseful of whatever it is he may have
done in the past, and we found that he is willing to work with us
to resolve the crisis in the country,'' Kai Kai said.
</P>
<P>
   Koroma claims that the reason he seized power in 1997 and
invited the RUF into the government was for the sake of peace. At
the time, he says, corrupt politicians profiting from the civil war
showed no willingness to let the fighting end.
</P>
<P>
   His regime was toppled by a Nigerian-led West African
intervention force. He became disillusioned with his rebel allies
soon after, as they fought side by side against the intervention
force, known as ECOMOG.
</P>
<P>
   ''When we invited them out of the bush we were very, very
friendly with them,'' Koroma said. ''When we went to them (after
being forced from power), they were hostile with us.''
</P>
<P>
   He claims no knowledge of his followers' role in a rebel assault
on Freetown in January 1999 during which thousands were maimed,
raped and killed, because the rebels had placed him under house
arrest.
</P>
<P>
   Now a born-again Christian, Koroma insists he has no lingering
presidential aspirations.
</P>
<P>
   ''I am not interested in power. If I want power I will go
through the ballot box,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   That is little comfort to some anxious Sierra Leoneans who
remember the looting and burning sprees after Koroma seized power.
</P>
<P>
   While insisting there were no preconditions for the ex-junta's
support, Koroma warned that the government has a responsibility to
the soldiers who have rallied to its defense.
</P>
<P>
   ''The government must keep to its responsibility or they might
have problems with the civilian populace,'' he said, adding
ominously: ''even the troops will not be happy.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
