<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-05-13 13:18 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Pinelands Commission eases cost of development credits  </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	   SOUTHAMPTON, N.J. (AP) -- The agency that manages growth in the
ecologically sensitive Pinelands region has approved new rules that
could lower the cost of building homes in certain areas.
</P>
<P>
   The Pinelands Commission approved rule changes Friday designed
to prevent towns from granting zoning variances that differ
significantly from the Pinelands master plan for development.
</P>
<P>
   Developers wishing to build residential units in commercial
zones such as Route 72 in Stafford Township or the Black Horse Pike
in Hamilton must buy additional building rights, called Pinelands
development credits.
</P>
<P>
   The credits are building rights sold by owners of
environmentally sensitive land where construction is strictly
limited.
</P>
<P>
   The system is designed to compensate owners of such land, as
well as to steer builders to more suitable areas for construction.
</P>
<P>
   The rule changes reduce the number of credits needed to build
residential developments of up to 20 units. Credits let developers
build more units per acre.
</P>
<P>
   The changes also should lower costs for individual property
owners who want waivers from Pinelands environmental rules, such as
building on odd-shaped lots near wetlands.
</P>
<P>
   Credits currently cost more than $20,000 apiece, which can
quickly add to the cost of building in the Pinelands.
</P>
<P>
   The changes did not come without opposition. Some commissioners
said the master plan should not be amended piecemeal. Commissioner
Candace Ashmun said the commission would be better off waiting for
an upcoming five-year review to make changes.
</P>
<P>
   She said the changes are ''looking for a problem to solve. We've
got to stop Band-Aiding the plan.''
</P>
<P>
   The changes apply only to 80,000 acres designated as regional
growth areas, which are targeted for the most intensive
development. These areas include Egg Harbor, Galloway and Hamilton
townships.
</P>
<P>
   The changes also make it easier to build assisted-living
facilities by treating them as residential rather than commercial
projects. Thus, builders of these facilities will no longer have to
buy additional development credits when building in approved growth
areas.
</P>
<P>
   The commission also formed a committee including the mayor of
Dennis, Mullica and Bass River townships to increase tourism by
creating a ''scenic byway'' between the communities.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER> AP-ES-05-13-00 1318 </TRAILER>
