<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-05-13 13:29 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Police: Liquor smuggling ring busted that reversed famous Prohibition route </HEADLINE>
By ANDREW Z. GALARNEAU
The Buffalo News
<TEXT>
<P>
   NIAGARA-ON-THE-LAKE, Ontario (AP) -- A small but highly organized
ring of liquor smugglers made millions of dollars ferrying untaxed
booze across the border in car trunks, Canadian and U.S.
authorities said.
</P>
<P>
   Police said the booze crew accused of hauling $10,000 worth of
liquor in the trunk of a specially rigged car reversed the alcohol
smuggling route from Canada to the United States during Prohibition
in the 1920s.
</P>
<P>
   Led by David Pasquantino and Carl Pasquantino, brothers from
Niagara Falls, N.Y., the smuggling ring moved 40,000 cases of
low-quality liquor worth $5.6 million from stores in Maryland to
drinkers in southern Ontario, according to investigators of the
Bureau of Alcohol, Tobacco and Firearms and the Royal Canadian
Mounted Police.
</P>
<P>
   While avoiding some $4.1 million (U.S.) in Canadian taxes, the
smuggling ring made a profit of roughly $3 million, according to
law enforcement estimates.
</P>
<P>
   The Pasquantino brothers were among six U.S. citizens charged in
the scheme, investigators said Friday in Ontario. Six Canadians
were also charged.
</P>
<P>
   David Pasquantino, 53, was arrested in Maryland Wednesday night
after leaving a Maryland liquor store in a van loaded with 200
cases of whisky, vodka and rum, said Mike Campbell, spokesman for
ATF's Baltimore office. ''He asked us why we stopped him,''
Campbell said. ''Then he asked for his attorney.''
</P>
<P>
   Those 200 cases were headed to Ontario, authorities said. For at
least two years, hundreds of cases of bottom-shelf liquor left
Maryland liquor stores in vehicles driven by the booze crew,
authorities said.
</P>
<P>
   The cases were stashed in the Niagara Falls area, according to
the indictments. With help from the Niagara County Sheriff's
Department, search warrants were served Thursday on units at 2365
Niagara Falls Blvd. and 2728 Niagara Falls Blvd. in Wheatfield,
Campbell said.
</P>
<P>
   Then, the liquor was loaded into the trunks of cars and driven
over the border, authorities said. One car seized as part of the
scheme was a 1985 Ford Crown Victoria with heavy-duty shock
absorbers controlled by an air valve under the rear bumper.
</P>
<P>
   ''We found 280 1.75 liter bottles of alcohol in the trunk,
weighing about a thousand pounds,'' said RCMP Constable Allen
Rodgers. The car rode about five inches high when empty, but
hunkered down into a normal profile when fully loaded, Rodgers
said.
</P>
<P>
   That one trunk load would fetch about $10,000 on the black
market in Ontario, police said.
</P>
<P>
   Investigators said that despite the well-organized smuggling
scheme, there was no solid evidence the group was related to
traditional organized crime groups.
</P>
<P>
   There were some indications some members of the group knew each
other from gambling locations, such as Casino Niagara and the Fort
Erie Racetrack, investigators said. They declined to be more
specific.
</P>
<P>
   In Ontario, the liquor was apparently sold mainly by individuals
to individuals, not to businesses and bars, said the RCMP's Linda
Martell. Customers ''were just your general next-door-neighbors,
people you might meet around the barbecue.''
</P>
<P>
   Charged in the United States with wire fraud were: David B.
Pasquantino, 53, and Carl J. Pasquantino, 52, both of Niagara
Falls; Francis A. Gillotti, 51, of North Tonawanda; Gerald T.
Ciccone, 57, of Town of Tonawanda; Cosmo D. Candido, 75, of Niagara
Falls; and Arthur ''Butch'' Hilts, 41, of Sanborn.
</P>
<P>
   Ciccone was also charged with interstate transportation of a
shotgun.
</P>
<P>
   The Americans were also charged in Canada with conspiracy to
smuggle, possess and distribute alcohol.
</P>
<P>
   Canadians, all from Ontario, charged were: Samuel Quaranta, 46,
of Niagara Falls; Joseph Prince, 57, of Stoney Creek; Terry Fraser,
76, of Niagara Falls; Donald MacDonald, 75, of Hamilton; Maralyn
Dusome, 39, of Stoney Creek; and Christine Martin, 42, of Niagara
Falls.
</P>
<P>
   Authorities are still considering whether to level charges
against the liquor stores and neighborhood bars in Maryland that
may have knowingly cooperated with the scheme, said BATF Canadian
attache David Krieghbaum.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
