<DATE_TIME> 2000-05-13 14:04 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Poverty Frames Philippine Rebellion  </HEADLINE>
By J.L. HAZELTON
<TEXT>
<P>
   ZAMBOANGA, Philippines (AP) -- At the heart of the Philippine
military's headquarters in the war against Islamic guerrillas is an
open-air Christian chapel.
</P>
<P>
   Little churches are scattered everywhere outside the base in
Zamboanga as well, nestled between shacks piled high with coconuts,
mangos, bananas and other produce. So are simple plastic shelters
put up by families without four solid walls to call home.
</P>
<P>
   Religion and poverty make for an explosive mix in the southern
Philippines, where two Muslim rebel groups were holding about 70
hostages -- including 40 people who were seized from the small
village of Pamantingan on Saturday by the Moro Islamic Liberation
Front.
</P>
<P>
   ''The rebels said they would behead us if we tried to escape,''
said 16-year-old Ricardo Gregorio, who was freed last week after
being held for 40 days by a second, smaller rebel group. ''It was
terrible up there, with the rebels up in the mountains. ... I'm
angry with the Abu Sayyaf, with the Muslims.''
</P>
<P>
   Their threat was not an idle one. The Abu Sayyaf rebels have
decapitated two of their hostages and have done the same to wounded
soldiers. A priest's toenails were pulled out before he was killed.
</P>
<P>
   Roman Catholicism is woven deeply into the lives of most
Filipinos. Bible texts appear in the newspapers every day. The Ten
Commandments hang behind judges on the bench. Priests say Mass in
urban shopping malls.
</P>
<P>
   But Islam came to what is now the southern Philippines with Arab
traders long before the Spanish claimed the whole stretch of
islands in the 16th century under the banner of the cross.
</P>
<P>
   As in the Americas, Spain used its missionaries to subdue,
control and convert the indigenous residents. But Mindanao's
Muslims boast they never succumbed.
</P>
<P>
   Muslims make up about 5 percent of the country's population of
74 million and are clustered mostly in Mindanao, so few Christian
Filipinos interact with their Islamic countrymen on a daily basis.
Stereotypes of Muslims as dangerous and crime-minded are rampant,
including in the media lately, where references to ''ragheads'' and
''dogs with rags wrapped around their heads'' have appeared in
opinion columns.
</P>
<P>
   Heightening Mindanao Muslims' longtime sense of dispossession
are the jobs, land and opportunities lost to Christian Filipino
migrants.
</P>
<P>
   Mindanao is the poorest region of the Philippines, a country so
destitute that children are still dying of measles. It is rich in
resources, however, including timber, fish and gold, but the per
capita annual income in its poorest Muslim provinces is about $200,
compared with more than $1,000 nationally.
</P>
<P>
   Though a four-province semiautonomous Muslim region was created
a decade ago, little development has survived the corruption and a
tight national budget.
</P>
<P>
   The governor, Nur Misuari, draws criticism for having difficulty
making the transition from rebel chief to statesman-manager.
</P>
<P>
   While much of Mindanao remains quiet, hundreds of thousands of
people have fled their homes in fear of the fighting. Stark lists
of the dead and wounded -- soldiers and civilians both -- scroll down
TV screens.
</P>
<P>
   ''This is probably the most serious security problem that has
confronted us since independence'' in 1946, said Senate Foreign
Relations Committee Chairman Francisco Tatad.
</P>
<P>
   The war began some three decades ago when Philippine dictator
Ferdinand Marcos was strengthening the central government's control
over possible separatist movements.
</P>
<P>
   The largest rebel group, Misuari's Moro National Liberation
Front, made peace in 1996, leaving the fringe Abu Sayyaf and the
much larger Moro Islamic Liberation Front, or MILF, to fight on,
along with a small communist insurgency.
</P>
<P>
   About 1,000 MILF guerrillas burst into Pamantingan in Sultan
Kudarat province on Saturday, stealing food and taking at least 40
people hostage as they escaped from pursuing government troops,
according to radio reports and officials.
</P>
<P>
   In similar attacks in the past, MILF rebels have released their
hostages unharmed under cover of darkness after completing their
escape.
</P>
<P>
   Abu Sayyaf is holding 21 Western and Asian hostages on the
island of Jolo in Mindanao province and another group of about nine
in the nearby province of Basilan.
</P>
<P>
   Freed from Basilan, 9-year-old Nova Verallo remembers playing
with the other young captives at the rebel camp during the day and
crying with loneliness at night. Twisting her hands together
constantly, she said Friday: ''I want to forget the rebels.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER> AP-NY-05-13-00 1404 </TRAILER>
