<DOCNO> APW20000513.0086 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-05-13 14:11 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Falun Gong Followers Beaten by Cops  </HEADLINE>
By CHARLES HUTZLER
<TEXT>
<P>
   BEIJING (AP) -- Police punched, knocked over and dragged away
followers of the banned Falun Gong sect in Tiananmen Square on
Saturday as group members defiantly celebrated the spiritual
movement's eighth anniversary.
</P>
<P>
   Followers raised up banners and chrysanthemums -- all yellow, a
traditionally auspicious color adopted by Falun Gong. Their
separate protests lasted seconds before police pounced, hauling
them away. The flowers remained on the square's gray paving stones
until a street sweeping truck was brought in.
</P>
<P>
   Police punched and kicked five women who tried to unfurl a
banner. The beating continued even after they were forced into a
police van. Another woman, standing amid 10 followers, was sent
sprawling to the ground. Others had to be dragged away, half-seated
in a meditation pose, although many protesters did not resist.
</P>
<P>
   At least 50 people were taken away by police after staging
scattered acts of civil disobedience across the vast square in
central Beijing. Chinese and foreign tourists, who come to the
square by the thousands every day, gawked at the outbursts and the
frenzied police response.
</P>
<P>
   The rougher tactics on display underscored the frustration of
police, who have been unable to stop protests since the communist
government banned Falun Gong 9 1-2 months ago.
</P>
<P>
   Saturday's was the third in recent weeks to mark important sect
anniversaries. On April 25, followers came to Tiananmen to remember
a protest by 10,000 followers last year that provoked the
government's ban three months later. Thursday, they honored the
birthday of founder Li Hongzhi's birthday.
</P>
<P>
   Saturday marked the sect's founding in 1992. The group has
declared the date the first World Falun Dafa Day, using another
name for the practice.
</P>
<P>
   In Hong Kong -- where the sect is not banned -- 150 practitioners
meditated, slowly performing exercises with their eyes closed, in a
park in the central business district. Events were also planned in
New York and other cities worldwide.
</P>
<P>
   An ex-government grain clerk, Li combined traditional meditation
exercises with Buddhist, Taoist and his own unorthodox ideas to
create Falun Gong. Practice is supposed to promote health and moral
living. Falun Gong attracted millions of followers in China.
</P>
<P>
   Li left China for New York in 1998, helping his movement attract
millions more around the world. But he dropped from public view
shortly after the July ban. His only trace: a photograph on Falun
Gong Web sites of Li meditating in the mountains. The picture
carries no date or location.
</P>
<P>
   Chinese leaders have called the group a public menace and a
threat to Communist Party authority. They have accused Falun Gong
of cheating people and causing 1,559 deaths, mostly among
practitioners who refused medical treatment. Human rights groups
estimate 5,000 followers have been sent to labor camps.
</P>
<P>
   Police knew protests were likely Saturday. Plainclothes police
with high-powered binoculars scanned the crowd for suspected
followers.
</P>
<P>
   Police also detained at least three foreign tourists Saturday,
apparently for photographing or videotaping protests. A uniformed
officer pushed and kicked one of the tourists into a police van.
</P>
<P>
   The government did not comment on the protests directly, but
sent its people signals that it is prevailing over the sect. State
television on the nationwide evening newscast ran a report on a
university student from a village outside Changchun, a northeastern
provincial capital, who had renounced Falun Gong.
</P>
<P>
   Newspapers reported that a leading U.S.-based religious
broadcaster supported the crackdown. On Friday, Paul Crouch,
president of the Trinity Broadcasting Network, defended China's
crackdown on the Falun Gong spiritual movement, saying the
government was protecting its citizens from a false and dangerous
cult.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER> AP-NY-05-13-00 1411 </TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> APW20000513.0087 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-05-13 14:12 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Cubans Press for Elian's Return  </HEADLINE>
By VIVIAN SEQUERA
<TEXT>
<P>
   HAVANA (AP) -- With folk dances and political speeches, tens of
thousands of Cubans on Saturday celebrated the 45th anniversary of
Fidel Castro's release from prison by pressing for the return of
Elian Gonzalez to his communist homeland.
</P>
<P>
   An estimated 50,000 government supporters massed outside the
prison on the Isle of Youth -- then known as the Isle of Pines --
where Castro was jailed for a little less than two years after he
led the disastrous July 26, 1953 attack that launched his
revolutionary battle.
</P>
<P>
   The rally on the island, located just south of Cuba's main
island, was led by Gen. Raul Castro, Fidel Castro's younger brother
and chief of the Revolutionary Armed Forces.
</P>
<P>
   Raul Castro was jailed on the island with his brother, and
released at the same time under a political amnesty by
then-President Fulgencio Batista.
</P>
<P>
   ''Our legacy for the present and future generations is ... we
are and will continue to be in a state of combat,'' said Pedro
Miret, vice president of Cuba's Council of Ministers and among
those who attacked the Moncada army barracks in the eastern city of
Santiago in 1953.
</P>
<P>
   ''Today, we say with our people: 'Bring back Elian!' '' Miret
shouted to the crowd decked out in T-shirts printed with the
6-year-old's image.
</P>
<P>
   Cuba has promised to keep up the fight for Elian's return until
his case is resolved.
</P>
<P>
   A three-judge panel of the 11th Circuit Court in Atlanta, one
step below the U.S. Supreme Court, heard arguments Thursday on a
request by Elian's Miami relatives that a political asylum hearing
be held for the boy. A ruling is not expected for several weeks.
</P>
<P>
   Elian was rescued off the coast of Florida in late November
after his mother and 10 others died when their boat sank during an
illegal journey from Cuba to the United States.
</P>
<P>
   Father and son were reunited in the United States last month
after an armed federal raid on the Miami relatives' home where they
boy had been staying. They must remain in the United States pending
the court's decision.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER> AP-NY-05-13-00 1412 </TRAILER>
