<DATE_TIME> 2000-05-13 14:58 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Zimbabwe Opposition Plan Strikes  </HEADLINE>
By ANGUS SHAW
<TEXT>
<P>
   HARARE, Zimbabwe (AP) -- Zimbabwe's main opposition party said
Saturday it is organizing a campaign of strikes and civil
disobedience to force the government to stop political violence by
ruling party militants.
</P>
<P>
   ''We need to embark on mass action to bring the government to
its senses,'' said Morgan Tsvangirai, leader of the Movement for
Democratic Change. He spoke about the plans to ask labor groups to
prepare for the campaign following an emergency meeting of party
officials.
</P>
<P>
   Earlier Saturday, war veterans and militants of the ruling party
armed with clubs and iron bars broke up a peace rally called by the
National Constitutional Assembly, an alliance of civic groups.
</P>
<P>
   The rally was aimed to protest worsening political violence over
land that has left at least 18 opposition supporters dead --
including three white farmers. War veterans and violent squatters
have been illegally occupying more than 1,000 white-owned farms for
months, saying the land disparity between whites and blacks is
unacceptable.
</P>
<P>
   Scores of police, some in riot gear, watched passively as
militants chased at least 100 people away from a sports arena in
western Harare. Others approaching were turned away by armed
militants.
</P>
<P>
   National Constitutional Assembly spokesman Tendai Biti said the
alliance had received police permission to hold the rally.
</P>
<P>
   ''It is our constitutional right to meet,'' Biti said. The
ruling Zimbabwe African National Union Patriotic Front ''forced our
people to disperse. They are the sponsors of violence.''
</P>
<P>
   At a memorial service at a Harare church, about 1,000 mourners
paid tribute to white farmer Alan Dunn, an opposition supporter who
was beaten to death May 7. Dunn's attackers are allegedly linked to
war veterans and squatters.
</P>
<P>
   Besides the deaths, opposition party officials reported more
than 5,000 incidents of ''state sponsored violence'' since
February, Tsvangirai said. The reported incidents include assaults,
rapes, intimidation and the destruction of homes.
</P>
<P>
   ''The government's strategy has been to completely undermine law
and order'' to instill fear in the electorate ahead of elections
expected to be called next month, he said.
</P>
<P>
   President Robert Mugabe's ruling party organized and financed
the farm occupations to create fear in country districts backing
the opposition that once were Mugabe's traditional stronghold,
Tsvangirai said.
</P>
<P>
   He said some veterans of the war that ended white rule in 1980
were being used to stir up violence and to ''promote the ruling
party's desperate attempts to hold onto power,'' he added.
</P>
<P>
   ''It will not surprise us if one or two of our candidates are
killed'' in election campaigning, he said. ''No one is safe in this
society.''
</P>
<P>
   Also Saturday, the state controlled Herald newspaper quoted the
country's Citizenship Office as saying that whites who never
formally renounced their British citizenship were not considered
true Zimbabweans and should surrender their Zimbabwe passports.
</P>
<P>
   Zimbabwe banned dual citizenship in 1984. Britain, however,
allowed Zimbabweans of British descent to keep their British
passports. That right could only be officially renounced at a sworn
ceremony before British officials, a step few whites took.
</P>
<P>
   The farm occupations began in February, when the government lost
a constitutional referendum that would have entrenched Mugabe's
powers and allowed the government to seize white farms without
paying compensation. Mugabe says the land seizures are acceptable
in a country where one-third of the fertile land is owned by a few
thousand whites.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER> AP-NY-05-13-00 1458 </TRAILER>
