<HEADLINE> Clooney's 'ER' Return Surprised NBC  </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
   LOS ANGELES (AP) -- ''ER'' fans weren't the only ones stunned by
George Clooney's reappearance on the show.
</P>
<P>
   Even top-ranking NBC executives didn't know Clooney's character,
Dr. Doug Ross, would be showing up to sweep nurse Carol Hathaway
off her feet in Thursday's episode.
</P>
<P>
   The Los Angeles Times reported in Saturday's editions that
''ER'' executive producer John Wells was desperate to keep the
moment secret -- desperate enough to promise bonuses to crew members
for keeping quiet, excise the scene from the script presented to
NBC, and even hide the footage in his refrigerator.
</P>
<P>
   ''John gave everyone checks and said, 'If no one finds out,
these checks are good,''' Clooney said in an interview from the
Cannes Film Festival.
</P>
<P>
   TV producers are increasingly frustrated with network executives
who give away their shows' best moments in promos designed to lure
viewers.
</P>
<P>
   For once, Wells wanted to give fans a real surprise.
</P>
<P>
   ''It's so difficult to keep anything quiet anymore,'' Wells
said.
</P>
