<HEADLINE> Armstrong Talks Politics With Grads  </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
   CINCINNATI (AP) -- What's said during a presidential election
year can seem like something from a horror movie, if you listen to
the first man to walk on the moon.
</P>
<P>
   ''Election rhetoric oozes under the door, settles over transoms
and radiates through solid walls,'' Neil Armstrong said in a rare
public speaking appearance.
</P>
<P>
   ''But if you can withstand it for six months, it will disappear
like the summer fog, at least until the next election cycle,'' he
told graduates of the College of Mount St. Joseph on Saturday.
</P>
<P>
   The 69-year-old Armstrong didn't mention his famous 1969
moonwalk during a commencement address to 214 graduates of the
suburban Cincinnati college. Rather, he discussed politics and
economic prosperity.
</P>
<P>
   Armstrong said that neither Democrats nor Republicans are
responsible for the United State's current economic success.
</P>
<P>
   ''The reality is that neither of them have much to do with the
business cycle and the state of the economy,'' said Armstrong, who
received an honorary doctorate in humane letters.
</P>
