<DOCNO> APW20000513.0098 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-05-13 15:40 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Jury Awards Top Ore. Ballot Issues  </HEADLINE>
By BRAD CAIN
<TEXT>
<P>
   SALEM, Ore. (AP) -- Linda McCathern was left a quadriplegic,
unable to hug her young daughter and requiring around-the-clock
medical care, by an accident involving a sport utility vehicle in
1995.
</P>
<P>
   A jury determined the Toyota 4-Runner had a faulty design and
awarded her $7.6 million.
</P>
<P>
   Now, McCathern is appalled that Oregon voters are being asked to
limit such awards.
</P>
<P>
   ''It's irresponsible,'' McCathern, 41, said of a measure being
decided in Tuesday's primary election that would let the state
Legislature set limits on the amount of money juries may award in
personal-injury lawsuits.
</P>
<P>
   ''Companies should be punished for the faulty products they
produce,'' she said.
</P>
<P>
   Many doctors disagree. They restrictions on jury awards are
needed to hold down the costs of malpractice insurance for doctors
and insurance coverage for all Oregonians.
</P>
<P>
   Measure 81, known as the ''pain and suffering'' meaure, is one
of six measures on the ballot in the nation's first regular primary
election conducted exclusively by mail. Oregon voters decided two
years ago to abolish the traditional polling place election in
favor of holding all future elections by mail.
</P>
<P>
   The ballots must be returned by Tuesday night.
</P>
<P>
   The primary includes contests for secretary of state, state
treasurer, state attorney general, the U.S. House and legislative
seats. George W. Bush and Alan Keyes are listed in the presidential
race for the Republicans, and Al Gore and perennial candidate
Lyndon LaRouche are listed for the Democrats.
</P>
<P>
   But the real heat is being generated by Measure 81.
</P>
<P>
   The proposition has become a high-stakes battle pitting business
and medical groups who want to limit damages against trial lawyers
and others who want juries to decide damages for themselves.
</P>
<P>
   Opponents scored a public relations coup when they persuaded
Erin Brockovich to appear, for free, in their television
commercials. The California legal investigator, portrayed by Julia
Roberts in the recent movie ''Erin Brockovich,'' bluntly tells
viewers that letting politicians decide how to run the courts ''is
a crime.''
</P>
<P>
   The president of the Oregon Medical Association, Dr. Richard
Kincade, remembers that during the 1980s some doctors refused to
deliver babies because of the skyrocketing cost of malpractice
insurance.
</P>
<P>
   ''If Measure 81 doesn't pass, there will be no mechanism to get
control over those large jury awards,'' Kincade says. ''Ultimately,
the consumer will end up paying for the increase in insurance
premium rates.''
</P>
<P>
   But Kristi Schaefer, a registered nurse who has worked with
brain injury patients for 23 years, says it's wrong to limit how
much a person can be awarded for being injured as a result of a
shoddy product or someone else's negligence.
</P>
<P>
   ''Some of the people I work with can't brush their teeth; they
don't know their children's names; they get lost going to the
mailbox,'' Schaefer says. ''For many survivors, functioning from
day to day is nearly insurmountable.''
</P>
<P>
   ------
</P>
<P>
   On the Net:
</P>
<P>
   Secretary of State: http://www.oregonvotes.com
</P>
</TEXT>
