<HEADLINE> Hearse Tours Planned in Salem, Mass.  </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
   SALEM, Mass. (AP) -- In a city that's made money capitalizing on
the murderous hysteria of its infamous witch trials, a proposal to
give tourists tours by hearse of gory landmarks is meeting heavy
resistance.
</P>
<P>
   The Mass Hysteria Haunted Hearse tour would highlight macabre
events in Salem from the time of the witch trials to the present,
including some recent murders.
</P>
<P>
   City councilors say it goes way too far.
</P>
<P>
   ''I'm not going to tell you this promotes a positive image of
the city,'' said Councilor Kim Driscoll.
</P>
<P>
   ''People say tourism is the answer here,'' Councilor Regina
Flynn told The Salem Evening News. ''On the other hand, it's what
kind of tourism do you want?''
</P>
<P>
   The council has refused to grant Douglas Antreassian a license
to run the tour, saying his application had several flaws that had
nothing to do with whether or not they liked his idea. Those flaws
included the lack of a permanent office or adequate space to park
the hearse.
</P>
<P>
   But Antreassian has decided he doesn't need a city permit and
plans to open for business June 1. He says the tour is educational
and maintains he has a First Amendment right to show even offensive
sites.
</P>
<P>
   Antreassian's attorney, Edward Dailey, said the council has
overstepped its bounds.
</P>
<P>
   ''Whether the City Council likes it or not, the City Council has
no right whatsoever to censor the script that these people are
using,'' Dailey said
</P>
</TEXT>
