<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-05-13 15:55 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> AM-NJ--School Construction, Bjt,1020  </HEADLINE>
By KATHLEEN CANNON
<TEXT>
<P>
   TRENTON, N.J.(AP) -- Irvington kindergarten teacher Consuelo
Knnerly considers her cramped classroom a mixed blessing.
</P>
<P>
   ''This is an upgrade. I used to teach in the cafeteria,'' said
Knnerly, who teaches English as a second language.
</P>
<P>
   Her classroom is in the basement of the 100-year-old Grove
Street School and has two windows; only one opens. Books and files
are piled precariously because there is no storage space. Dim
lights hang from the antique tin ceiling.
</P>
<P>
   Despite the shabby surroundings, her children are well-behaved
and busy reading text books.
</P>
<P>
   The scene is similar about 120 miles away in the southwestern
corner of the state.
</P>
<P>
   At the Oak and Main School, a 90-year-old red brick building in
Vineland, teachers accompany kindergartners down a steep flight of
stairs to the basement, to the only bathrooms in the building.
</P>
<P>
   There is no cafeteria, no multi-purpose room, no indoor
recreation space. When weather is bad during recess, teachers roll
a television with a video cassette recorder from room to room to
allow children to watch a movie.
</P>
<P>
   ''This is make-do,'' said architect Larry Merighi, who is
contracted by Vineland schools.
</P>
<P>
   Irvington and Vineland are special needs school districts, two
of 30 in New Jersey.
</P>
<P>
   The districts are in line for hundreds of millions of dollars to
improve, expand or replace outmoded and overcrowded school
buildings -- once the Legislation passes the school construction
bill.
</P>
<P>
   The bill is an outgrowth of a May 1998 state Supreme Court
ruling that most believe ordered the state to provide 100 percent
funding to improve crumbling school facilities in the special needs
districts.
</P>
<P>
   Two years later, the measure, which also includes money for more
affluent suburban districts, is crawling through the Legislature.
Two versions, with substantial differences, are pending in the
Assembly and Senate.
</P>
<P>
   Various price tags have been affixed to the bills. Last week,
state education officials estimated the program will cost $5
billion in the special needs districts and another $5.4 billion for
the others.
</P>
<P>
   The Senate bill, scheduled for a final vote Thursday, covers 100
percent of the costs in the special needs districts.
</P>
<P>
   But the version advanced by Assembly Speaker Jack Collins
proposes full funding only for emergency repairs and new classrooms
to relieve overcrowding. State money for ''extras'' such as
cafeterias and media rooms would be provided on a sliding scale,
depending on a district's ability to pay.
</P>
<P>
   Legislative leaders insist they'll craft a compromise in time to
meet the court's spring 2000 deadline to supply the money for
construction this summer.
</P>
<P>
   In the meantime, Irvington School Business Administrator Michael
G. Steele, who oversees 12 schools with an enrollment of 8,000
pupils, is trying to stretch his limited funds. The school district
estimates it needs about $172 million to upgrade facilities to meet
court requirements.
</P>
<P>
   ''We know the quirks and the limits of the buildings, and we
know what is in the budget. Then something happens like a boiler
breaks. It's very difficult planning,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   ''Because of the politics, the longer is takes, the more
expensive it becomes,'' Steele said.
</P>
<P>
   Across town, at Irvington's University Six elementary school,
hallways are grimy, windows in the stairwells are cracked and water
fountains are unsanitary
</P>
<P>
   Only three of the district's school builders are outfitted with
computers because wiring in the other schools is inadequate.
</P>
<P>
   The picture in Vineland is also grim. A booming enrollment
fueled by new families buying up cheap land is straining the
Cumberland County district's resources.
</P>
<P>
   The district is growing so fast, it still relies on trailers
housing temporary classrooms even after building an 18-room
addition to the Vineland Middle School.
</P>
<P>
   Superintendent Gerald Kohn estimates it will cost $234 million
to finish the job district-wide and upgrade or replace the 12
schools whose total enrollment of 9,400 students grows every year.
</P>
<P>
   Kohn is frustrated with the Legislature and the state Department
of Education. Lawmakers have procrastinated over the financial
solution, while the bureaucrats have nit-picked over interim
stopgap measures to help the schools, he said.
</P>
<P>
   ''It's been a huge struggle for all 30 districts,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   For example, the department forbade the district from using
state aid to finish a school expansion project to accommodate
full-day kindergarten in the city's Johnstone School -- a Supreme
Court requirement. As a result, the classrooms are finished, but
the school is still served by one six-burner stove in the
cafeteria, and rainy days turn the unfinished playground into a
muddy pit.
</P>
<P>
   ''How much begging, cajoling and table beating do we have to do
to get the state to release funding for provide full-day
kindergarten?'' he asked.
</P>
<P>
   Neither Kohn nor Steele believe local taxpayers can help pay the
bill for districts' mounting needs, as proposed by Speaker Collins.
</P>
<P>
   Kohn said Vineland voters haven't approved a bond referendum
since the late 1970s, when they voted to replace a school destroyed
by a fire.
</P>
<P>
   ''Vineland has an overtaxed population,'' he said. ''People
cannot afford to have any tax increase.
</P>
<P>
   ''That's why Collins is wrong,'' he said. ''Not only does his
proposal violate the court opinion, he'd put the burden on families
and voters who can least afford it.''
</P>
<P>
   Steele, a former township school board member and mayor, has
followed the school funding court case through its 25-year history.
</P>
<P>
   He sympathizes with Collins' position that some special needs
districts may be able to pay for their own improvements.
</P>
<P>
   ''To overburden the taxpayer is not fair. But if a community can
do it, I probably agree with Collins,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   But he said his district does not fall in that category. ''We're
tapped out. Between the school and the town, we're above our debt
limit.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
