<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Jackson State Shootings Recalled  </HEADLINE>
By PAUL PAYNE
<TEXT>
<P>
   JACKSON, Miss. (AP) -- Time has claimed much of the anger and
terror of the night 30 years ago when nightly clashes between white
motorists and black students on campus ended in a barrage of police
gunfire that left two young people dead at historically black
Jackson State University.
</P>
<P>
   Today, only the bullet-scarred walls of Alexander Hall still
attest to the violence that forced Mississippi to look at race
relations and at the way its police respond.
</P>
<P>
   May 14, 1970, marked the tragic climax of a week of
demonstrations and nightly clashes between students and white
motorists harassing them along Lynch Street, a busy thoroughfare
that cut through the then-3,500-student campus.
</P>
<P>
   The student protests had started over the Jackson Police
Department's refusal to shut down the street.
</P>
<P>
   That night, when students refused to disburse, a police
fusillade set off by the sound of a bottle breaking killed Phillip
L. Gibbs, a 21-year-old Jackson State student, and James Earl
Green, a 17-year-old passerby. Both victims were black.
</P>
<P>
   Ten days earlier, four white students had been killed when the
National Guard opened fire on anti-Vietnam protesters at Ohio's
Kent State University.
</P>
<P>
   ''I can still recall the awful screaming and yelling and the
gunfire,'' said Jack Hobbs, a television reporter who filmed the
shooting at Jackson State. ''It was deafening. I thought 'Oh my
God, they're shooting these kids.'''
</P>
<P>
   Like their northern, white counterparts, many of the Jackson
State students were angry about the Vietnam War, but in a Southern
city divided by a long and bitter civil rights struggle, the unrest
was more about simmering racial tension.
</P>
<P>
   Jackson State instructor Gene Young witnessed the shooting as a
19-year-old sophomore and traveled to Kent State on May 4 for a
service to remember the victims of both tragedies.
</P>
<P>
   ''It's therapeutic to meet with other people coming to terms
with conflict,'' Young said. ''Students on other campuses suffered
great losses also.''
</P>
<P>
   Young said he hopes Jackson State will do a better job of
educating a new generation about the shootings. Thousands turned
out for ceremonies at Kent State, but fewer than 50 attended a
candlelit vigil at Jackson State.
</P>
<P>
   Students living in Alexander Hall today admit they know little
about the shooting that made national headlines and history books.
</P>
<P>
   ''I think some police shot some guys and they had a riot about
it,'' said junior Erica Wilson, 20. ''That's all I know about it.''
</P>
<P>
   Bert Case, who along with Hobbs had been covering the protests,
said a standoff developed when police and the Mississippi Highway
Patrol demanded the students disperse after a city dump truck was
set ablaze near campus.
</P>
<P>
   When a wine bottle shattered near Case's feet, lawmen apparently
mistook the noise for gunfire and began firing in the direction of
the dormitory.
</P>
<P>
   ''Right after that bottle broke they unleashed a 29-second
fusillade, firing shotguns,'' Case said.
</P>
<P>
   ''They just panned down the side of the dormitory,'' he said.
''It was like a war zone.''
</P>
<P>
   Police and the Highway Patrol would later defend their action,
which riddled the dormitory with 275 bullet holes, with claims of a
dormitory sniper, which were never substantiated.
</P>
<P>
   A dozen injured students were transported to a hospital within
20 minutes of the incident. A federal investigation later revealed
that ambulances were not called until after the officers had picked
up their shell casings.
</P>
<P>
   Then-university president John Peoples heard news of the
shooting from National Guardsmen who arrived at his on-campus house
with fixed bayonets shortly afterward. He said students took him to
the dormitory where ''blood was running down the stairway.''
</P>
<P>
   James Earl Green's younger sister, Gloria Green McCray, now 46,
went to Kent State this year to bring closure to her brother's
death.
</P>
<P>
   Vivid memories of distant gunfire, chaos and waiting in vain for
her brother still haunt McCray.
</P>
<P>
   Last year, she earned a degree at the university -- the first in
her family.
</P>
<P>
   ''I always felt I lost something at Jackson State which could
never be returned,'' McCray said. ''But I gained something which
can never be taken away.''
</P>
<P>
   ------
</P>
<P>
   On the Net: Jackson State University site: http://www.jsums.edu/
</P>
<P>
   Kent State University's May 4.Net site: http://www.may4.net/
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER> AP-NY-05-13-00 1605 </TRAILER>
