<HEADLINE> Rainfall Hampers Soaked Mozambique  </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
   MAPUTO, Mozambique (AP) -- A week of unseasonable, heavy rainfall
in Mozambique has destroyed a key road used to deliver aid through
the southern African country, prompting officials to appeal for
more aircraft, a top relief official said Saturday.
</P>
<P>
   The rains interrupted traffic on a dirt road linking southern
and central Mozambique, Silvano Langa, director of the National
Disasters Management Institute. That road was being used to deliver
aid after parts of the main road were destroyed by floods in
February and March.
</P>
<P>
   Langa asked foreign donors to allow Mozambique to use eight
helicopters beyond Friday, when original agreements had them
retiring from the aid distribution operation. China agreed to make
two aircraft available for longer, Langa said.
</P>
<P>
   The renewed rains were also hindering flood victims trying to
resettle and build new homes, he said.
</P>
<P>
   The floods killed at least 700 people and destroyed the homes or
jobs of an estimated 2 million more.
</P>
