<HEADLINE> Homeless From N.M. Fire Taken In  </HEADLINE>
By MICHELLE KOIDIN
<TEXT>
<P>
   OJO CALIENTE, N.M. (AP) -- Janice Fron and David Fricks had never
met before, but shortly after he arrived at her home, he was
sipping a beer and flipping TV channels from her couch.
</P>
<P>
   In the days since a wildfire raged through Los Alamos,
destroying 260 homes and forcing 25,000 residents from the homes at
least a week, dozens of people in nearby communities have opened
their doors to strangers.
</P>
<P>
   A few, like Fron, spread the invitation by word of mouth, often
though friends or volunteers working at the three American Red
Cross shelters. Others who had a spare bed to offer taped
handwritten notes to bulletin boards. Some said they could take in
a family; others said they would watch over dogs and cats, horses
and even goats.
</P>
<P>
   ''When people are in need, I wouldn't think of any less than
trying to help any way I can because, you know, the shoe can be on
the other foot,'' Fron, a 48-year-old receptionist, said after
Fricks showed up with his two dogs.
</P>
<P>
   While Fricks, 50, was showering at Fron's mobile home 28 miles
north of Los Alamos, hundreds of other evacuees streamed into the
shelters seeking food, toiletries and information.
</P>
<P>
   For those like Fricks, whose home is still intact, the situation
should be short-lived. But for those whose homes were in the 36,000
acres the wildfire has burned, help food and shelter may be needed
for months to come.
</P>
<P>
   So far, volunteers have donated so much food since Wednesday's
evacuations, the Red Cross and Gov. Gary Johnson have had to plead
with would-be donors to send checks instead.
</P>
<P>
   At one shelter, a converted bingo hall at an Indian casino in
nearby Pojoaque, the director loaded two tractor-trailers with food
and sent it to another shelter.
</P>
<P>
   Jugs of water and cardboard boxes filled with canned food were
stacked up outside the hall for lack of storage space. Inside,
mothers holding the hands of small children filed down a long row
of wooden tables stacked with peanut butter and jelly, tuna and
crackers.
</P>
<P>
   Some people brought in used paperback books and board games,
which were stacked on one of 50 cots set up in the noisy, crowded
room. One person dropped off a teddy bear with the words ''I love
you'' in a red heart on its chest.
</P>
<P>
   Volunteers have arrived by the dozens, as well, at least 100
from across New Mexico and 100 more from elsewhere, Red Cross
spokeswoman Kristin Warzocha said.
</P>
<P>
   Judy Spoonhoward, 40, of Santa Fe, said she opened her home to a
man from Los Alamos because she can understand how the evacuees
feel. When she was 8, her home in North Dakota burned down.
</P>
<P>
   ''I figured anything I could do would be worth it,'' she said.
</P>
<P>
   ------
</P>
<P>
   On the Net:
</P>
<P>
   The American Red Cross: www.redcross.org
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
