<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-05-13 16:58 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Rabbi could become first clergyman to face death penalty  </HEADLINE>
By JOHN P. McALPIN
<TEXT>
<P>
   TRENTON, N.J. (AP) -- For four years her death was a mystery. Now
the killing of a rabbi's wife could become a capital crime, with
the rabbi himself facing a death sentence.
</P>
<P>
   If Camden County Prosecutor Lee Solomon decides to seek the
death penalty against Rabbi Fred J. Neulander, experts say it would
be the first time since New Jersey re-enacted the law that jurors
would be asked to execute a clergyman.
</P>
<P>
   Those on both sides of the debate say the case highlights legal
pitfalls and moral challenges posed by the death penalty.
</P>
<P>
   ''It's a potential problem for a prosecutor. You're damned if
you do, and damned if you don't,'' said Dale Jones, an assistant
public defender who specializes in capital murder trials.
</P>
<P>
   If Solomon does not seek a death sentence, he could be accused
of favoring a white middle-class defendant with the ability to hire
two private lawyers, Jones said. Saying the crime warrants
execution could be seen as vindictive.
</P>
<P>
   But the decision not to push for a death sentence could be based
more pragmatically on the difficulties in prosecuting a rabbi,
Jones said.
</P>
<P>
   Neulander would be the first clergyman to face a capital murder
charge in New Jersey, Jones said.
</P>
<P>
   Nearly six years after Carol Neulander's beating death, two men
said they were hired by the rabbi to commit the murder.
</P>
<P>
   Private investigator Leonard Jenoff and Paul Michael Daniels
told investigators they showed up at Carol Neulander's Cherry Hill
home with a lead pipe, intent on killing her, according to
prosecutors and defense lawyers for the suspects.
</P>
<P>
   Until May 1, Fred Neulander was the only person accused in the
Nov. 1, 1994, death of his 52-year-old wife. He was not charged
until September 1998.
</P>
<P>
   Neulander's lawyers maintain that the rabbi did not kill his
wife, despite accusations of infidelity on his part. They say she
was killed by an intruder in a possible robbery.
</P>
<P>
   Prosecutors had theorized that Neulander had his wife killed so
he could continue an affair, fearful a divorce would harm his
standing as senior rabbi at Congregation M'Kor Shalom, which he
founded with his wife in 1974.
</P>
<P>
   Murder for hire is one of several factors that allow prosecutors
to seek the death penalty if a defendant is found guilty.
</P>
<P>
   Before they decide, prosecutors must review the case and weigh
those factors against possible material the defense might present
to a jury in a defendant's favor. Included in that assessment is
how well mitigating evidence -- for example, all the good a
defendant has done in his life -- could play before jurors.
</P>
<P>
   Prosecutors must seek the death penalty if they believe the
aggravating factor -- in this case the plan to pay killers for the
murder -- exists, said Michael E. Riley, a former Burlington County
first assistant prosecutor.
</P>
<P>
   Under New Jersey law, every juror must agree that the
aggravating factor exists and outweighs evidence in the rabbi's
life that suggests life in prison would be a better sentence.
</P>
<P>
   ''That's why it's a horse race when it comes to a case like
this,'' said Riley, now in private practice.
</P>
<P>
   For the defense, jury selection is critical, Jones said.
</P>
<P>
   Some jurors might be swayed by a life of good works before the
murder, the public defender said. Others might feel Neulander ''had
all the accouterments of white middle-class respectability'' and
therefore be predisposed toward execution, Jones said.
</P>
<P>
   ''They might think, 'But that guy has no excuse,''' he said.
</P>
<P>
   Solomon has not said how the arrests of Daniels and Jenoff will
affect charges against Neulander. He said his office ''will review
and re-evaluate'' the case and decide whether to seek the death
penalty.
</P>
<P>
   ''That's a decision I'll have to make further down the road,''
he said.
</P>
<P>
   Neulander's trial, scheduled to begin June 19, has been
postponed. A conference to discuss the trial schedule is slated for
Sept. 5.
</P>
<P>
   His attorney, Dennis Wixted, declined to comment on possible
aggravating factors until the prosecutor makes his decision.
</P>
<P>
   Rabbi Neulander has said he found his wife's body when he
returned from Congregation M'Kor Shalom synagogue.
</P>
<P>
   Neulander, who was indicted in January 1999, remains free on
$400,000 bail.
</P>
<P>
   Jenoff and Daniels have been held in the Camden County Jail
since their arrests. Daniels is being held on $400,000 cash bail;
Jenoff's is $250,000.
</P>
<P>
   For death penalty opponents, the rabbi's case is not
extraordinary.
</P>
<P>
   ''It doesn't change our position whether he's guilty or not,
whether he's a rabbi or a homeless person, no one deserves to
die,'' said Lois Seeligshon, a spokeswoman for New Jerseyans for a
Death Penalty Moratorium.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER> AP-ES-05-13-00 1658 </TRAILER>
</DOC>
