<DOCNO> APW20000513.0114 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-05-13 17:24 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Allegations Made in Sierra Leone  </HEADLINE>
By CLARENCE ROY-MACAULAY
<TEXT>
<P>
   FREETOWN, Sierra Leone (AP) -- The feared rebel leader who
restarted Sierra Leone's civil war this month has been striking
illegal deals with international diamond firms in return for
military equipment and other supplies, the justice minister said
Saturday.
</P>
<P>
   Revolutionary United Front leader Foday Sankoh -- who during the
country's short-lived peace was put in charge of a commission
regulating mineral policy -- tried to trade or sell gems abroad for
his own enrichment and to fund his rebel movement, said the
minister, Solomon Berewa, who is also the attorney general.
</P>
<P>
   During a February trip to South Africa for medical treatment,
Sankoh conducted deals ''in a reckless manner,'' Berewa said. The
rebel leader gave one diamond company a list of supplies he wanted
-- including drugs, military equipment, radio and television gear,
political campaign materials and school supplies.
</P>
<P>
   South Africa eventually withdrew Sankoh's visa after a U.N.
Security Council committee overseeing sanctions against Sierra
Leone protested that he had violated a travel ban.
</P>
<P>
   Sankoh and his rebels have waged an eight-year war to oust
President Ahmed Tejan Kabbah's government. In a campaign of terror,
the rebels killed tens of thousands of people, and intentionally
mutilated or dismembered many more.
</P>
<P>
   The rebels are also believed to have seized about 500 U.N.
peacekeepers last week, and were holding them hostage.
</P>
<P>
   Sankoh abandoned his Freetown home Monday, and his whereabouts
were unknown. Earlier that day, demonstrators had swarmed his
house, and his bodyguards shot and killed at least four of them.
</P>
<P>
   Sierra Leonean and U.N. officials have been searching for Sankoh
since his disappearance. But it was unclear if authorities would
press charges while the rebels still held the peacekeepers hostage.
</P>
<P>
   Pro-government forces and the United Nations have managed to
restore relative calm in the capital, Freetown. But anarchy still
reigned in the rest of the West African country.
</P>
<P>
   In Sankoh's abandoned home, which was looted after he left,
officials found documents describing the illegal gem deals or
negotiations with several ''well-known'' companies and individuals
based abroad.
</P>
<P>
   ''The names are so many,'' Berewa said. ''Foday Sankoh was
anxious to have power.'' It was unclear when the officials found
the documents, or if the Justice Ministry had ordered the search.
</P>
<P>
   One document recorded Sankoh receiving 2,134 diamond pieces --
347 carats in gem-quality stones and 95 carats of industrial stones
worth at least $150,000 -- from rebel mining activities between
August 1999 and January 2000, Berewa said.
</P>
<P>
   The minister said one of the businessmen named in the documents
suggested Sankoh had smuggled the diamonds from Sierra Leone by
bringing a helicopter to the rebel-controlled eastern Kono region
and flying the gems to neighboring Guinea or Liberia.
</P>
<P>
   Under Sierra Leone's power-sharing peace deal, signed in July,
Sankoh was appointed Vice president and chairman of a state
minerals commission. His rebel fighters were given unconditional
pardons for war atrocities.
</P>
<P>
   However, the minerals commission was not allowed to issue
licenses, give concessions or export gems, Berewa said.
</P>
<P>
   ''This commission was not supposed to usurp the functions of the
Ministry of Resources,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   Overnight Friday, the rebels attacked the eastern city of Port
Loko twice, but were driven back by government forces, state-run
radio reported Saturday. Port Loko, about 45 miles northeast of
Freetown, is on a key highway linking the capital to the border
with Guinea.
</P>
<P>
   There was no independent confirmation of the battle, though the
rebels have reportedly been targeting Port Loko in recent days
because reinforcements have made Freetown increasingly resistant to
assault.
</P>
<P>
   A British naval frigate, the Argyll, was expected to arrive off
Sierra Leone's coast Saturday night to provide communications
support to British paratroopers based at the airport outside
Freetown, officials said in London.
</P>
<P>
   The Argyll, the Royal Navy's West Africa guard ship, will later
be joined by the aircraft carrier Illustrious and helicopter
carrier Ocean, carrying 800 Royal Marines, along with three smaller
vessels.
</P>
<P>
   About 700 British soldiers are already bolstering the defense of
Freetown after arriving to help evacuate British expatriates. On
Friday, more peacekeepers, including a few hundred Jordanian
troops, arrived in Freetown to reinforce the beleaguered U.N.
peacekeepers.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER> AP-NY-05-13-00 1724 </TRAILER>
