<DOCNO> APW20000513.0115 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-05-13 17:26 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Trouble With Seismic Network  </HEADLINE>
By MATTHEW FORDAHL
<TEXT>
<P>
   PASADENA, Calif. (AP) -- Southern California's advanced
seismic-monitoring system faces a shaky future -- and not because of
the earthquakes it locates and analyzes minutes after the ground
stops moving.
</P>
<P>
   Money for the system, known as TriNet, is set to be halved next
year and end completely in 2002 as the grant that established the
system expires. So far nobody has offered to pay an estimated $2
million in annual maintenance costs.
</P>
<P>
   ''I don't get it,'' said Lucy Jones, scientist in charge of the
U.S. Geological Survey's Pasadena field office. ''People don't
understand what it is that we're doing.''
</P>
<P>
   TriNet uses advanced seismometers and computers to capture data
and uniformly analyze it. Within minutes of a quake, it maps
regions of intensity and probable hardest-hit areas. Rescue crews
then can be dispatched, engineers can monitor weakened buildings
and utilities can target repair crews.
</P>
<P>
   TriNet is primarily funded with Federal Emergency Management
Agency grants made after the 1994 Northridge quake. The networks at
that time helped determine its size and epicenter, but could not
discern pockets of intensity and some data were thrown off-scale by
such a large quake.
</P>
<P>
   TriNet has 110 new, high-quality instruments that can handle
both small and large quakes. By the end of next year, Southern
California will be blanketed with 670 seismometers.
</P>
<P>
   The system, established in 1997, performed flawlessly in its
first big test, last October's magnitude-7.1 Hector Mine
earthquake, showing immediately that the temblor's energy was not
directed at any urban areas.
</P>
<P>
   Supporters say TriNet's value would be even more apparent after
catastrophes like last year's quakes in Turkey.
</P>
<P>
   ''You watched all these people dying three days after the
earthquake in Turkey because it took so long to figure out the
scale of what they were dealing with,'' Jones said.
</P>
<P>
   TriNet may be a victim of its own success. State and federal
officials want to see it expanded and are directing money elsewhere
-- not to the existing Southern California project.
</P>
<P>
   The USGS has proposed the Advanced National Seismic System, a
$170.8 million, five-year project that would fold in TriNet. Last
year's federal budget funded seismic stations in Northern
California, the Pacific Northwest and Utah. President Clinton's
proposed budget seeks $2.5 million for the system, but doesn't
direct any money to Southern California.
</P>
<P>
   The state could decide to pick up the tab by including funding
in the budget revision Gov. Gray Davis is set to unveil Monday. Tom
Mullins, spokesman for the governor's Office of Emergency Services,
said the state supports TriNet and would like to see it expanded
statewide.
</P>
<P>
   ''The state now looks at Southern California and sees it being
ahead,'' said Caltech geophysicist Egill Hauksson. ''And, of
course, they want to put more into Northern California to allow
them to catch up.''
</P>
<P>
   ------
</P>
<P>
   On the Net: TriNet home page: http://www.trinet.org
</P>
<P>
   Seismology primer: http://www.scecdc.scec.org/Module/module.html
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER> AP-NY-05-13-00 1726 </TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> APW20000513.0116 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-05-13 17:32 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Image Problem Targeted in Romania  </HEADLINE>
By ALISON MUTLER
<TEXT>
<P>
   SNAGOV, Romania (AP) -- The problem of abandoned children is a
''great insult to most Romanians,'' the prime minister said
Saturday, calling for new measures to reduce the number of
youngsters in the country's orphanages.
</P>
<P>
   About 150,000 children live in government institutions, many of
them abandoned by parents too poor to care for them.
</P>
<P>
   ''It is a great insult to most Romanians, 99 percent of whom do
not abandon their children,'' Prime Minister Mugur Isarescu said at
the lakeside resort of Snagov, 25 miles north of Bucharest. ''I am
emotionally upset by this.''
</P>
<P>
   Isarescu was to meet EU officials in Brussels this week about
the abandoned children -- a problem the Eastern European country
must solve before gaining status as an EU member.
</P>
<P>
   In Brussels, Romanian officials planned to outline programs to
EU leaders on how to move children out of orphanages and into
families.
</P>
<P>
   But the plight of Romania's children -- many of whom live in
remote homes, rural towns and in the poorest areas -- was ''a human
drama that costs a fortune,'' Isarescu said. Sources close to the
premier said the programs would require international funding.
</P>
<P>
   It costs about $100 a month -- more than the average monthly
salary -- to keep a child in an institution.
</P>
<P>
   ''The larger the institution, the bigger the problems,'' he
said. ''Children must be taken into families or family-type
institutions. It is a beginning, and very important for the
country.''
</P>
<P>
   Former dictator Nicole Ceausecsu outlawed abortion and birth
control in an effort to increase population. Today, abortion is the
most popular form of birth control.
</P>
<P>
   ''These children are caused by poverty, by 20 years of sexual
ignorance,'' the prime minister said.
</P>
<P>
   Romania's abandoned children -- who were hidden away under
Ceausescu -- were first revealed after the collapse of communism.
Aid flooded into the country, and international adoptions began to
take place.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER> AP-NY-05-13-00 1732 </TRAILER>
