<DOCNO> APW20000513.0117 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-05-13 17:37 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Navy Tackles Belgian Oil Slick  </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
   BRUSSELS, Belgium (AP) -- The Belgian navy was working Saturday
to disperse an oil slick spread 25 miles off the popular beaches of
the country's North Sea coast.
</P>
<P>
   In some places the oil was as close as 1\ miles from the coast,
but the navy was confident the slick could be broken up and the oil
evaporated before it hit the shore.
</P>
<P>
   ''We expect most will be dispersed,'' Cmdr. William Blomme said
by telephone from the port of Zeebrugge. ''The risk for the beaches
is rather small.''
</P>
<P>
   Patches of oil up to 3 yards wide were detected Saturday along
the Belgium's 30 mile coastline from Zeebrugge, in the north, to
Nieuwpoort, close to the French border in the south.
</P>
<P>
   Blomme said a naval vessel had dispersed a large patch off
Zeebrugge, and was working its way down the coast breaking up the
oil on its way. The cleanup operation was helped by calm seas and
bright sunshine, which was evaporating the oil.
</P>
<P>
   He said the pollution was most likely caused by a leaking ship
or a vessel cleaning its oil tanks at sea. Samples of the oil would
be taken in an effort to trace the source, Blomme said.
</P>
<P>
   The Belgian navy warned coast guards in Britain, France and the
Netherlands about the possible pollution risk.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER> AP-NY-05-13-00 1737 </TRAILER>
