<DOCNO> APW20000513.0118 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-05-13 17:45 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Giuliani mulls future after a wild week  </HEADLINE>
By BETH GARDINER
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK (AP) -- At the end of a grueling, topsy-turvy week,
Mayor Rudolph Giuliani canceled an upstate campaign speech Saturday
and spent much of the day resting and mulling his medical options
as uncertainty hung over his Senate campaign.
</P>
<P>
   An announcement about whether the mayor plans to stay in the
U.S. Senate race against Hillary Rodham Clinton could come as soon
as Sunday or Monday, according to a person who was very
knowledgeable about Giuliani's discussions with political advisers
and spoke on condition of anonymity.
</P>
<P>
   The mayor backed out of a Delaware County GOP dinner in Oneonta
where he was to have been the keynote speaker. Aides said he was
staying in New York City and thinking about how to proceed with
treatment for his prostate cancer.
</P>
<P>
   But he also held a surprise news conference in the Bronx,
playing his favorite public role -- mayor in charge of a city
emergency -- after police discovered several barrels of stolen
cyanide.
</P>
<P>
   After briefing reporters on emergency workers' efforts, Giuliani
cautioned the press not to read too much into his decision to
cancel the Oneonta event.
</P>
<P>
   ''I've decided that I needed the time to do some consultation,''
he said. ''At this point I don't think I was up to taking the trip,
actually just taking the trip in the car for three hours. ... It
wasn't a good idea to do it healthwise.''
</P>
<P>
   The mayor's campaign manager, Bruce Teitelbaum, said that as of
early Saturday Giuliani had not made a decision about whether to
proceed with the Senate campaign and wouldn't do so until he had
more time to consider his medical options.
</P>
<P>
   ''I don't know what he's going to do,'' Teitelbaum said.
</P>
<P>
   Campaign spokeswoman Kim Serafin said a California fund-raising
trip planned for Tuesday and Wednesday was still on the mayor's
schedule.
</P>
<P>
   ''Right now nothing else has been taken off,'' she said.
</P>
<P>
   But Giuliani warned that some campaign events were likely to be
canceled, explaining that marital strife had prevented him from
speaking with all the doctors he needed to consult last week. The
mayor's marriage to Donna Hanover crumbled very publicly, as he
announced that they planned to separate and she retaliated by
accusing him of having had a relationship with a City Hall aide.
</P>
<P>
   ''You should not view the fact that I will cancel several things
next week as anything other than the fact that I didn't get the
chance to meet with the doctors that I had to meet with last week
... for obvious reasons, because of personal issues that came up,''
he said.
</P>
<P>
   Giuliani said when he revealed his illness that he would likely
cut his campaign schedule in half.
</P>
<P>
   The mayor's personal life remained a subject of intense
speculation. Just days after declaring that his marriage was
ending, he dined out Friday with Judith Nathan, the woman he has
called his ''very good friend.''
</P>
<P>
   As political wags wondered how personal woes would affect
Giuliani's standing with voters, he and Nathan ate with several
aides at an Italian restaurant on the Upper East Side of Manhattan
and then smiled for photographers.
</P>
<P>
   The group walked Nathan home, where she kissed each of her
dining companions on the cheek and gave the mayor a goodbye hug.
</P>
<P>
   The city's tabloids gobbled up the story, contrasting Giuliani's
night out with Hanover's flight to her parents' California home.
</P>
<P>
   ''Rudy and Judi Take it To Streets,'' said a New York Post
headline. ''Walkin' My Baby Back Home,'' said the Daily News front
page.
</P>
<P>
   He declined to comment on the evening, telling reporters ''It
speaks for itself.''
</P>
<P>
   Giuliani had spent part of Friday closeted with political
advisers. A person very knowledgeable about the discussions, who
spoke on condition of anonymity, said that as the conversations
proceeded, Giuliani sounded increasingly discouraged about the
prospects for his campaign.
</P>
<P>
   The source said that pessimism was reflected in ''the type of
questions that he's asking and the kinds of comments he's making
after we give him answers.''
</P>
<P>
   Cautioning that the situation was extremely fluid, the source
said the mayor was going back and forth in his thinking about
whether to stay in the race. The source said that the mayor's inner
circle did not expect a decision before Sunday or Monday at the
earliest.
</P>
<P>
   In public remarks Friday, Giuliani made clear that his health
was his top priority but promised a decision soon on the Senate
race.
</P>
<P>
   ''I'm going to make a decision as quickly as I can responsibly
make it,'' he told reporters. ''I do feel that I have an obligation
to the party.''
</P>
<P>
   ------
</P>
<P>
   AP Political Writer Marc Humbert contributed to this story.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER> AP-ES-05-13-00 1745 </TRAILER>
</DOC>
