<HEADLINE> Giuliani Mulling Future  </HEADLINE>
By BETH GARDINER
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK (AP) -- At the end of a topsy-turvy week, Mayor Rudolph
Giuliani stepped out of the spotlight Saturday, canceling a
campaign appearance and spending most of the day with doctors as
uncertainty hung over his Senate campaign.
</P>
<P>
   His campaign manager, Bruce Teitelbaum, said that as of Saturday
Giuliani had not made a decision about whether to proceed with the
campaign and wouldn't do so until he had more time to consider his
medical options. Giuliani was recently diagnosed with prostate
cancer.
</P>
<P>
   ''I don't know what he's going to do,'' Teitelbaum said.
</P>
<P>
   An announcement about whether the mayor plans to stay in the
U.S. Senate race against first lady Hillary Rodham Clinton could
come as soon as Sunday or Monday, according to a person
knowledgeable about Giuliani's discussions with political advisers
who spoke on condition of anonymity.
</P>
<P>
   The mayor backed out of a GOP dinner in Oneonta where he was to
have been the keynote speaker. He spent the day in New York City,
where a campaign adviser said he was meeting with doctors to decide
about treatment for his prostate cancer.
</P>
<P>
   But he also held a surprise news conference in the Bronx,
playing his favorite public role -- mayor in charge of a city
emergency -- after police discovered several barrels of stolen
cyanide.
</P>
<P>
   After briefing reporters on emergency workers' efforts, Giuliani
cautioned the press not to read too much into his decision to
cancel the Oneonta event.
</P>
<P>
   ''I've decided that I needed the time to do some consultation,''
he said. ''At this point I don't think I was up to taking the trip,
actually just taking the trip in the car for three hours. ... It
wasn't a good idea to do it healthwise.''
</P>
<P>
   The mayor's personal life remained a subject of intense
speculation. Just days after announcing plans to separate from wife
Donna Hanover -- she responded with a public accusation that he had
had a relationship with an aide -- Giuliani dined out Friday with
Judith Nathan, the woman he has called his ''very good friend.''
</P>
<P>
   He and Nathan ate with several aides at an Italian restaurant on
the Upper East Side of Manhattan and then smiled for photographers.
</P>
<P>
   The city's tabloids gobbled up the story, contrasting Giuliani's
night out with Hanover's flight to her parents' California home.
</P>
