<DATE_TIME> 2000-05-13 18:20 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Eight Rockets Explode in Baghdad  </HEADLINE>
By WAIEL FALEH
<TEXT>
<P>
   BAGHDAD, Iraq (AP) -- Wails of sorrow mixed with calls for
revenge Saturday hours after rockets shook Baghdad in the third
bombardment in less than two months on the heart of the tightly
policed Iraqi capital.
</P>
<P>
   A 3-year-old girl, Zahra Mohammed Hammeed, was killed and four
of her relatives were wounded in the attack, which Iran-based Iraqi
dissidents said targeted the presidential palace.
</P>
<P>
   ''My home, my home is destroyed. My child is dead now. My
brother and I are hurt. Everything is destroyed, what more do you
want?'' said Wafa Kareem Jassim, Zahra's mother.
</P>
<P>
   Two rockets struck homes in the Karadat Mariam district west of
Baghdad at just after midnight, residents said, leaving Jassim's
house a heap of rubble. Several other rockets, they said, exploded
in an open space nearby.
</P>
<P>
   Hussein Mohammed, Zahra's uncle whose home next door was
slightly damaged by another explosion, said the rocket that killed
Zahra landed next to her bed. ''Dust was all over and we could not
see anything at first. Then we found Zahra who was already dead,''
said Mohammed.
</P>
<P>
   Targeting the presidential palace -- about two miles (3.2
kilometers) from where the missiles landed -- made Saturday's attack
the most daring by the Iranian-backed Iraqi dissidents who claimed
responsibility for it.
</P>
<P>
   The Supreme Council for the Islamic Revolution in Iraq issued
statements in London and Syria saying the attack was carried out by
its affiliate, the Iraqi National Islamic Resistance.
</P>
<P>
   In Damascus, the council said assailants fired nine Katyusha
rockets at presidential palace offices ''in retaliation for the
great violations of the Iraqi people by the repressive Iraqi
regime.''
</P>
<P>
   In London, the council's Hamid al-Bayati said five rockets were
fired at the palace and four at a government building nearby.
</P>
<P>
   Odai al-Taie, director general of the state-run Iraqi News
Agency, pointing the finger at Iran, vowed in an interview that
Saturday's strike ''will not pass without punishment.'' He did not
elaborate.
</P>
<P>
   Earlier, the official Iraqi News Agency quoted an unidentified
Interior Ministry official pledging retaliation: ''The Iraqi
government holds the Iranian regime fully responsible for these
vicious acts.'' Iran will ''pay for these crimes,'' it said.
</P>
<P>
   Iraq and Iran fought an eight-year war that ended with a
U.N.-brokered cease-fire in 1988. The neighbors never signed a
peace treaty and their relations since the end of the war have
remained tense. Each harbors dissident groups fighting the other's
government.
</P>
<P>
   Both governments, however, distance themselves from such attacks
and label them acts of domestic resistance.
</P>
<P>
   On May 1, rockets exploded near the headquarters of Iraq's
General Directorate of Security in Baghdad, wounding eight people.
At about the same time, police headquarters in Tehran, Iran, were
targeted by mortar fire in an attack that wounded six people.
Iranian rebels of the Mujahedeen Khalq -- a group based in Iraq --
claimed responsibility for that attack.
</P>
<P>
   On March 22, a mortar attack on the same area killed four people
and injured 38.
</P>
<P>
   Despite the bombings, more than 1,000 Iranian pilgrims pour into
Iraq every day to pay homage at Shiite Muslim sites in the country.
In the past two months, Iran also has freed 2,479 Iraqi prisoners
captured during the war.
</P>
<P>
   Mistrust lingers with Iraq seeing itself as beleaguered by
hostile neighbors. Its relations are strained with all but Jordan.
Its pleas for rapprochement with Iran have gone unheeded.
</P>
<P>
   According to Baghdad-based diplomats, who spoke on condition
they not be named, Iran has turned down an Iraqi offer to rein in
Iranian exiles on its territory provided that Tehran ends cross
border attacks by Iraqi dissidents on its soil.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER> AP-NY-05-13-00 1820 </TRAILER>
