<HEADLINE> Guerrillas Attack Israeli Outpost  </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
   NABATIYEH, Lebanon (AP) -- Israeli warplanes bombarded suspected
guerrilla positions in southern Lebanon on Saturday following a
guerrilla attack on an Israeli outpost, Lebanese security officials
said.
</P>
<P>
   Two Israeli jets fired two missiles on hills and valleys near
the village of Habboush, two miles east of the market town of
Nabatiyeh, the officials said.
</P>
<P>
   Jets returned 15 minutes later to strike near the village of
Ahmadiyeh, 13 miles east of Habboush in Israel's self-styled
''security zone.''
</P>
<P>
   A few minutes before the air raids, guerrillas attacked an
outpost manned by Israeli troops and allied militiamen in the
occupied zone. The areas targeted by the jets are believed to be
used by guerrillas as bases.
</P>
<P>
   The Lebanese officials said guerrillas fired several rockets and
mortars at the Blatt outpost at Saturday evening, but had no word
on casualties or damage. The outpost is three miles north of
Israel's border with Lebanon.
</P>
<P>
   In Jerusalem, the Israeli military confirmed the air raids but
did not immediately comment on the Blatt attack.
</P>
<P>
   Hezbollah, or the Party of God, and the Lebanese resistance,
another Hezbollah-backed group, have led a fight to expel Israel
from the zone, which was carved out of southern Lebanon in 1985.
Israel says it needs the buffer region to protect its northern
settlements from cross-border guerrilla attacks. Some 1,500 Israeli
soldiers and the 2,500 SLA militiamen from the occupied zone
control the zone.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
