<DATE_TIME> 2000-05-13 18:23 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Utah's Jeff Hornacek May Retire  </HEADLINE>
By TIM KORTE
<TEXT>
<P>
   SALT LAKE CITY (AP) -- Jeff Hornacek might be playing the last
game of his 14-year NBA career Sunday when Portland goes for a
four-game sweep of the Utah Jazz.
</P>
<P>
   But there are no tears or emotion. As he rationalized his
retirement at Saturday's practice, Hornacek couldn't have been more
steady if he was staring at a wide-open 3-pointer.
</P>
<P>
   ''I don't think anybody's worried about the end of an era,'' he
said. ''Guys just play. There will be a guy to take this spot next
year. It's no big deal.''
</P>
<P>
   Hornacek will be the first of Utah's so-called ''Big Three'' to
leave. After this season, Karl Malone has three years left on his
contract and John Stockton has one more year.
</P>
<P>
   Stockton, Malone and Hornacek led Utah to the NBA Finals in 1997
and 1998, where they lost to Michael Jordan, Scottie Pippen and the
six-time champion Chicago Bulls.
</P>
<P>
   Jordan retired after hitting the game-winning shot to beat Utah
in Game 6 two years ago. Pippen's still playing, helping the Trail
Blazers to a 3-0 lead over the Jazz in the Western Conference
semifinals.
</P>
<P>
   Portland has dominated, putting Utah on the brink of being swept
in a best-of-seven series for the first time in franchise history.
The situation suggests the Jazz are finished as a consistent NBA
title contender.
</P>
<P>
   Perhaps it also marks the beginning of the end for Utah's
gritty, self-sacrificing approach, where long-term loyalty to
teammates has been rewarded in camaraderie if not NBA titles.
</P>
<P>
   ''I don't think it's anything we'll see again, particularly John
Stockton, the scrawny guy he is and such a feisty competitor,''
Pippen said. ''I don't expect to see another player like John.
</P>
<P>
   ''And Karl, you know he's just a different breed,'' Pippen said.
''He has a competitiveness that you can't duplicate. I don't expect
to see that type of tandem in this game again, not in my
lifetime.''
</P>
<P>
   Bonzi Wells, a second-year player who has stepped up for the
Blazers in the series, is awestruck by the monuments to Stockton
and Malone inside the Delta Center.
</P>
<P>
   ''I'm used to watching Utah against Chicago in the finals at
home on my couch,'' Wells said. ''Being here, this is overwhelming
for me just to see the banners in the air, the things on the
wall.''
</P>
<P>
   Portland coach Mike Dunleavy said because of today's free agent
market, the league isn't likely to have another veteran core of
players who stick together so long.
</P>
<P>
   ''You like to see teams who can establish that kind of identity
and rapport with each other,'' Dunleavy said. ''They genuinely look
like they enjoy playing together.''
</P>
<P>
   Hornacek's arsenal of off-balance shots and his skill at the
free-throw line became hallmarks of the Jazz, as much an
identifying mark of the team as Stockton-to-Malone on the
pick-and-roll.
</P>
<P>
   Hornacek doesn't know if he'll ''feel comfortable'' with
retirement immediately after the season ends, but he expects to
settle in as the months pass, spending more time with his family.
</P>
<P>
   And he expects the Jazz to endure without him, at least until
Stockton and Malone retire.
</P>
<P>
   ''Every year you have changes,'' Hornacek said. ''You just move
on.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER> AP-NY-05-13-00 1823 </TRAILER>
