<HEADLINE> Weekend Soccer Roundup  </HEADLINE>
By STEPHEN WADE
<TEXT>
<P>
   Bayer Leverkusen's first Bundesliga title is only one tie away.
</P>
<P>
   Leverkusen inched tantalizingly close to the championship
Saturday by thrashing Eintracht Frankfurt 4-1 with three goals
after halftime. Second-place Bayern Munich also won, 3-0 over
Arminia Bielefeld.
</P>
<P>
   Leverkusen has 73 standings points to Munich's 70, and the
season ends next week. Leverkusen, which has never finished first
since joining the Bundesliga in 1979, needs a victory or draw at
Unterhaching to clinch the title.
</P>
<P>
   Defending champion Munich, home to Werder Bremen in its finale,
needs to win and hope Leverkusen loses. If the clubs finished tied
on points, Munich would take its 16th title because of a larger
difference between goals-for and goals-against.
</P>
<P>
   A trio of German national team players -- Ulf Kirsten, Paulo Rink
and Stefan Beinlich -- scored for Leverkusen after Oliver Neuville
put Leverkusen up in the 11th minute and Eintracht's Torsten Kracht
made it 1-1 in the 40th.
</P>
<P>
   ''The nerves will decide now,'' Leverkusen manager Reiner
Calmund said.
</P>
<P>
   In other matches, 1860 Munich moved into fourth place, which
awards a Champions League berth, by beating Hertha Berlin 2-1.
Hamburg beat Unterhaching 3-0, Ulm defeated Wolfsburg 2-0, Freiburg
edged Kaiserslautern 2-1, Dortmund tied Schalke 1-1, and Stuttgart
routed Rostock 4-1.
</P>
<P>
England
</P>
<P>
   Substitute Bruce Dyer scored twice as Barnsley beat Birmingham
4-0 in the opener of a two-game, total-goals semifinal in the
playoffs for promotion to the Premier League.
</P>
<P>
   Ipswich and Bolton play Sunday in the other semif The final is
May 29 at Wembley Stadium.
</P>
<P>
   Charlton and Manchester City have already sealed the other two
promotion slots.
</P>
<P>
   Watford and Sheffield Wednesday have been relegated to the first
division next season.
</P>
<P>
   The third relegated team will be decided Sunday with either
Wimbledon or Bradford going down. Wimbledon faces Southampton, and
Bradford plays Liverpool.
</P>
<P>
France
</P>
<P>
   Lyon held out for a 2-2 draw at Montpellier to join champion
Monaco and runner-up Paris Saint-Germain as the three French clubs
in next season's Champions League.
</P>
<P>
   Marseille rallied to tie Sedan 2-2 and stay in the first
division, sending Nancy down to the second division.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
