<DATE_TIME> 2000-05-13 18:31 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Flyers' Primeau May Play Game 1  </HEADLINE>
By TOM CANAVAN
<TEXT>
<P>
   PHILADELPHIA (AP) -- In a season marked by cancer, concussions
and turmoil, the Philadelphia Flyers got some optimistic news on
the eve of the Eastern Conference finals against New Jersey.
</P>
<P>
   Center Keith Primeau, who suffered a concussion in Game 6 of the
Pittsburgh series, practiced with the Flyers on Saturday, and there
is an outside chance he will play in Game 1 of the best-of-seven
series that starts Sunday at the First Union Center.
</P>
<P>
   Before Saturday, it appeared that the earliest Primeau would
return would be for Game 2 on Tuesday.
</P>
<P>
   However, he skated for 20 minutes on his own on Saturday and
then talked to trainer John Worley. He got the OK to skate with the
team for some drills and appeared to have no problems.
</P>
<P>
   ''I've been feeling really good,'' said Primeau, who had one of
the biggest goals of the season for the Flyers when he scored in
the fifth overtime of Game 4 with the Penguins to even the series.
''Every day I've been feeling better, and that's a positive.''
</P>
<P>
   Dr. Gary Dorshimer, the Flyers' team physician, will probably
have the final say on when Primeau can return.
</P>
<P>
   Primeau does not expect a final decision to be made until just
before game time, scheduled for 3 p.m. EDT.
</P>
<P>
   If Primeau does come back, it would be a lift the Flyers, who
have battled adversity all season.
</P>
<P>
   Coach Roger Neilson had to take a leave of absence on Feb. 20
because of a battle with multiple myeloma, a form of cancer. He was
replaced by assistant Craig Ramsay.
</P>
<P>
   Superstar center Eric Lindros missed the last 14 games of the
season with a Grade 2 concussion, and then he was stripped of his
captain's title for criticizing the team's doctors.
</P>
<P>
   There have also been other little problems that have now been
forgotten since the team got its act together under Ramsay and won
the Atlantic Division with a late-season rush and an accompanying
swoon by the Devils.
</P>
<P>
   Ramsay thought Primeau, injured in a collision with Pittsburgh
defenseman Bob Boughner, skated well.
</P>
<P>
   ''He was well enough after his own skate that he thought he
would participate in some of our drills, and he handled himself
well,'' Ramsay said. ''I haven't spoken to him since he came off.
It was encouraging.''
</P>
<P>
   Still, Ramsay knows Primeau might not be ready on Sunday.
</P>
<P>
   ''It's always nice to have one of your top guys playing,''
Ramsay said. ''But we emphasize the team and if we have to play
without him, we will.''
</P>
<P>
   The Devils, who beat the Flyers 4-1 in the season series,
weren't surprised by the possible change in Primeau's status.
</P>
<P>
   ''I didn't (see what) happened to him,'' Devils goalie Martin
Brodeur said after the Devils finished an hour-long practice
Saturday afternoon. ''I just know he got hurt a little bit. I guess
he's fine. We never really counted this guy out. We had him in all
the meetings. For us, he is part of the Flyers. We'll see if he
plays tomorrow.''
</P>
<P>
   Larry Robinson, who has turned around the slumping Devils after
replacing Robbie Ftorek as coach with eight games left in the
regular season, is expecting a great series no matter who plays for
the Flyers.
</P>
<P>
   ''You have to give that team a lot of credit,'' Robinson said.
''They were 11 or 12 points behind us at one point, and they came
through and won the division. That says a lot about their team and
their character, and even more so after what they have gone
through. That is a good team we are playing against. We are only
kidding ourselves if we think they are not.
</P>
<P>
   ''They are tenacious workers, they hunt the puck down and they
are playing with a purpose now,'' he added.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
