<HEADLINE> Ducklings Rescued in England  </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
   LONDON (AP) -- A family of ducks caused a flap at Parliament on
Saturday when seven ducklings fell down a ventilation shaft into
the Underground subway, halting trains briefly and bringing
firefighters to the rescue.
</P>
<P>
   The drama began when a mother duck set off across the House of
Commons courtyard with seven young waddling in her wake. Crossing
the grill of an Underground ventilation shaft, the ducklings
slipped through the cracks, the London Fire Brigade said.
</P>
<P>
   The mother duck quacked frantically on the cobbled stones of the
Carriage Gate entrance to Parliament, and six firefighters rushed
to the scene.
</P>
<P>
   A House of Commons window cleaner lowered himself into
ventilation shaft, and found that three of the ducklings had died
in the 75-foot fall, fireman Graham Barber said
</P>
<P>
   But the four survivors wandered onto a subway platform at
Westminster station, where trains were brought briefly to a
standstill as animal protection officials rounded the ducklings up.
</P>
<P>
   ''The survivors are quite healthy,'' said animal ambulance
driver Roy Blackburn. ''Apparently ducks have been living in the
House of Commons for 20 years.''
</P>
<P>
   During the drama, the mother duck disappeared. Rescuers said the
surviving ducklings would be cared for at Egham Swan Center in
Surrey.
</P>
<P>
   A parliamentary observer said that members of Parliament often
brought in dry bread for the ducks ''like kindergarten children,''
and would mourn their passing.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
