<DATE_TIME> 2000-05-13 18:45 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Stasi Files Taken From Journalist  </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
   BERLIN (AP) -- German authorities have confiscated thousands of
East German spy agency bugging records that had been secretly kept
by a journalist, the federal prosecutors' office said Saturday.
</P>
<P>
   Der Spiegel newsmagazine reported that the files from the
so-called Stasi contained the results of phone taps and other
electronic surveillance on West German politicians, including
now-Chancellor Gerhard Schroeder. The 20,000 pages were the largest
stash of Stasi files in private hands, the magazine said.
</P>
<P>
   Prosecutors are investigating possible charges of revealing
state secrets against Paul Limbach, a Bonn-based journalist who is
an editor at Focus newsmagazine, spokeswoman Eva Schuebel said.
</P>
<P>
   The files had been confiscated last Wednesday, Schuebel said.
She said after a search turned up some of the files, Limbach handed
over the rest.
</P>
<P>
   Limbach told Der Spiegel he had given ex-Chancellor Helmut Kohl
the files that related to him in 1990. However, Kohl told the
magazine that he could not recall ever seeing the records.
</P>
<P>
   Stasi files on former West German politicians have figured into
the scandal around Kohl's Christian Democratic party over its
illegal financial practices.
</P>
<P>
   A parliament committee investigating bribery charges during his
16 years in power has decided it won't use Stasi files as evidence.
But lawmakers say they will still ask witnesses questions based on
media reports about the files.
</P>
<P>
   Some speculate the files could reveal Kohl had knowledge about
the system of off-the-books payoffs and secret accounts run by his
party, something he has vehemently denied.
</P>
<P>
   A federal agency based in the same Berlin building that was
Stasi headquarters is now in charge of the files, and those who
were the target of the Stasi's spying can request to see their own
files. The head of the agency has said Kohl will get no special
treatment on his request to see his files.
</P>
<P>
   Limbach had received the files from Stasi officers that went to
work for the German counter-intelligence agency after the two
Germanys were reunited in 1990, Der Spiegel said.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
