<HEADLINE> Golden Missile Wins Pimlico Special  </HEADLINE>
By DAVID GINSBURG
<TEXT>
<P>
   BALTIMORE (AP) -- Golden Missile took the lead at the top of the
stretch and jockey Kent Desormeaux guided him home for a surprise
victory in the $750,000 Pimlico Special on Saturday.
</P>
<P>
   In beating a talented field of older horses, including Lemon
Drop Kid and Cat Thief, Golden Missile stayed just off the pace
before moving past Pleasant Breeze and winning by two lengths.
</P>
<P>
   Lemon Drop Kid, who won the 1999 Belmont Stakes and the Travers,
was third, followed by Almutawakel, Cat Thief, favored K One King,
Budroyale and Allen's Oop.
</P>
<P>
   ''I was quite confident all the way around,'' Desormeaux, who
won the Kentucky Derby last Saturday aboard Fusaichi Pegasus, said.
''He made the lead without being asked, and when I asked him to run
he just exploded.''
</P>
<P>
   Golden Missile, a 5-year-old chestnut colt, earned $450,000 for
the win. He covered the 1 3/16 miles at Pimlico in 1:54 3-5, and
paid $11.40, $7.20 and $4.60.
</P>
<P>
   Pleasant Breeze paid $23 and $13, and Lemon Drop Kid returned
$4.40 to show.
</P>
<P>
   Cat Thief, trained by D. Wayne Lukas, rattled the gate open
before the race. Once the gates opened for good, the colt grabbed
the lead and held onto it until Golden Missile blew past him at the
top of the stretch. Cat Thief faded to fifth.
</P>
<P>
   The race featured several participants in last month's Oaklawn
Handicap, when K One King defeated Almutawakel, Cat Thief,
Budroyale, Allen's Oop and Pleasant Breeze. The addition of the
talented Lemon Drop Kid, as well as Golden Missile, only enhanced
the field.
</P>
<P>
   Lemon Drop Kid, with new jockey Edgar Prado aboard, was forced
to the outside early but still had a shot before Golden Missile
made his move.
</P>
<P>
   Lemon Drop Kid carried a highweight of 120 pounds. The betting
favorite in the morning line, he went off as the second-favorite.
</P>
</TEXT>
