<BODY>
<HEADLINE> ANC To Help With Zimbabwe Elections  </HEADLINE>
By RAVI NESSMAN
<TEXT>
<P>
   PRETORIA, South Africa (AP) -- President Thabo Mbeki said
Saturday his African National Congress party has sent a delegation
to Zimbabwe to work with the ruling party and the opposition to
ensure that coming parliamentary elections are free and fair.
</P>
<P>
   In a wide-ranging interview with foreign journalists a week
ahead of his first state visit to Washington, Mbeki talked about
investment in Africa, his controversial stance on AIDS and the
crisis in Zimbabwe, where at least 18 people have been killed in
recent political violence.
</P>
<P>
   An ANC delegation was sent to Zimbabwe this weekend to hear the
opposition's concerns and to present them to the ruling party in an
effort to find a way to hold fair elections, Mbeki said.
International election monitors must also be part of the equation,
he said.
</P>
<P>
   ''We should try and encourage as many people as possible --
organizations, institutions -- to send observers to Zimbabwe as
early as possible ... to observe all elements of the election
process,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   Mbeki has shied away from criticizing Zimbabwean President
Robert Mugabe, whom the opposition blames for sparking the violence
and the occupations of white-owned farms in order to gain support
for his party -- and to intimidate the opposition -- ahead of the
elections.
</P>
<P>
   Mbeki has focused his public statements about Zimbabwe on the
importance of land reform in a country where a handful of whites
own one-third of the productive farmland.
</P>
<P>
   On Saturday, Mbeki said he had told Mugabe privately that the
violence must end, the rule of law must be restored and free and
fair elections must be conducted. In return, he would mediate with
Britain -- Zimbabwe's former colonial master -- and international
institutions to ensure Zimbabwe gets the funds to embark on a
meaningful program of land reform.
</P>
<P>
   ''This is our neighbor. We have to live with the Zimbabweans
forever here,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   Zimbabwe's main opposition Movement for Democratic Change has
said fair elections will be impossible after months of violent
intimidation by militant members of Mugabe's ruling party. The
party announced Saturday it would begin a campaign of strikes and
civil disobedience to protest the violence.
</P>
<P>
   Mbeki is expected to be dogged with questions about his AIDS
policies during his visit to the United States, which begins May
22. He leaves the on May 26.
</P>
<P>
   In a country where an estimated 4 million people are infected
with HIV, the government has refused to finance a program to treat
pregnant mothers with the medicine AZT, which many AIDS researchers
believe greatly reduces the chances the virus will be transmitted
to the baby in childbirth.
</P>
<P>
   Mbeki has convened a panel of scientists, many of them on the
fringe of AIDS research, to discuss the efficacy of accepted AIDS
treatments and whether HIV causes AIDS.
</P>
<P>
   ''There are real, genuine scientific questions recognized by the
scientists ... and they've set up a forum so that they do address
these problems,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   Mbeki also worried that many businesses were scared to invest
money in a continent where violent conflicts tend to overshadow
positive developments.
</P>
<P>
   Mbeki advocated developing an early warning system in Africa to
alert other countries in the region to brewing conflicts before
they develop into full-blown violence.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
