<HEADLINE> AP Top News at 7 p.m. EDT  </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
 Saturday, May 13, 2000
</P>
<SUBHEAD>
Magazine Challenges No Gun Ri Story
</SUBHEAD>
<P>
   NEW YORK (AP) -- U.S. News &AMP; World Report today challenged accounts of three
U.S. veterans who told The Associated Press that they witnessed the killing of
civilians by American soldiers in the early days of the Korean War. AP said it
stood behind its story, and The New York Times reported that Army investigators
have confirmed the central finding that U.S. troops killed hundreds of refugees
in July 1950 near the hamlet of No Gun Ri. Two historians, meanwhile, told The
Washington Post that they believed that a mass killing had occurred as reported
by AP last fall.
</P>
<SUBHEAD>
Giuliani Mulling Political Future
</SUBHEAD>
<P>
   NEW YORK (AP) -- Mayor Rudolph Giuliani stepped out of the spotlight today,
canceling a campaign appearance and spending much of the day mulling his medical
options as uncertainty hung over his Senate campaign. His campaign manager said
that as of today Giuliani had not made a decision about whether to proceed with
the campaign and wouldn't do so until he had more time to consider his medical
treatment for prostate cancer. An announcement about whether the mayor plans to
stay in the race against first lady Hillary Rodham Clinton could come as soon as
tomorrow or Monday, according to a person knowledgeable about Giuliani's
discussions with political advisers who spoke on condition of anonymity.
</P>
<SUBHEAD>
Allegations Made in Sierra Leone
</SUBHEAD>
<P>
   FREETOWN, Sierra Leone (AP) -- The feared rebel leader who restarted Sierra
Leone's civil war this month has been striking illegal deals with international
diamond firms in return for military equipment and other supplies, the justice
minister said Saturday. Revolutionary United Front leader Foday Sankoh -- who
during the country's short-lived peace was put in charge of a commission
regulating mineral policy -- tried to trade or sell gems abroad for his own
enrichment and to fund his rebel movement, said the minister, Solomon Berewa,
who is also the attorney general.
</P>
<SUBHEAD>
Bush Blasts Bigotry, Education Gap
</SUBHEAD>
<P>
   PRAIRIE VIEW, Texas (AP) -- Gov. George W. Bush condemned bigotry and the
scholastic achievement gap between the nation's rich and poor students in a
commencement address today at Prairie View A&AMP;M University. ''Bigotry and
intolerance are unworthy of our country, because they go against our country's
creed -- the worth of every person as an individual,'' Bush told a crowd of
about 4,000. ''The worth of an individual is measured by our hearts and our
souls and our potential. We are measured by how we live our lives and how we
treat others,'' he said.
</P>
<SUBHEAD>
Israel Peace Talks Pass Deadline
</SUBHEAD>
<P>
   JERUSALEM (AP) -- Israeli soldiers clashed with Palestinian protesters for
the second day in a row today as Palestinian leaders accused Israel of causing
peace negotiators to miss another deadline for the outlines of a final treaty.
Demonstrations demanding the release of some 1,600 Palestinians held in Israeli
jails were slated to continue tomorrow, even as negotiators were scheduled to
meet in Jerusalem in an effort to discuss the issue.
</P>
<SUBHEAD>
N.M. Fire Looking Beatable
</SUBHEAD>
<P>
   LOS ALAMOS, N.M. (AP) -- More than a week after the National Park Service
started a blaze to remove dry brush and grass, the fire that has destroyed 260
homes and threatened the Los Alamos National Laboratory is no longer looking
invincible, and Los Alamos is beginning to come to grips with the scale of its
destruction. Most of the 25,000 people evacuated will not be allowed to return
to their homes for at least a week, although the National Guard will begin
escorting groups into Los Alamos as early as tomorrow to pick up clothes,
medicine and other essentials.
</P>
<SUBHEAD>
Blaze Remains Near Grand Canyon
</SUBHEAD>
<P>
   GRAND CANYON NATIONAL PARK, Ariz. (AP) -- More firefighting resources and
sustained calmer winds helped to prevent a 7,000-acre wildfire from spreading,
authorities said today. The size of the fire had not increased since yesterday,
when calmer winds gave firefighters a break after a blustery Wednesday and
Thursday. ''That finally gave firefighters a chance to get in there and fight
it,'' said Grand Canyon Park spokeswoman Margee Hench. The Outlet fire began
April 25 as a prescribed burn to thin out brush on about 1,500 acres.
</P>
<SUBHEAD>
76ers Defeat Pacers 92-90
</SUBHEAD>
<P>
   PHILADELPHIA (AP) -- The Philadelphia 76ers kept their season alive today
with a 92-90 victory over Indiana in a fight-marred Game 4. The Sixers still
trail 3-1 in the best-of-seven series. Travis Best missed two long jumpers in
the final seconds, including a 3-pointer as time expired that could have ended
the series. The Pacers rallied from an 18-point deficit to lead by five after
Miller and Philadelphia's Matt Geiger were ejected with 1:19 left in the third
quarter. Both are subject to suspensions for the next game Monday.
</P>
<SUBHEAD>
AP NewsBrief by ANDREW DAMPF
</SUBHEAD>
