<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Delegate Selection Angers McCain  </HEADLINE>
By DEE-ANN DURBIN
<TEXT>
<P>
   GRAND RAPIDS, Mich. (AP) -- Arizona Sen. John McCain has canceled
campaign events in Michigan because he feels people loyal to him
were slighted by the state Republican party's delegate election
this weekend, a spokesman said Saturday.
</P>
<P>
   McCain had been scheduled to appear at fund-raisers during the
upcoming week for Sen. Spence Abraham and congressional candidates
Chuck Yob and state Sen. Mike Rogers.
</P>
<P>
   But McCain spokesman Todd Harris said McCain is upset about the
party's delegate selection process.
</P>
<P>
   ''What is the point of having an election if party bosses in the
back rooms can ultimately control the outcome?'' Harris said.
</P>
<P>
   Party officials denied they did anything wrong, and insisted
their delegation to the national convention will represent that
McCain won the state's Feb. 22 primary. Under Michigan party rules,
the McCain ''delegates'' won in the primary actually amounted to
blank spaces to be filled in at the party convention.
</P>
<P>
   ''We worked long and hard to make sure this was a united
party,'' Michigan GOP spokesman Sage Eastman said.
</P>
<P>
   The spat comes less than a week after McCain endorsed his former
rival, Texas Gov. George W. Bush, for the presidency, a show of
unity many had said could help repair Michigan's divided party.
</P>
<P>
   Approximately 1,200 Republicans attended the two-day state
convention to elect delegates for the national convention in
Philadelphia this summer. McCain was to attend the convention
Friday, but couldn't due to severe weather.
</P>
<P>
   Michigan has 58 delegates, including three from each of its 16
congressional districts and 10 at-large delegates.
</P>
<P>
   Because McCain won in most of Michigan's congressional districts
in the Feb. 22 primary, he had 52 delegates to six delegates for
Texas Gov. George Bush.
</P>
<P>
   When McCain suspended his campaign in March, he agreed to give
six of his at-large delegates to Bush. But under an agreement
signed by McCain, Gov. John Engler, Michigan Republican Party
Chairman Rusty Hills and state Sen. John Schwarz, R-Battle Creek,
all of McCain's remaining 46 delegate slots were to go to people
who ''worked for the election of John McCain.''
</P>
<P>
   Instead, many of the 46 ''McCain delegates'' elected Friday
night actually were longtime Bush supporters, including Hills,
state Senate Majority Leader Dan DeGrow, R-Port Huron, and state
House Speaker Chuck Perricone, R-Kalamazoo.
</P>
<P>
   ''By not keeping their commitment, Governor Engler and chairman
Hills are sending the following message: the Republican party in
Michigan is a closed shop -- reformers and newcomers need not
join,'' said McCain political director John Weaver in a prepared
statement. ''This does not bode well for our party in the general
election in an important battleground state like Michigan.''
</P>
<P>
   Hills, who was elected as a delegate in the 8th congressional
District along with two other Bush supporters, said he should be
elected for the sake of party unity. Three delegates supported by
McCain were elected as alternates for that district.
</P>
<P>
   ''We had a great convention. ... We elected a great slate of
McCain delegates for the convention in Philadelphia,'' said Engler
spokesman John Truscott.
</P>
<P>
   Harris said in the end, only about 15 McCain activists won
seats, even though 46 will be listed, technically, as McCain
delegates at the convention.
</P>
<P>
   ''It doesn't help party unity and it's a slap in the face of
party unity,'' Harris said.
</P>
<P>
   Eastman said he couldn't confirm the number of McCain supporters
who became delegates. ''All along, we didn't really know who the
McCain people were and who the Bush people were,'' Eastman said.
</P>
<P>
   Some convention delegates said they were unaware there had been
problems.
</P>
<P>
   ''We went by the book in the 16th District,'' said Jo Bach, a
McCain volunteer from Carleton who will attend the national
convention as an alternate delegate. ''I'm very proud to be
McCain's delegate. I will vote and campaign for Bush, but McCain
had my vote in the primary.
</P>
<P>
   ------
</P>
<P>
   On the Net: http://www.MichGOP.org.
</P>
<P>
   McCain's Web site: http://www.straighttalkamerica.com.
</P>
</TEXT>
