<DATE_TIME> 2000-05-13 19:59 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Party Calls for Pols Resignation  </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
   MEXICO CITY (AP) -- A small Mexican opposition party said
Saturday it would ask its presidential candidate to resign, after
he called for a ''united front'' against the ruling PRI, the
government news agency Notimex reported.
</P>
<P>
   In an extraordinary session of its national assembly, the
Authentic Party of the Mexican Revolution, or PARM, voted to ask
Porfirio Munoz Ledo to step down, Notimex reported.
</P>
<P>
   The announcement came shortly after the release of the first
major poll to place Fox ahead of the ruling Institutional
Revolutionary Party, or PRI, which has governed Mexico for 71
years.
</P>
<P>
   Speaking at a news conference, Vicente Diaz Lopez, a
representative of the center-right party, said Munoz Ledo
''intended to sell the party to the extreme political right of this
country,'' by considering backing the leading opposition candidate,
Vicente Fox, of the conservative National Action Party.
</P>
<P>
   PARM plans to replace Munoz Ledo with its party's president,
Carlos Guzman Perez, Notimex reported.
</P>
<P>
   Munoz Ledo could not be reached for comment Saturday.
</P>
<P>
   On Thursday, the candidate called on all five opposition groups
to form a united front against the governing party, but he stopped
short of endorsing Fox. It is too late by law for the parties to
join a true coalition, but they can informally endorse one of the
front-runners.
</P>
<P>
   That same day, the Interior Ministry publicly accused Munoz Ledo
of trying to take over the leadership of the party he represents.
Munoz Ledo said that charge was meant to destabilize his candidacy.
</P>
<P>
   With the July 2 election less than two months away, Fox was
favored by 46.3 percent, according to a poll conducted by Zogby
International. Francisco Labastida of the PRI was favored by 41.6
percent. The margin of error was plus or minus 3.2 percentage
points.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
