<DOCNO> APW20000513.0165 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-05-13 20:12 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Authorities find potassium cyanide  </HEADLINE>
By MELANIE CARROLL
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK (AP) -- Twenty barrels of stolen potassium cyanide
turned up Saturday afternoon in the Bronx after a tipster reported
they were in plain view next to a baseball park.
</P>
<P>
   Police immediately evacuated about 75 families from the Castle
Hill neighborhood after they received the anonymous 911 call around
12:15 p.m.
</P>
<P>
   The barrels were located 10 days after a trailer went missing
from a Union County warehouse in Linden, N.J. It contained a
shipping container with the drums of potassium cyanide, destined
for Puerto Rico.
</P>
<P>
   The trailer that had been loaded with the cyanide was found
empty late Friday, without a cab or license plates, in an
industrial park in Queens in the Long Island City section.
</P>
<P>
   The orange drums were each marked with the number ''1680,'' an
industrywide number used to identify the chemical, said Officer
Joseph Pentangelo, a police spokesman.
</P>
<P>
   Investigators wearing protective suits inspected the orange
barrels -- which were laying in short grass upon their sides -- to
ensure they remained sealed, and then covered the containers until
they were removed, said Mayor Rudolph Giuliani.
</P>
<P>
   ''This is a real credit to the emergency response of the city of
New York,'' Giuliani said at a press conference near the scene.
''It could have been very dangerous. It turned out that it
wasn't.''
</P>
<P>
   Police said it was unclear how the barrels holding the deadly
chemicals arrived on Pugsley Avenue, in between Cicero and Lacombe
Avenues.
</P>
<P>
   ''Obviously the person who stole it, since they were dumped this
way, had no idea what they were taking,'' said Richard J. Sheirer,
the director of the city's Office of Emergency Management.
</P>
<P>
   Police also were unsure how long the barrels had been there
since being stolen. But neighbors weren't surprised to find
something left there.
</P>
<P>
   ''They dump stuff around here all the time,'' said Jesus
Raimundi, who lives in Pugsley Avenue. ''I've been fighting if for
13 years.''
</P>
<P>
   The barrels were removed around 4:15 p.m., and residents were
allowed to return to their homes. By that time, a group of young
men were already playing baseball on the field.
</P>
<P>
   The FBI confiscated the barrels. Federal agents and the NYPD
will continue investigating.
</P>
<P>
   ''The No. 1 focus has been the public safety,'' said FBI
spokesman Joe Valiquette. ''The focus now is to find out who is
responsible for the theft.''
</P>
<P>
   The World Health Organization says potassium cyanide could be
used by terrorists.
</P>
<P>
   ''We don't believe it's terrorists,'' Sheirer had said early
Saturday morning.
</P>
<P>
   Robert J. Cordier, of the FBI's New York office, said the
federal agency was involved in the investigation only because it
involved an interstate theft.
</P>
<P>
   ''Right now, we don't have anything to indicate to us that it is
something like that,'' Cordier said when asked whether he thought
terrorists might be involved in the theft.
</P>
<P>
   Potassium cyanide is used in electroplating, a process employed
to make silverware and jewelry, and can be fatal to anyone who
drinks or inhales it. The manmade chemical kills by preventing
oxygen from reaching vital organs.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER> AP-ES-05-13-00 2012 </TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> APW20000513.0166 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-05-13 20:20 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Willey on Verge of Bankruptcy  </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
   RICHMOND, Va. (AP) -- Kathleen Willey, who accused President
Clinton of an unwanted sexual advance at the White House in 1993,
is hundreds of thousands of dollars in debt and likely will be
declared insolvent, a federal bankruptcy court official says.
</P>
<P>
   Willey voluntarily filed for protection under federal bankruptcy
laws last month, listing debts of more than $700,000 and assets of
$19,011, primarily household furnishings, a car and a wedding ring.
</P>
<P>
   ''It's my impression at this time that we'll be in a no-asset
bankruptcy case,'' U.S. Bankruptcy Trustee J. Stephen Bus said
Friday at a meeting of creditors.
</P>
<P>
   Clinton denied Willey's allegation. A federal judge ruled in
March that the president had violated privacy laws by releasing
Willey's letters to him to undermine her credibility.
</P>
<P>
   Her money trouble stemmed from nearly $275,000 her late husband,
Ed Willey, embezzled from a client, according to court papers. Ed
Willey killed himself in 1993.
</P>
<P>
   Ed Willey, a real estate lawyer who made some bad investments in
the late 1980s, was hundreds of thousands of dollars in debt to the
Internal Revenue Service.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER> AP-NY-05-13-00 2020 </TRAILER>
</DOC>
