<DOCNO> APW20000513.0167 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-05-13 20:22 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Performing Magic Win Illinois Derby  </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
   CICERO, Ill. (AP) -- Performing Magic overtook favored Country
Only in the final strides and won the $500,000 Illinois Derby by a
head at Sportsman's Park on Saturday.
</P>
<P>
   Performing Magic, ridden by Shane Sellers for the first time ,
won the Derby Trial in his last start but went off as the second
choice in the nine-horse field.
</P>
<P>
   Trainer by Alex Hassinger Jr., Performing Magic won $300,000 for
owner Prince Ahmed Salman of Riyadh in Saudi Arabia.
</P>
<P>
   Sellers, winning his first Illinois Derby, said the colt is a
stalker. ''I knew he could be close to the pace.''
</P>
<P>
   And when Country Only, who led from the start, began tiring in
the stretch, Performing Magic had enough finishing kick to get the
win.
</P>
<P>
   Performing Magic covered the 1 1-8 miles in 1:50.86.
</P>
<P>
   Country Coast, who went off at odds of 36-1, was third, ahead of
Kombat Kat.
</P>
<P>
   Performing Magic paid $6.20, $3.20 and $2.80 in winning for the
fourth time in 12 career starts. The 3-year-old colt, who began
racing in England, now has two wins, a second and a third in four
starts in the United States.
</P>
</TEXT>
