<DOCNO> APW20000513.0168 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-05-13 20:29 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Americans Sweep Synchronized Titles  </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
   FORT LAUDERDALE, Fla. (AP) -- David Pichler and Mark Ruiz won the
synchronized platform final and P.J. Bogart and Chris Devine
captured the synchronized 3-meter event Saturday at the FINA-USA
Diving Grand Prix.
</P>
<P>
   Pichler and Ruiz scored 301.26 points to 298.50 for Mathew Helm
and Robert Newbery of Australia. Ivan Bondarenko and Alisher Seitov
of Kazakhstan were third with 234.78.
</P>
<P>
   Pichler, of Fort Lauderdale, and Ruiz, of Orlando, just began
working together at last month's indoor nationals.
</P>
<P>
   ''We're still ironing out some wrinkles,'' Pichler said. ''It
would be nice if we both end up making the (Olympic) team and doing
it together, if we get a little more chance to work on it we should
end up doing real well.
</P>
<P>
   ''We seem to be making some little stupid mistakes, I know I am,
anyway. We didn't do near as well as we could have.''
</P>
<P>
   Bogart and Devine have worked together for three years, but
don't get in a lot of practice time because Bogart lives in Eden
Prairie, Minn., while Devine resides in Lighthouse Point, Fla. They
have twice combined for titles, but not at international events.
</P>
<P>
   ''We've never won anything at the international level, so this
is kind of a nice thing to do,'' said Devine, the 1994 Big 10
Conference champion in 3-meter diving at Penn State. ''When we got
up there on the board, he looked at me and said, 'It's a contest.'
In other words, we've got a chance at this.''
</P>
<P>
   They won a very close event, scoring 288.90 points to 288.78 for
Germany's Stefan Ahrens and Alexander Mesch and 288.60 for China's
Wang Tianling and Yu Zhuocheng.
</P>
<P>
   In the only women's final Saturday, Russians Vera Ilyina and
Yulia Pakhalina won the synchronized 3-meter final with 297.75
points.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
