<HEADLINE> Obituaries in the News  </HEADLINE>
By The Associated PressDonald George Bollinger
<TEXT>
<P>
   RACELAND, La. (AP) -- Donald George Bollinger, the founder of
Bollinger Shipyards Inc. and an influential Republican in Louisiana
politics, died Saturday of heart failure. He was 85.
</P>
<P>
   Bollinger played a key role in the Louisiana Republican Party's
resurgence in the 1970s, served as chairman of the party, and was
secretary of public safety and corrections under Gov. Dave Treen in
the early 1980s.
</P>
<P>
   Bollinger, a machinist, started the family company in 1946 in a
backyard shop. Today, the company has eight shipyards throughout
south Louisiana.
</P>
<P>
   As a political activist, Bollinger helped to build the state GOP
from a virtual nonentity into a powerful force.
</P>
<P>
   The work culminated in 1979, when Treen was elected Louisiana's
first Republican governor since Reconstruction. Treen said Saturday
that he would miss Bollinger.
</P>
<P>
   ''I'm deeply saddened by his passing,'' Treen said. ''He was a
man of integrity and honesty.''
</P>
<P>
   Bollinger served as chairman of the Louisiana Republican Party
between 1984 and 1986. He retired from overseeing the shipyards in
1989.
Harry Volk
</P>
<P>
   LOS ANGELES (AP) -- Harry J. Volk, an innovative leader who
successfully led Union Bank through recession, died Friday. He was
94.
</P>
<P>
   Born in Trenton, N.J., Volk earned business and law degrees at
Rutgers University.
</P>
<P>
   He divided his long career between Prudential Insurance Co. and
Union Bank and left a lasting imprint on the insurance and banking
industries.
</P>
<P>
   When he arrived in Los Angeles in 1947, he was the youngest vice
president in Prudential history at 41. He helpd create the
company's first regional home office as part of the
decentralization of the mammoth company he helped engineer.
</P>
<P>
   Volk's work at Prudential led to his 1957 recruitment as
chairman and chief executive officer of Union Bank, where for 23
years he led the bank through a period in which banks across the
country were surrounded by loan defaults. He retired from the bank
in 1980.
</P>
<P>
   Volk also was a founder of the Los Angeles Music Center and Los
Angeles County Museum of the Art.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER> AP-NY-05-13-00 2110 </TRAILER>
