<DOCNO> APW20000513.0175 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-05-13 21:34 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Bill would ask those registering vehicles for eye money  </HEADLINE>
By JENNIFER JORDAN
<TEXT>
<P>
   ALBANY, N.Y. (AP) -- State Sen. Kemp Hannon knows firsthand how
troublesome correcting children's vision problems can be.
</P>
<P>
   When his twin daughters were faring poorly in school, it took
weeks of conversation with teachers and the 9-year-old girls before
the adults realized faulty eyesight may be to blame.
</P>
<P>
   Waiting to see an ophthalmologist required another six weeks. If
the children were even younger with less-developed communication
skills, a resolution may have taken longer.
</P>
<P>
   ''The school didn't figure it out,'' said Hannon, chairman of
the Senate's health committee. ''The statistic is 80 percent of
kids under 6 are not being screened for visual difficulties.''
</P>
<P>
   Hannon has proposed a bill to raise money specially for
youngsters with eye problems through donations by people who are
registering vehicles in New York state. By checking a box on
registration applications, drivers would be able to donate $1, the
measure said.
</P>
<P>
   Money from the fund would be used for vision tests, protective
eyeware and eyesight education for people who care for young
children.
</P>
<P>
   The bill is sponsored in the state Assembly by health committee
Chairman Richard Gottfried, a Manhattan Democrat.
</P>
<P>
   ''The thought was that now that we're doing earlier screening
for hearing problems, we should do the same for vision,'' Hannon
said.
</P>
<P>
   Curtailing amblyopia, or ''lazy eye,'' is the program's main
goal. The condition, which is diagnosed in 2 percent to 3 percent
of children who are screened, is from misalignment or crossed eyes
or one eye that focuses better than the other, according to Prevent
Blindness America. If untreated, the weaker eye may become
functionally blind.
</P>
<P>
   The fund would also provide protective eyewear for children.
Damage to the ''strong eye'' of a child who has amblyopia could
cause blindness, said Rosemary Clemens, CEO of Prevent Blindness
New York.
</P>
<P>
   Florida, Texas, Ohio and Utah are among the states with programs
similar to the Hannon-Gottfried bill.
</P>
<P>
   A similar donation checkoff box is offered on state income tax
forms, but this would be the first time driver registration forms
would be used.
</P>
<P>
   The popularity of donations in tax forms varies. So far this
year, $43,563 had been donated to the Gift to Lake Placid from tax
refunds. The Gift to Breast Cancer has fared much better -- bringing
in $433,737.
</P>
<P>
   New Yorkers can also donate to the Return a Gift to Wildlife
Fund and the Missing and Exploited Children Fund on their tax
returns.
</P>
<P>
   While praising the bill's intent, Clemens said the bill should
also include donation checkoffs on drivers' license renewals,
instead of just vehicle registration.
</P>
<P>
   She also objected to a provision in the bill, drafted in part
and lobbied for by the New York State Ophthalmological Society,
that would allow only licensed professionals to join an advisory
council to help manage the ''save our sight'' fund. Prevent
Blindness, a nonprofit that screens children at day-care programs
and Head Start programs and has support groups for people with eye
problems, would not be included in that definition.
</P>
<P>
   ''By leaving out other groups, that to me is unacceptable and
doesn't cover the spectrum of people who supply these services,''
she said.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER> AP-ES-05-13-00 2134 </TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> APW20000513.0176 </DOCNO>
