<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-05-13 23:08 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> President Lauds 'Million Mom March'  </HEADLINE>
By LARRY MARGASAK
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON (AP) -- Seven-year-old Heather McDonnell used her
show-and tell time to speak about Sunday's ''Million Mom March''
for gun control. Lorrain Franklin-Taylor, a gospel singer, wrote a
song for the Mother's Day rally. Spring Venema and her daughters
sold homemade muffins for bus fare.
</P>
<P>
   For thousands of Americans, the rallies in Washington and 70
other communities nationwide are a call to action for registration
of handguns and licensing of their owners. For others, the events
will be personal memorials to loved ones lost to bullets.
</P>
<P>
   That is the case for Heather, whose father was shot to death;
Franklin-Taylor, whose twin sons were gunned down together; and
Venema, whose father-in-law was killed with a gun.
</P>
<P>
   ''It will be the greatest Mother's Day of my life,'' said
Venema, who is from Otsego, Mich. She planned to march with her
daughters, ages 18 and 22; the three raised bus fare with their
weekly ''Million Mom Muffin'' Mondays.
</P>
<P>
   Franklin-Taylor was to participate in a rally in Oakland, where
her twin 22-year-old sons, Obadiah and Albade, were gunned down
while trying to start Obadiah's stalled car.
</P>
<P>
   The day of the killing, the gospel singer and teacher from
Hayward, Calif., was speaking at an elementary school's
African-American history event. ''I was feeling so good,'' she
said. ''The next morning my youngest son, Greg, called. He said,
'Stop what you're doing and pray for strength.'''
</P>
<P>
   ''We're going to make a commitment, not just drown in our
tears,'' she said. Franklin-Taylor intended to perform the song she
wrote. The chorus goes: ''It's time to take a stand. It's time to
take a stand today.''
</P>
<P>
   President Clinton praised the ''Million Mom March'' in his
weekly radio address Saturday, telling Americans the pro-gun lobby
''is no match for America's moms. But our nationwide fight won't be
over tomorrow, no matter how many march.''
</P>
<P>
   While not everyone in the march will have a personal story of
grief, most have more experience as soccer moms and car pool
organizers than as demonstrators.
</P>
<P>
   ''It's important enough for us to go a little bit beyond our
boundaries,'' said Joy Livingston, of Plainwell, Mich., who
responded to an ad in her church bulletin and ended up as her
state's coordinator. She has never demonstrated before.
</P>
<P>
   Joan Gold, a state coordinator from New York City, said she
''always wanted to go to demonstrations against the war in Vietnam
but I never made it. I always regretted it. This is my Vietnam.''
</P>
<P>
   Also set to demonstrate Sunday near the Washington Monument were
pro-gun supporters. The sponsor, Second Amendment Sisters, says the
''Million Mom March'' does not speak for all mothers.
</P>
<P>
   One such mother is Suzanna Gratia Hupp, a Texas state legislator
whose parents were killed when a gunman drove his pickup into a
cafeteria in Killeen, Texas, and killed 23 people, including her
parents.
</P>
<P>
   Hupp, a mother of two young sons, said she would have had a
clear shot to stop the shooter, but her handgun was 150 feet away
under the passenger seat of her car.
</P>
<P>
   The ''Million Mom March'' organizers want uniform handgun
control laws that would include licensing and registration, longer
waiting periods, a one-gun-a-month purchase limit, and child safety
standards.
</P>
<P>
   Second Amendment Sisters contends gun control increases violent
crime by shifting the balance of power to criminals and disarming
helpless victims.
</P>
<P>
   Heather McDonnell's father was shot to death in July after he
got into an argument in a bar in the New York City borough of
Queens.
</P>
<P>
   ''She gave fliers (about the march) to other kids in the
classroom'' for show-and-tell, said her mother, Martha McDonnell --
who was so depressed she would not come out of her house except to
take her daughter to and from school.
</P>
<P>
   That changed when a crossing guard gave her a flier about the
march. She got in touch with Gold, the New York coordinator, who
told her to ''go outside, do something.'' She heeded the advice and
was coming to the Washington rally with Heather and 17-year-old son
Mitchell. ''If this continues, I'm going to be there to the end,''
she said.
</P>
<P>
   Victoria Swain, of Charleston, W.Va., attended her last
demonstration in 1972, against the Vietnam War. She read about the
march in a magazine and became her state's coordinator. The mother
of a 3-year-old son, Swain said the Columbine shootings made her
feel ''like the world had gone crazy.''
</P>
<P>
   Deborah Louria, of North Oakland, Calif., the Bay Area
coordinator, learned of the march from a parenting site on the
Internet. Mothers involved in the movement in her area ''meet one
another between 9 and midnight in cyberspace ... after the kids are
tucked into bed.''
</P>
<P>
   ------
</P>
<P>
   On the Net: http://www.millionmommarch.com
</P>
<P>
   National Rifle Association: http://www.nra.org
</P>
<P>
   Second Amendment Sisters: www.sas-aim.org
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
