<HEADLINE> Angels' Mercker In Stable Condition  </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
   ANAHEIM, Calif. (AP) -- Anaheim pitcher Kent Mercker was under
observation in intensive care but in stable condition Saturday
night, two days after being taken to the hospital with bleeding in
his brain.
</P>
<P>
   In a brief statement, the Angels said the left-hander was
''feeling better and resting comfortably.''
</P>
<P>
   Team trainer Ned Bergert, who visited Mercker on Saturday, found
him in a much better, more alert mood than he had the day before.
</P>
<P>
   ''He was in good spirits, joking around,'' Bergert said.
</P>
<P>
   Julie Mercker arrived from the family's Ohio home to join her
husband, who is expected to continue undergoing neurological tests
in an effort to determine the cause of the bleeding.
</P>
<P>
   Mercker threw 30 pitches against Texas on Thursday night in his
second start of the season before sinking to one knee and leaving
under his own power, complaining of headaches and dizziness.
</P>
<P>
   Mercker, 32, was hospitalized that night.
</P>
<P>
   John Kusske, head of neurologic surgery at UC-Irvine Medical
Center, said test results indicated there was bleeding within the
brain. An origin was not immediately determined.
</P>
<P>
   The Angels said there was no word on when Mercker might leave
the hospital or when a decision would be made about his ability to
continue playing.
</P>
<P>
   The 12-year veteran, who pitched a no-hitter for Atlanta on
April 8, 1994, at Los Angeles, is 0-1 with a 5.16 ERA.
</P>
</TEXT>
