<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-05-13 23:22 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Severe weather snaps trees, floods backyards and roadways  </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	   ALBANY, N.Y. (AP) -- Fast-moving thunderclouds shrouded most of
the state Saturday afternoon in drenching blasts of wind and rain,
flooding already swollen central New York waterways and spinning
into tornado threats in the Mohawk Valley further east.
</P>
<P>
   ''It just got dark as night and started to rain real hard,''
said Skip Hellmig, a senior pastor at the Oneida Methodist Church.
''We had a wedding going on and I told people that if the lights go
out, just be prepared to play it by ear.''
</P>
<P>
   The storm's most concentrated punch was at Herkimer County,
where creeks spilled over their banks, sealing off roadways and
washing away a bridge. More than 300 volunteers redirected traffic,
bailed out basements and cleared debris.
</P>
<P>
   In Utica, where whole sections of the city were left under a
pool of water, Mayor Edward A. Hanna mulled declaring a state of
emergency.
</P>
<P>
   ''It's just impossible to take care of it all. We can't possibly
have enough manpower for the problems we've got,'' Hanna said.
</P>
<P>
   Manhole covers started ''blowing off'' because the city's sewers
could not accommodate so much water, Utica Police Lt. Sherman Jones
said.
</P>
<P>
   A house was damaged when a tree was blown onto its roof. A short
time later, a reinforced garage door was damaged by wind and trees
and electrical wires were blown to the ground. The National Weather
Service reported mud slides in Sauquoit and in Marathon, Cortland
County, according to age report by the Weather Service.
</P>
<P>
   Police and fire officials said the flooding took a heavy toll on
the region's transportation infrastructure, damaging bridges,
roadways and train tracks. In Utica alone, Hanna said the damage
would cost ''several hundred thousand dollars'' to repair.
</P>
<P>
   A bridge on Route 69 between Yorkville and Whitesboro was
ordered closed because the Sauquoit Creek had spilled over the top
of it, hiding it from view. Another bridge spanning the creek also
was closed.
</P>
<P>
   ''We have to wait for the water to go down and the light to come
up so we can inspect them before we can open them,'' state
Transportation Department Regional Director Frank Gerace said.
</P>
<P>
   City of Sherrill firefighters Saturday afternoon rescued a woman
from her trailer home, flooded by rainwater on its way down a hill.
</P>
<P>
   Patricia Roberts' home of 21 years at 3770 Graves Road looked
like an island in the middle of a raging river of brown,
foul-smelling water.
</P>
<P>
   ''I noticed it was coming, but I didn't think it was going to be
that bad,'' Roberts told the Utica Observer-Dispatch.
</P>
<P>
   Forecasters said they received several unconfirmed reports that
tornadoes had touched down in Vernon, 16 miles west of Utica, with
others saying funnel clouds had been spotted in nearby Deerfield.
National Weather Service radar images also showed what looked to be
tornadoes, but those reports could not be verified Saturday, said
Susan Faust, a Weather Service meteorologist in Binghamton.
</P>
<P>
   Forecasters also spotted the beginnings of circular-motion
clouds in Montgomery County west of Schenectady, sending people to
basements to wait out what appeared poised to develop into a
tornado.
</P>
<P>
   In the Rensselaer County town of Hoosick, a lightning blast is
believed to have started a hoad damage in Buffalo and the along the Niagara
coast, with reports of fallen trees and wind damage and flood
warnings extending into Saturday evening.
</P>
<P>
   The round of showers and thunderstorms broke out along a cold
front stretching from the Great Lakes to the Gulf Coast, the same
cold front that produced widespread power outages across the
southern Plains, central Mississippi Valley and upper Midwest.
</P>
<P>
   One person was killed when a tornado touched down Friday evening
in Texas, about 60 miles south of Dallas. In St. Nazianz, Wis.,
straight-line wind blowing at up to 110 mph and baseball-size hail
injured several people Friday night, local officials said. At least
two tornadoes were reported during the night in southern Illinois,
and storms around Chicago caused flight delays and cancellations.
</P>
<P>
   Storms had largely cleared New York state by midnight Saturday,
with forecasters predicting a kinder, gentler Mother's Day.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
