<DATE_TIME> 2000-05-13 23:39 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Notes From Saturday's Games  </HEADLINE>
By The Associated PressAMERICAN LEAGUE:
Yankees-Tigers:
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK: LHP Andy Pettitte lasted 4 2-3 innings against the
Tigers. It marked the first time he's failed to go at least five
innings this year. ... Tino Martinez was 4-for-7 in the first two
games at Detroit this weekend. His 2-for-4 effort Saturday was his
team-leading 13th multi-hit game of the season. ... The Yankees are
2-6 at Detroit the last two seasons but have won 29 of their last
40 games overall against the Tigers.
</P>
<P>
   DETROIT: The Tigers won Saturday despite a tying a season high
with three errors, including two by 3B Dean Palmer. Only one of the
Yankees' three runs was earned, and Detroit has now allowed 23
unearned runs this season. ... Juan Encarnacion was 1-for-5 and has
hit safely in 30 of 34 games this season. He's the only Tiger who's
played every game. ... RHP Jeff Weaver has a 2.55 ERA in five
starts at Comerica Park.
Royals-Indians:
</P>
<P>
   KANSAS CITY: Ricky Bottalico is 3-for-7 in save situations after
blowing his fourth when Cleveland rallied to win 7-6 win in 12
innings Saturday. But unlike his previous three blown saves, the
Royals didn't bail him out by winning this time. ... OF Todd
Dunwoody, who severely sprained his right ankle during a spring
game against the Indians in Florida, began a 20-day rehab
assignment at Triple-A Omaha. ... Before Cleveland rallied in the
bottom of the 12th, Kansas City was threatening to win for the 11th
time this season in its final at-bat. The Royals won just 12 games
in their final at-bat the entire 1999 season.
</P>
<P>
   CLEVELAND: OF Manny Ramirez is batting .420 (21-for-50) with
five homers and 16 RBIs during his 12-game hitting streak. He
picked up an RBI in his ninth straight game Saturday, matching Al
Rosen's club record set from May 15-23, 1954. ... Closer Steve
Karsay pitched a season-high two innings in his 17th appearance,
striking out four. ... Cuban pitching prospect Danys Baez, signed
this winter to a $14 million contract, pitched seven shutout
innings for Kinston (A) in the Carolina League. He walked three and
struck out nine in improving to 2-2 with a 5.11 ERA. ... Bench
coach Grady Little, who is serving as Cleveland's manager while
Charlie Manuel recovers from colon surgery, said he expects Manuel
to visit the team in the next few days. However, Little thinks it
may still be another week before Manuel's back full-time. Manuel
was released from the hospital on Friday, one week after his colon
was reattached.
Red Sox-Orioles:
</P>
<P>
   BOSTON: When Mike Stanley, Scott Hatteberg and Donnie Sadler
homered in the eighth inning, it marked the second time this season
the Red Sox have hit three homers in an inning. Stanley, Trot Nixon
and Nomar Garciaparra homered in the same inning April 19 at
Detroit. ... Manager Jimy Williams moved Stanley from DH to first
base in the eighth inning, meaning reliever Derek Lowe had to bat.
He struck out looking. ... Hatteberg's home run was his first
extra-base hit of the year.
</P>
<P>
   BALTIMORE: For the first time this season -- and for the first
time since April 22, 1999 -- LF B.J. Surhoff did not bat third. He
was dropped to sixth, with 2B Delino DeShields replacing him in the
No. 3 spot. DeShields last batted in that position May 29, 1996
with Los Angeles. ... Starter Jason Johnson walked a career-high
six batters. ... The Orioles have dropped five straight at home.
... Before the game, the Orioles activated C Willie Morales, out
with a hyperextended left elbow, from the 15-day disabled list and
optioned him to Triple-A Rochester.
Blue Jays-Devil Rays:
</P>
<P>
   TORONTO: OF Shannon Stewart, out since April 29 with a strained
right hamstring, went 3-for-3 with a double and triple in a rehab
assignment for Class A Dunedin on Friday night. He worked out at
Tropicana Field and is expected to be activated Sunday ... Manager
Jim Fregosi, in his second season with the Blue Jays, will manage
his 2,000th game Sunday. He's also managed for the California
Angels (1978-81), Chicago White Sox (1986-88) and Philadelphia
Phillies (1993). He's sixth among active managers behind Tony La
Russa, Bobby Cox, Joe Torre, Tom Kelly and Lou Piniella.
</P>
<P>
   TAMPA BAY: LHP Mark Guthrie, obtained Friday in a trade that
sent OF Dave Martinez to the Chicago Cubs, joined the team and
36-year-old rookie reliever Jim Morris was optioned to Triple-A
Durham. OF Quinton McCracken was recalled from Durham and INF Tony
Graffanino was designated for assignment ... Tampa Bay has gone 67
games without being shut out, the longest streak in the AL ...
Dwight Gooden made the 403rd start of his career. He's sixth among
active pitchers behind Roger Clemens, Orel Hershiser, Greg Maddux,
Tom Glavine and Mike Morgan.
Twins-White Sox:
</P>
<P>
   MINNESOTA: Distracted? Apparently not Twins third baseman Corey
Koskie, who had four hits Friday night, including a game-winning
single. Koskie's wife, Shannon, is back in Minneapolis where she
was due to deliver their child last Thursday. ... Twins manager Tom
Kelly, who has held the post since 1986, giving him the most tenure
of any manager or head coach in professional sports, has an admirer
in Chicago skipper Jerry Manuel. Manuel said when he first got his
job three years ago, Kelly greeted him warmly. So Manuel made sure
that when the Twins arrived Friday for the start of a three-game
series, he went to Kelly and congratulated him on getting his
1,000th career victory earlier this season. ''He's been through
good times and bad times and maintained the same demeanor,'' Manuel
said. ... Five of the Twins previous 12 games before Saturday went
to extra innings.
</P>
<P>
   CHICAGO: The slumping White Sox had a team meeting before
Saturday night's game. ''I don't like meetings personally at all,''
Chicago manager Jerry Manuel said. ''I just thought we had some
issues we needed to discuss with a trip coming up.'' The White Sox
embark on a trip to New York and Toronto next week. ... Certainly
one issue the White Sox must continue to address is defense. In its
first 35 games, Chicago had 38 errors. First baseman Paul Konerko
missed a ground ball in the 10th inning Friday night -- it was
scored a hit -- to let the winning run score. ''We have the players
to be better defensively,'' Manuel said. ''We have to understand
that eventually a sign of how good we are is how we catch the ball
in close games.''
Mariners-Athletics:
</P>
<P>
   SEATTLE: Seattle pinch-hitters are 3-for-19 (.158) without an
RBI this season. The Mariners went without a pinch hit between
April 18 and May 10 (0-for-9).
</P>
<P>
   OAKLAND: 2B Frank Menechino was sent down to Triple-A Sacramento
of the Pacific Coast League, but not because of anything h from the disabled
list to start Saturday's game.
Menechino hit .293 with four homers and 16 RBIs with the A's. ...
1B Olmedo Saenz, who left Friday night's game in the second inning,
was diagnosed with a slight sprain in his right ankle, better than
expected. ''I thought he would be out for a couple weeks,'' said
Howe. ''We dodged a bullet.'' Saenz did not play Saturday and is
listed day-to-day.
Rangers is also scheduled to go on a rehab assignment to Tulsa on
Monday, almost a month after arthroscopic surgery for bone spurs in
his right ankle. ... When the Rangers won Friday night 13-11 behind
four homers and the Angels countered with five, it represented a
new club record for a road game; the previous high of eight had
been done three times.
</P>
<P>
   ANAHEIM: C Bengie Molina, who had a two-homer game Friday night,
had hit just one home run in 190 previous big-league at-bats. ...
LHP Jarrod Washburn became the Angels' seventh different starter in
38 games Saturday night.
NATIONAL LEAGUE:
Cubs-Expos:
</P>
<P>
   CHICAGO: RHP Todd Van Poppel became the 14th player to make his
Cubs debut this season when he pitched 2 2-3 innings in relief of
Kerry Wood in Friday night's 8-3 loss to the Expos. ... Newly
acquired OF Dave Martinez is expected to join the team Sunday in
Montreal. Martinez, who was acquired from Tampa Bay Friday for LHP
Mark Guthrie and cash, will wear the No. 1, as he did during his
first stint with the Cubs from 1986-88.
</P>
<P>
   MONTREAL: Relievers Ugueth Urbina and Scott Strickland are both
scheduled to have surgery on their ailing right arms next
Wednesday, though Strickland threw long toss without any pain in
his shoulder prior to Saturday night's game. Strickland will throw
on the side Sunday. He had planned to consult Dr. James Andrews on
Monday for a second opinion to the MRI reading which determined
that he had a torn labrum. The results of the arthrogram performed
on Urbina's right elbow will be reviewed further on Monday. ... 2B
Jose Vidro tied his career-best hitting streak when he singled in
the first Friday to extend his current streak to 10 games. Vidro
also hit in 10 straight last May 25 to June 6.
Braves-Phillies:
</P>
<P>
   ATLANTA: The Braves' 8-7 victory over the Phillies on Friday
night was their first after trailing going into the eighth inning.
They had lost the first nine times they trailed that late in the
game. ... Rudy Seanez surrendered his first grand slam in the
seventh inning of that game when Scott Rolen moved the Phillies
ahead 7-6. Seanez had pitched 194 innings in 188 games without
allowing that feat. ... Prior to Saturday's game the Braves
activated Kevin McGlinchy after his rehab assignment in Greenville
and sent relief pitcher Kerry Ligtenberg to Triple-A Richmond.
</P>
<P>
   PHILADELPHIA: The Phillies have not won a series against the
Braves at home sine April 1998. ... Judy Wolf, mother of Phillies
pitcher Randy, was in attendance for the Braves series, compliments
of the team. The Phillies reinstituted an old tradition of flying
in a player's mother for a series during Mother's Day weekend. Judy
Wolf, whose name was selected at random, came to Philadelphia from
her home in Canoga Park, Calif., where Randy still lives during the
off-season. ...
Brewers-Pirates:
</P>
<P>
   MILWAUKEE: Brewers starting pitchers are averaging just 5 1-3
innings per game. The staff could get a couple of additions soon.
RHPs John Snyder and Jamey Wright are on rehab at Triple-A
Indianapolis and could be back soon. Both went on the disabled list
on March 28 -- Snyder with a left oblique muscle strain and Wright
with a right shoulder injury.
</P>
<P>
   PITTSBURGH: SS Pat Meares left Friday's game in the sixth inning
because of the flu and was unavailable for Saturday's game. ...
Brian O'Connor made his major league debut as Saturday's starter
and was the 16th pitcher used by the Pirates this season. O'Connor
is the first starting pitcher to be called up from Double-A by the
Pirates since Steve Parris in 1995.
Marlins-Mets:
</P>
<P>
   FLORIDA: Closer Antonio Alfonseca has saved all four games
during the Marlins' current winning streak. Florida manager John
Boles said he won't pitch Sunday and that Braden Looper will be
given the day off, too. ... Preston Wilson had four RBIs for the
second straight game, again matching his career high. He has an
eight-game hitting streak and five homers in his last eight games.
''You feel relaxed,'' he said. ''You have a very confident feeling.
Everything is a little bit slower than it usually is.''
</P>
<P>
   NEW YORK: The Mets have homered in five straight games for the
first time this year and have 18 in their last 13 games. ... Mike
Hampton was the first Mets' pitcher to pinch hit since Pat Mahomes,
who struck out at Houston last Aug. 30. Hampton is 4-for-18 (.222)
at the plate this season. ... ... Hampton (3-4) pitches against
Brad Penny (3-4) in Sunday's series finale.
Reds-Astros:
</P>
<P>
   CINCINNATI: The Reds purchased the contract of RHP Osvaldo
Fernandez from Double-A Chattanooga of the Southern League. He took
Pete Harnisch's spot on the roster and started Saturday against the
Astros. Harnisch has been on the disabled list since May 5 due to
weakness in the rotator cuff of his right shoulder. He is
undergoing a strengthening program and is expected to miss 3-4
weeks.
</P>
<P>
   HOUSTON: RHP Shane Reynolds (5-0) had his next start pushed back
one day because of slight stiffness in his shoulder. Reynolds will
pitch Tuesday at Milwaukee and RHP Jose Lima, originally scheduled
to pitch Tuesday, will pitch Monday night against the Reds. ... SS
Tim Bogar returned to the starting lineup for the first time since
May 5. Bogar was benched because of a hitting slump. He is hitting
.132.
Dodgers-Cardinals:
</P>
<P>
   LOS ANGELES: The Dodgers and Cardinals entered Saturday's game
tied with 103 victories apiece at Busch Stadium. ... The Dodgers'
13-0 victory Friday was their widest margin of victory in a shutout
since Sept. 24, 1975, when Doug Rau beat San Diego 14-0. ... The
Dodgers hit 56 homers in their first 34 games. Last year they had
39 over the same span. ... Carlos Perez, who makes his seventh
start on Sunday, is 3-0 in his last six appearances with a 3.89
ERA. ... Catcher Todd Hundley, who did not start Saturday, has
thrown out only two of 20 basestealers.
</P>
<P>
   ST. LOUIS: Trainer Barry Weinberg said third baseman Fernando
Tatis has made no progress with a groin injury that landed him on
the disabled list April 30. Weinberg said Tatis, who was leading
the NL with 28 RBIs when he was hurt, won't be back until the
All-Star break at the earliest. ''It's like Uncle Joe. He's kind of
slow at the Junction,'' Weinberg said. ... LF Ray Lankford was back
in the lineup, a day after leaving due to blurred vision after
one-half of an inning. Lankford's eyes were dilated during an
examination Thursday. ... The Cardinals are being patient with
reliever Darren Holmes, who allowed seven earned runs in 4 1-3
innings his first three appearances. Pitching coach Dave Duncan
pointed out that Holmes hadn't pitched in 22 days before his first
outing with St. Louis. ''You kind of have to give him the benefit
of the doubt,'' Duncan said. ''To give him a fair evaluation, we
have to let him pitch some more.''
Giants-Rockies:
</P>
<P>
   SAN FRANCISCO: OF Ellis Burks was placed on the 15-day disabled
list retroactive to May 9 with a strained left quadriceps. To
replace him, Terrell Lowery's contract was purchased from Triple-A
Fresno. ... 3B Bill Mueller extended his hitting streak to 10
games. ... Armando Rios' last five homers have come at Coors Field.
He hit two on Oct. 2, two more Friday night and one Saturday.
''Here, I feel like I'm 6-2,'' the 5-foot-9 outfielder said. ...
Barry Bonds became the sixth player to reach the third deck at
Coors Field with his 457-foot homer in the seventh. He left the
game with a back injury in the ninth.
</P>
<P>
   COLORADO: The Rockies placed OF Larry Walker on the 15-day
disabled list. He is expected to miss at least a month with a
stress fracture in his right elbow. Colorado purchased Bubba
Carpenter's contract from Triple-A Colorado Springs and moved RHP
Jerry Dipoto to the 60-day disabled list. Carpenter, a career minor
leaguer, had a pinch-single in his major league debut. ''You work
for nine years for that. It just feels good to get it over with,''
he said. ... Todd Helton fouled off nine pitches with two strikes
before hitting his 13th homer of the season in the sixth. ... With
10 runs Saturday, the Rockies scored in double figures for the
sixth straight home game. They have scored 79 runs in that stretch
(13.2 per game).
Diamondbacks-Padres:
</P>
<P>
   ARIZONA: Injured 3B Matt Williams received a pair of
specially-designed baseball shoes from Padres RF Tony Gwynn.
Williams, on the disabled list since March 29 with a fractured
second metatarsal, got the shoes before Friday's series opener
after telling Gwynn that his heel was bothering him. Gwynn, on the
disabled list with inflammation in his left knee, has worn shoes
with more padding than normal baseball shoes the past several
seasons. ... Ed Sprague's three-run homer allowed by LHP Greg
Swindell on Friday night was one of the bullpen's rare ineffective
outings in the last 10 games. Before Sprague's homer, the
Diamondbacks relievers had given up only two earned runs over 25
innings (0.72 ERA) with 29 strikeouts.
</P>
<P>
   SAN DIEGO: RHP Rodney Myers underwent successful surgery
Saturday to repair the torn patellar tendon in his left knee that
he suffered Thursday on the artificial turf in Cincinnati. Myers,
placed on the 60-day disabled list Friday, is expected to be out
for the season. ... CF Ruben Rivera may be running out of time to
prove he can hit major league pitching. Rivera, the key part of the
Hideki Irabu trade with the Yankees in 1997, has been a bust
offensively. Rivera, one of the NL's top defensive center fielders,
is hitting just .195 since becoming a regular in 1999. ''This is a
big year for Ruben,'' GM Kevin Towers said.
</P>
</TEXT>
