<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-05-13 23:42 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Female Officer Urges Timely Reports  </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK (AP) -- In her first public comments since accusing a
superior of sexual harassment, the Army's highest-ranking female
officer said women in the military who face harassment should
report it immediately.
</P>
<P>
   ''If discrimination or misconduct is not reported at an
appropriate time, then public policy may never change,'' Lt. Gen.
Claudia J. Kennedy said Friday at a ceremony honoring her 31 years
of military service.
</P>
<P>
   Kennedy did not make any direct reference to her case in remarks
before more than 100 people at the memorial to Women in Military
Service to America, which adjoins Arlington National Cemetery.
</P>
<P>
   Kennedy has accused Maj. Gen. Larry G. Smith of making unwanted
sexual advances in 1996. She did not report the alleged incident to
her superiors at the time, raising her allegations only last fall,
when the Army appointed Smith to be deputy inspector general. In
that post he would have investigated cases of sexual harassment.
</P>
<P>
   Her charge has been substantiated by Army investigators, senior
defense officials said last week. That finding will be reviewed by
the Army's vice chief of staff, Gen. John Keane, who will determine
whether to take disciplinary action against Smith.
</P>
<P>
   In her remarks Friday, Kennedy quoted French novelist Emile Zola
that he lived on earth ''to live out loud.''
</P>
<P>
   ''Living out loud begins by telling a friend and then later
telling people in authority who care,'' The New York Times quoted
her as saying. ''Our army is filled with women and men who care and
are in a position to change and improve the conditions in which we
serve.''
</P>
<P>
   Kennedy, the Army's deputy chief of staff for intelligence, is
due to retire in June.
</P>
</TEXT>
